<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals, Rockies Split Day  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Jeff Manto hit a go-ahead double during an
eight-run sixth inning that propelled the Colorado Rockies to a
14-13 victory over the St. Louis Cardinals in the second game of a
split doubleheader Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, who lost the afternoon opener 9-3, came back from
deficits of 3-0, 7-3 and 9-5 by sending 14 men to the plate against
four St. Louis pitchers in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The outburst came three days after Colorado scored 10 runs in
the second inning against former Rockies pitcher Darryl Kile. The
team record for runs in an inning is 11 against Seattle in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew had a three-run double and Pat Hentgen kept his record
with St. Louis perfect as the Cardinals won Game 1. St. Louis had
to settle for a split despite hitting four homers on the day.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth inning of Game 2 lasted an hour as the Cardinals took
a 9-5 lead on a run-scoring groundout by Fernando Tatis and an RBI
single by Eric Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cirillo started the Colorado comeback with a two-run double
off ex-Rockies reliever David Wainhouse. Mike Mohler (0-1)
relieved, two batters later, but promptly walked Larry Walker to
load the bases. Todd Helton tied it at 9 with a two-run single to
right.
</P>
<P>
   Manto, 4-for-5 this season, followed with a pinch double that
gave the Rockies their first lead of the day. After a fly out and
the fifth walk of the inning, Scott Servais hit a sinking line
drive that scored two more and chased Mohler. Brian Hunter added an
RBI infield single off Mike James to cap the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Jimenez (3-0), who threw a no-hitter for the Cardinals last
year, retired both hitters he faced in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals scored four times in the ninth, but fell just
short. Edgar Renteria had an RBI double, Jim Edmonds drove in
Fernando Vina with a sacrifice fly and Mike Matheny drew a
bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   But Gabe White, who entered with the bases loaded and Colorado
leading 14-10, ended the game by getting Placido Polanco to line
out to Larry Walker in right field. White retired two batters for
his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's comeback spoiled a big day by Vina, the St. Louis
leadoff man. Although he is the only Cardinals position player
without a homer, Vina went 6-for-9 -- including 5-for-5 in the
second game -- and scored six runs. The five hits matched a career
high.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Hentgen (3-0) gave up three runs and seven hits
in 5 2-3 innings. The St. Louis offense gave him plenty of room for
error in his first Coors Field appearance by roughing up Rolando
Arrojo (1-1), who surrendered a career-high eight earned runs in
four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Polanco and Thomas Howard each homered off Arrojo in the first.
Drew put the Cardinals ahead 7-1 when he capped a five-run third
with a two-out, bases-loaded double into the right-center field
gap.
</P>
<P>
   Drew, who had mixed results in his rookie year, is 8-for-16 with
four homers and 12 RBIs in the season's first two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was hit in the left wrist in the fifth inning of the opener
and did not play in the nightcap. Drew planned to have X-rays taken
Monday but did not expect the injury to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds and Eli Marrero each homered in the second game as the
Cardinals showed no signs of a power shortage without ailing Mark
McGwire. St. Louis has homered in nine straight games -- five
without the single-season home run king.
</P>
<P>
Notes: McGwire will be re-evaluated Monday after receiving
treatment over the weekend for inflammation in his lower back. ...
Colorado traded for Arrojo during the winter, in part because of
his control. He walked three hitters Sunday, and they all scored.
Arrojo also hit a batter with the bases loaded. ... Edmonds went
1-for-12 after a string of nine straight hits. ... St. Louis
scrapped plans to recall RHP Gene Stechschulte for Sunday's
doubleheader. Instead, Alan Benes remained on the active roster.
... The Rockies missed a chance for their first four-game home
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0033 </TRAILER>
