<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Drama Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Marines in the courtroom won a narrow victory
over a party girl in rehab at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rules of Engagement,'' a military court drama, remained the
top movie for the second straight weekend, taking in $10.9 million,
according to studio estimates Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Final figures were to be released today.
</P>
<P>
   Debuting in second place with $10.4 million was ''28 Days,''
starring Sandra Bullock as an alcoholic ordered into a clinic after
crashing a limousine at her sister's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Another new film, ''Keeping the Faith,'' was third with $8.2
million. The Edward Norton-Ben Stiller comedy focuses on a rabbi
and priest whose lifelong friendship is jeopardized when they fall
for the same woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Erin Brockovich,'' the No. 1 movie for three straight weekends
before last week, was in fourth place with $7 million and has
grossed $99.3 million. It should pass $100 million by Tuesday, the
first movie released this year to cross that mark.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's most-talked-about debut, the adaptation of Bret
Easton Ellis' ultra-violent novel ''American Psycho,'' opened at
No. 7 with $4.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''American Psycho'' posted a respectable per-theater average of
$3,964, playing at 1,236 cinemas. Among the top 10 movies, that was
second only to ''28 Days,'' which averaged $4,122 at 2,523
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Newman's latest, ''Where the Money Is,'' had a weak opening
of $2.7 million, coming in at No. 11 and averaging $1,778 in 1,538
theaters. Newman plays an imprisoned bank robber who feigns a
stroke to get sent to a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rules of Engagement'' stars Tommy Lee Jones as a Marine
attorney defending an old friend (Samuel L. Jackson) in a
court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess the guys still rule,'' said Ed Russell, executive vice
president for publicity at Sony, which distributed ''28 Days.''
''We were a predominantly female audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's tough sell was ''American Psycho,'' about a yuppie
serial killer who preys mainly on women. Ellis' 1991 novel drew
outrage from women's groups and others who criticized it as
pornographically violent.
</P>
<P>
   While ''American Psycho'' is bloody, director Mary Harron kept
most of the actual violence off-camera and turned the story into a
satire of 1980s materialism.
</P>
<P>
   Distributor Lions Gate worked to ''prepare people for the fact
that it was far less violent than the novel and much more sharply
satiric,'' said Mark Urman, co-president of Lions Gate. ''We really
wanted to make it clear that people won't see anything that would
turn the stomach or in anyway promote violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Lions Gate, which successfully marketed the religious satire
''Dogma'' last year, tried creative ways to pitch ''American
Psycho,'' including a plan to share a small percentage of revenue
with Internet users if the movie grosses more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not your mainstream film,'' said Paul Dergarabedian,
president of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks movie ticket sales.
''For them to even be in the top 10 says they did something
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc.
</P>
<P>
   1. ''Rules of Engagement,'' $10.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''28 Days,'' $10.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Keeping the Faith,'' $8.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''Erin Brockovich,'' $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''The Road to El Dorado,'' $6.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''Return to Me,'' $5.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   7. ''American Psycho,'' $4.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   8. ''The Skulls,'' $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   9. ''Final Destination,'' $2.83 million.
</P>
<P>
   10. ''High Fidelity,'' $2.8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
