<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A New York business landmark goes residential  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Looking for a primo Manhattan pad to go with
your high-flying Internet startup?
</P>
<P>
   Stuffy Park Avenue and pretentious SoHo just don't fit the bill?
</P>
<P>
   How about a luxury apartment at the top of the Woolworth
Building, the wondrously overwrought, 60-story neo-Gothic landmark
once dubbed the Cathedral of Commerce?
</P>
<P>
   One of the Old Economy's most famous addresses is converting its
top 30 floors to residential space and hoping (stock market tumbles
notwithstanding) to attract the New Economy's highest rollers as
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be tremendous ego gratification to saying that you
live on top of the Woolworth Building,'' said Pam Liebman, CEO of
the upmarket real estate firm the Corcoran Group, who recently
toured the building. ''There's nothing else in the city like it,
... because of the name, the history, the location, the beauty of
the building. It's pretty spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woolworth Building, erected by five-and-dime store magnate
Frank W. Woolworth in 1913, boasts a white marble lobby with
Tiffany stained-glass panels and colored-glass mosaics embedded in
its vaulted ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the city's signature skyscrapers, with an ornately
detailed terra cotta exterior designed by architect Cass Gilbert.
Across the street from City Hall and blocks from the financial
district, it served for 85 years as headquarters of Woolworth's
national chain and was the world's tallest building until 1929,
when the Chrysler Building surpassed it.
</P>
<P>
   Converting the building's upper tower to apartments ''is going
to create within an old structure a new vitality,'' said architect
Costas Kondylis, who is designing the residential space.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a serious building,'' he said. ''It's not just trendy,
fashionable architecture which two years from now might be
completely disregarded.''
</P>
<P>
   As few as one or two high-ceilinged luxury apartments may occupy
each floor of the building, whose length runs a full block.
</P>
<P>
   Crowning the redesign will be a three-story penthouse in the
building's spire. The lucky -- read extremely wealthy -- occupants
will have access via a private glass elevator to Frank Woolworth's
own wraparound terrace and its breathtaking views.
</P>
<P>
   The vistas from lower down aren't bad either. The Brooklyn
Bridge, New York Harbor, the World Trade Center, midtown Manhattan
and the Hudson River are all visible from the tower.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sort of a 'Wow' factor when you walk in there,'' Liebman
said. ''It's like being in a helicopter.''
</P>
<P>
   An ocean of amenities are planned for those ready to pay prices
that have not been announced but will certainly be eye-popping. The
New York Observer guessed residents may have to ante up $6 million,
and as much as $12 million for the penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   A wine cellar, media room, cigar lounge, business center and a
private dining room were all being considered for a basement
concourse, Kondylis said. Woolworth's private pool will become part
of a health club.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul comes about two years after the Witkoff Group,
headed by developer Steven Witkoff, bought the building from the
Venator Group, formerly known as the Woolworth Corp., for a
reported $122 million.
</P>
<P>
   The office space vacated when Venator moved out has been
outfitted with Internet connections and filled with new companies,
many of them high-tech ventures, said Brad Gerla, managing director
of Insignia-ESG, which handles commercial leasing for the building.
</P>
<P>
   But some longtime occupants are unhappy with Witkoff's
management style -- he's raised rents and pushed out many
upper-floor business tenants to make way for the superrich. Even
the venerable Harry's restaurant on the ground floor had to go.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sad thing is, they're not interested in people,''
complained Tom Oliva, whose small barber shop has been a fixture in
the building for 33 years but recently lost its lease. ''They're
just interested in money. The human factor is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Woolworth Building is to join a slew of other Lower
Manhattan office and factory spaces that have gone residential
recently, adding a new dimension to a part of town that was once
deserted after dark.
</P>
<P>
   Liebman said the apartments were likely to attract Wall
Streeters eager to walk to work, dot-com entrepreneurs and
out-of-towners looking for a New York pied-a-terre.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has broad-based appeal,'' she said. ''The one thing they'll
have to have in common is they'll have to have money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 0111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Begins Visit to Britain  </HEADLINE>
By MARA D. BELLABY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin begins his first
official visit to the West eager to forge closer ties with Europe
while presenting his credentials as a reformist leader who can
bring stability to the world's largest nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the newly elected leader faces protests and criticism over
Chechnya and allegations that Russian troops have used excessive
force and executed civilians in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who arrived Sunday night with his wife, Lyudmila, was
scheduled to hold a roundtable meeting today with foreign investors
in a bid to lure their badly needed capital back to his country.
The seminar was to be followed by a working lunch with Prime
Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prime minister sees the election of a new generation to
power in Moscow as a potential turning point in relations with
Russia,'' said Blair's spokesman, Alastair Campbell. ''He will use
the visit as an important opportunity for Britain to build a new
strategic relationship with the new Russian leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a longtime KGB agent who never held elected office until
last month's presidential vote, has made it clear that Russia's
future lies with Europe, and he seems to have singled out Britain --
with its unique role as a bridge between the United States and the
European Union -- as a key partner to cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's first meeting with a Western leader was with Blair, who
accepted the Russian's invitation in March to visit St. Petersburg.
Blair, who at 46 is one year younger than Putin, left impressed
with the new Russian leader's energy and ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also said he was pleased with Blair's willingness to work
with Moscow, which he cited as the reason for choosing London for
his first Western trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''We strongly hope that this will not be simply a visit of
courtesy, but it will help advance the solution of a number of key
problems of cooperation,'' Putin told reporters in the Kremlin
before leaving, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   But while topics such as fighting drugs, international crime and
terrorism and how the two nuclear powers can cooperate were to be
high on the agenda during the 24-hour visit, Blair promised not to
shy away from criticism of Putin's military assault on Chechen
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union submitted a resolution to the United Nations'
top human rights body last week condemning alleged human rights
abuses and urging Russia to take a more restrained approach. The
Council of Europe has lifted Russia's voting rights and asked for a
full suspension unless peace talks begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's up to Prime Minister Tony Blair to keep up the
pressure,'' said Holly Cartner of the New York-based Human Rights
Watch. ''Blair has to make clear that Britain will take the lead in
bringing Russia to account.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader's international credentials, however, were
boosted Friday when the Duma ratified the START II treaty. Putin's
predecessor, Boris Yeltsin, had repeatedly failed to win approval
for the nuclear arms reduction agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Putin ends his London visit at Windsor Castle, where he has a
private audience with the queen, a distant relative of Russia's
last monarch, Czar Nicholas II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0117 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quotes From Mets' Valentine Printed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Ignoring New York Mets manager Bobby
Valentine's e-mail request, the University of Pennsylvania
newspaper published portions of an audio tape of his speech to a
group of business students.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Pennsylvanian is the first to quote Valentine
directly. About 30 minutes of his speech was taped, and portions of
the transcript were provided to The Associated Press on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Valentine sent an e-mail to the newspaper's
reporter asking her to call him. She returned the call and
Valentine requested that the tape not be released to the public.
The reporter told him that her editor would make the decision about
the tape.
</P>
<P>
   There was no further contact.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, speaking Wednesday to students at Penn's Wharton
School of Business, addressed the team's failure to sign Japanese
reliever Kazuhiro Sasaki and criticized former Mets player Bobby
Bonilla and outfielder Rickey Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a proponent during the offseason to say, 'Let's boost
our bullpen,''' Valentine said of Sasaki. ''I thought that if we
can sign this kid Sasaki, who's a free agent, it would have cost us
no talent, just a little money, and we would have one heck of a
baseball team right now. But the group who makes the decisions
decides that wasn't a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki signed with the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bonilla, Valentine said, ''He found his stroke and lost
45 pounds. That makes a big difference. ... There seems to be
commitment this year, interestingly enough, because he's without a
contract this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla is batting .273 while playing regularly for the Atlanta
Braves this season.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were posted on the Mets' Web site by a Penn student
late Wednesday or early Thursday. Valentine said his comments were
misrepresented. Several newspapers reported conflicting versions of
his comments.
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips flew from New York to
Pittsburgh on Friday to talk to Valentine. Phillips said he was
satisfied with Valentine's explanation.
</P>
<P>
   In comments about Henderson, Valentine related a story in which
Henderson asked for the sports section of The Wall Street Journal,
which does not have a sports section.
</P>
<P>
   ''Worldly, he's worldly,'' he said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   He also joked about dealing with Henderson, who is often
disgruntled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just ignore him as much as I can,'' he laughed. ''Seriously,
the personality of Rickey ... it's the same personality that we all
have, probably that he's always had.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also endorsed building one stadium for the Mets and
the World Champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's any way the city of New York and the
public is going to co-venture two buildings in excess of a billion
dollars each for these rich kids that run around with baseballs and
rich owners that make a lot of money,'' Valentine said.
</P>
</TEXT>
