<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Student newspaper releases quotes from Valentine's speech  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- New York Mets manager Bobby Valentine
prefaced his remarks to a crowd of about 100 business students by
asking for a guarantee that they wouldn't ''be seen on 20/20.''
Then he proceeded to criticize the front-office as well as current
and former players.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Pennsylvania newspaper ignored Valentine's
plea to a reporter shortly after the speech and today published
portions of an audio tape of his comments.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Pennsylvanian is the first to quote Valentine
directly. About 30 minutes of his speech was taped, and portions of
the transcript were provided to The Associated Press on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Valentine sent an e-mail to the newspaper's
reporter, Laura Spadanuta. She called him back on Friday, and he
asked her not to release an audio tape of the comments. Spadanuta,
a student, said her editor would have the final decision. There was
no further contact.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, speaking Wednesday to students at Penn's Wharton
School of Business, addressed the team's failure to sign Japanese
reliever Kazuhiro Sasaki and criticized former Mets player Bobby
Bonilla and outfielder Rickey Henderson. He also questioned the
league's handling of Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a proponent during the offseason to say, 'Let's boost
our bullpen,''' Valentine said of Sasaki. ''I thought that if we
can sign this kid Sasaki, who's a free agent, it would have cost us
no talent, just a little money, and we would have one heck of a
baseball team right now. But the group who makes the decisions
decides that wasn't a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki signed with the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bonilla, Valentine said, ''He found his stroke and lost
45 pounds. That makes a big difference. ... There seems to be
commitment this year, interestingly enough, because he's without a
contract this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla is batting .273 while playing regularly for the Atlanta
Braves this season.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were posted on the Mets' Web site by a Penn student
late Wednesday or early Thursday. Valentine said his comments were
misrepresented. Several newspapers reported conflicting versions of
his comments.
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips flew from New York to
Pittsburgh on Friday to talk to Valentine. Phillips said he was
satisfied with Valentine's explanation.
</P>
<P>
   In comments about Henderson, Valentine related a story in which
Henderson asked for the sports section of The Wall Street Journal,
which does not have a sports section.
</P>
<P>
   ''Worldly, he's worldly,'' he said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   He also joked about dealing with Henderson, who is often
disgruntled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just ignore him as much as I can,'' he laughed. ''Seriously,
the personality of Rickey ... it's the same personality that we all
have, probably that he's always had.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was originally suspended for one month for racist
comments he made about New York fans in a magazine interview. His
suspension was later reduced to two weeks. Valentine said he was
''disappointed in the way the league handled'' the matter and ''in
the way the players association got involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I personally am totally in favor of free speech in our
country, whether you're in a baseball uniform or whether you're in
a postman's uniform,'' he said. ''I thought John Rocker's situation
should have been handled by his team and his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine called Rocker's remarks ''appalling,'' but said he
doesn't think ''there's any disciplinary act from the supreme ruler
of our game that should have been handed down. I don't particularly
like the thought that ... something I say here might be held
against me by the commissioner of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The university's television station said it taped Valentine's
speech, but it was unclear if the station still has it. The
newspaper reported Valentine contacted the group that organized the
event -- Wharton Wide World of Sports -- and asked that all copies be
given to him.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Valentine also endorsed building one stadium
for the Mets and the World Champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's any way the city of New York and the
public is going to co-venture two buildings in excess of a billion
dollars each for these rich kids that run around with baseballs and
rich owners that make a lot of money,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
