<BODY>
<HEADLINE> '60s Protester Compares Eras  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A veteran of the civil rights movement watched
this weekend's protests against the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund with a measure of contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a demonstration,'' said Vladimr Budney, who was a
one-man counter-demonstration Sunday. ''This is a rock concert held
at the expense of the local population.''
</P>
<P>
   Budney, who had a long, white beard and gave his age as ''over
50,'' carried a sign that said ''Stop A16 Anarchy,'' which someone
tried to burn. A16 is the name of the umbrella effort to close down
Sunday's IMF meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm asking them to go back to Berkeley and Seattle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lecturing a protester outside a police barricade near George
Washington University, Budney said, ''A political demonstration is
when you get a bunch of people together, and you influence a member
of Congress, and you get a bill introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's liberalism!'' objected the protester, Richard Degen,
36.
</P>
<P>
   Budney, who protested against Spanish fascism and for civil
rights in the '60s, said he agrees with the goals of the
protesters. But he said their tactics are dated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The revolution is over,'' he said. ''(Former Soviet leader)
Mikhail Gorbachev abandoned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Budney said he joined the A16 effort in January but was booted
out two months later for calling for negotiations with the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   He called the effort a rock concert because ''it has a bunch of
kids like this walking around, having fun with each other,
shouting, screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Frost, a 26-year-old medical student at Case Western
University, disagreed, saying many people felt deeply about the
issues. ''Oh, give us a little more credit,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
