<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Blasts Bush's Leadership  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM C. MANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Pat Buchanan quit the Republican Party,
he complained that the GOP had become as bad as the Democrats in
refusing to fight for the American culture. He now says the party
under George W. Bush has given in to cultural demise.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to rule out abortion advocates as potential running
mates, and by meeting with Republican homosexuals, the Texas
governor and presumed GOP presidential nominee is telling the party
not to stand on the principle that family is all-important,
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's raising the white flag and stacking arms (surrendering)
in the cultural war for the soul of this country,'' Buchanan said
on ''Fox News Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan bolted the party in October after a series of opinion
polls had him trailing badly for the 2000 GOP presidential
nomination. He told supporters then that, like the Democrats, the
Republicans had stopped fighting ''with conviction and courage to
rescue God's country from the cultural and moral pit into which she
has fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the leading contender for the Reform Party nomination,
Buchanan said Bush's apparent list of possible running mates gives
Republicans reason for dismay because it includes Govs. Tom Ridge
of Pennsylvania and Christie Whitman of New Jersey. Neither
supports banning abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ''What he's saying basically is, 'I'm pro-life,' and Governor
Ridge is pro-choice, and Christie Todd Whitman is pro-partial-birth
abortion, but that's really not a matter that really should divide
us as a party,''' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   On Bush's meeting last week with a dozen gay Republicans,
Buchanan said: ''He's sending a signal that this really is not a
matter that we ought to let trouble us. But you know, what he's
doing is he's walking away from the pro-family Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Look, Republicans believe -- or used to believe -- the idea of
preserving the family is critical, and any assault upon the family
was really one of the reasons why this country is in such profound
trouble,'' he said. ''Mr. Bush is saying that this point of view
(homosexuality) is thoroughly acceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
