<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA To Recommend Boeing 737 Changes  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Changes in the design of the rudder of the
Boeing 737, the most widely used passenger jet in the world, are
being recommended by a special engineering panel convened by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-member Federal Aviation Administration board is also
preparing recommendations calling for improved crew training in
dealing with rudder problems and increased rudder inspections, top
FAA officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But while the changes are included in preliminary
recommendations scheduled to be made final in June, FAA assistant
administrator Thomas McSweeny stressed that the board considers the
chance of problems with the 737 rudder so small that it is not
calling for any immediate corrective action.
</P>
<P>
   The 737 rudder system, which controls left-right movement of the
plane, came under close suspicion after the crash of USAir flight
427 near Pittsburgh, Pa., in 1994 that killed all 132 people
aboard. A similar disaster had occurred in 1991, when United flight
585 crashed in Colorado Springs, Colo., killing 25.
</P>
<P>
   After those accidents, the FAA issued airworthiness directives
requiring changes in the rudder controls of 737s, and those changes
have been made, said Elizabeth Erickson, the FAA's director of
aircraft certification.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the FAA formed the panel of aviation experts who
were not involved previously with the 737 design and asked them to
study the rudder design and report on possible ways it could fail,
Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   The important finding is that ''we have not found any safety
issues requiring immediate action,'' said McSweeny, who is in
charge of aircraft regulation and certification.
</P>
<P>
   He said the group did uncover ways that a jam in control
linkages could cause the rudder to jam to one side in a
''hardover'' -- a sudden jerk of the rudder that can steal control
from the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   And they found that spraying water onto the controls inside the
tail in extreme cold could cause ice to form and cause problems, he
said. But, McSweeny said, it is not clear if that could happen in
flight conditions, so more tests are being done.
</P>
<P>
   He said the committee recommendations will be final in June, and
engineers then will consider how to correct problem areas they
found. In the meantime, he said, Boeing is also looking into
possible rudder design changes.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's preliminary recommendations, he said, are:
</P>
<P>
   --''In the long term, they do believe that the failures that can
result in hardovers need to be addressed by design changes.''
</P>
<P>
   --''In the short term, they believe operations and maintenance
procedures should be enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the second recommendation means changing inspections to
detect latent rudder problems and finding ways for air crews to
respond to rudder problems better if they occur.
</P>
<P>
   He would not speculate on what changes might be made in crew
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson stressed that the 737 ''maintains an excellent safety
record. It has half the accident rate of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more than 3,600 737s in service takes off every five
to seven seconds somewhere in the world, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials added that they are cooperating with the FAA
and have supplied a plane for testing.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board Chairman Jim Hall issued a
statement Sunday saying he was pleased that the engineering board,
which was formed last year in response to safety board
recommendations following its investigation of the crash of USAir
flight 427, is nearing completion of its assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The safety board has been monitoring the progress of the
board,'' Hall said. ''We look forward to publication of its full
report.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0206 </TRAILER>
