<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Sides With Striking Janitors  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Al Gore, looking to protect his lead in
vote-rich California, spent just two hours campaigning here, but
his appearances were surgically tailored to bolster support from
key voter blocs, including Hispanics, Roman Catholics and labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   After spending most of Sunday in his hotel room, the vice
president ventured out at about 1:30 p.m., declaring his solidarity
with striking janitors at a rally, then meeting with the
influential Cardinal Roger Mahony. By 3:30 p.m. he was flying home
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The events marked the end of a weekend California swing that was
low-key but often high-profile. Gore made two quick appearances in
Los Angeles Saturday morning, then went into private meetings for
more than five hours.
</P>
<P>
   That evening he re-emerged for the political event of the
season, a fund-raiser in Beverly Hills with President Clinton and a
small army of Hollywood stars that raised $2.8 million for
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he landed in San Jose on Friday until the time he
left Los Angeles, Gore helped raise more than $5 million for his
campaign and for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, however, the focus was on the working class.
</P>
<P>
   ''The position of president is the only one filled by someone
who has the responsibility to fight for all of the people, not just
the wealthy and the powerful, the connected, the influential, but
all of the people, including the janitors!'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your cause is just, and you are gaining the ears and hearts of
the people in the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive Democratic presidential nominee spoke in English
and in Spanish from atop a flatbed truck at a rally of more than
1,000 people, nearly all of them Hispanics, and received a
boisterous show of support.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd thundered a warm greeting in Spanish as Gore took the
makeshift stage.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,500 janitors have been striking across the Los Angeles
area since April 3. They generally earn between $6.80 and $7.90,
and are seeking wage increases of $1 a year for each of the next
three years. Contractors have offered more modest raises, and talks
broke down again on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the striking janitors are Hispanic -- a group that makes
up 15 percent of the electorate in California, and one that
presumptive Republican nominee George W. Bush is aggressively
pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest California Field Poll on the presidential race,
Gore led Bush, 51 percent to 41 percent in late February. The
Republicans say it is now a bit closer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a Southern Baptist, chose Palm Sunday for his first
meeting with Mahony, the archbishop of the Los Angeles Diocese.
Mahony has spoken out in support of the striking janitors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, his wife, Tipper, and high-ranking Gore campaign officials
discussed a variety of topics with Mahony, lingering on the issue
of schools, said campaign chairman Tony Coelho. The meeting was
closed to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Californians, and an overwhelming number of
Hispanics, are Roman Catholic. And Gore is counting on labor
support for donations and to get out the vote on Election Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0206 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
