<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Examine Suharto  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Four cars and an ambulance pulled up
outside the home of former dictator Suharto in yet another effort
to pursue a landmark investigation into high-level corruption
during his 32-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors waited patiently in the heavily guarded street
while government-appointed physicians examined the ailing and
reclusive 78-year-old inside.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers want to question Suharto over allegations that he
siphoned off billions of dollars for himself, his family and
cronies while head of the world's fourth most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the medical team emerged to say no: The old man's blood
pressure was too high for interrogation. Come back another day.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto has denied any wrongdoing but for months has kept
prosecutors at bay by refusing to give evidence. With the stalling
tactics of his highly paid lawyers beginning to wear thin, however,
claims of failing health appear to be his last line of defense.
</P>
<P>
   He has suffered two strokes in recent years and claims to be too
sick to face interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia's new reformist government is under pressure from
international lenders and investors to clean up the endemic
corruption that was the hallmark of Suharto's rule and a trigger of
the nation's deepest economic crisis in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Students and activists, whose bloody protests pushed Suharto out
of office two years ago, also demand that he be prosecuted as the
first step toward real democratic change.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Marzuki Darusman, a human rights campaigner who
struggled under Suharto's authoritarian rule, slapped a travel ban
on the old leader Wednesday amid rumors he was about to skip the
country.
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid, a moderate Muslim cleric elected
last June, has threatened to put Suharto under house arrest if he
doesn't answer prosecutors' questions soon. That's a tactic Suharto
used himself on another former president, Sukarno, the founding
father of independent Indonesia who died in isolation in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the government's tough talk, many Indonesians think it
unlikely Suharto will have a day in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to imagine that Suharto will ever be put on trial,''
said Benny Subianto, a political analyst. ''I think he is really
sick, and if he doesn't get healthier then he won't be
questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past two weeks, doctors have twice prevented
prosecutors from quizzing Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Juan Felix Tampubolon suggested last Monday that
his client's condition was likely to deteriorate. He has lost the
ability to speak properly and regularly wears an oxygen mask, the
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is getting worse every day,'' Tampubolon said.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's six super-rich children, some of whom are also being
investigated for graft, scoff at skeptics who question whether
their father is feigning ill health to evade justice.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has pledged not to let Suharto off the
hook. ''We will call him again and again until he is stated to be
fit to face questioning,'' Darusman said.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the screws a little tighter, officials at Darusman's
office said they plan to interrogate Suharto's eldest daughter and
his second son on Tuesday about their father's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Chairul Imam, who heads the investigation into the corruption
scandal, said today that prosecutors may freeze Suharto's bank
accounts and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have so far had limited success in nailing down
Suharto-era corruption. They forced but lost a graft case against
Suharto's youngest son, Tommy, late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last month they arrested a former Cabinet minister and one of
Suharto's closest friends, Mohammad ''Bob'' Hasan, over an alleged
scam in Indonesia's lucrative lumber industry. He made a fortune
cutting down swaths of rare rain forest and jungle over many years.
</P>
<P>
   Hasan's arrest has been the hardest blow dealt to the old
regime, but it does not pose any direct threat to Suharto himself.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-president spends most of his time at his home in central
Jakarta, but occasionally is seen in public.
</P>
<P>
   Last month he attended his granddaughter's wedding, where he
looked relatively fit and chatted with guests, an appearance that
fueled suspicions he is healthy enough to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if he does go before a court, it might be only a
symbolic gesture.
</P>
<P>
   While Wahid has ordered that Suharto's prosecution go ahead, the
president has also promised to pardon him as long as he returns any
ill-gotten gains. This has enraged student activists, who accuse
Suharto of decades of human rights abuses and who have resumed a
campaign of noisy and sometimes violent protests a few blocks from
Suharto's home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe President Backs Takeovers  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Fearing for their safety, about 80 white
farmers and their families were refusing to return to their fields
today after black squatters killed a white farmer over the weekend
and badly beat five others.
</P>
<P>
   With violence occurring throughout the Macheke district, 75
miles east of Harare, farmers said Sunday they would stay out of
the area until police and military officials could guarantee
security.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violence, President Robert Mugabe, returning from an
economic summit in Cuba, reaffirmed his support Sunday for the
forced occupations of more than 900 white-owned farms, reputedly
led by veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war that ended 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe says the occupations were a justified protest against the
unequal distribution of land in a country where 4,000 white farmers
own one-third of the productive farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We warned the white farmers: We cannot protect you if you
provoke the war veterans. You must accept the consequences,''
Mugabe said. ''There is an expectation I will say to the war
veterans they must get off the land. I will not do that until we
start redistributing the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's comments contradicted his government's appeal Thursday
for the squatters to abandon the plots peacefully. The appeal
followed a High Court ruling that police must evict the squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they lack the resources and manpower to carry out the
High Court's order and have appealed the ruling to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say Mugabe has orchestrated the takeovers as a ploy to
gain support in national elections, expected to be held in May.
</P>
<P>
   Two officials of the main opposition party, the Movement for
Democratic Change, were killed in a firebomb attack Saturday in
Buhera, 150 miles south of Harare, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents hurled a blazing bottle of gasoline into a car being
driven by Tichaona Chimenya, party leader Morgan Tsvangirai's
official driver, said Nomore Sibanda, Tsvangirai's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The attack killed Chimenya and the car's other occupant, whose
name was not released.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe said Tsvangirai, who is visiting Britain to raise money
and support for his party, ''is running around like a real
traitor.'' The president told his supporters to defend themselves
against violence he said was perpetrated by the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't kill, but hit back wildly,'' Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
   The farm violence Saturday marked a sharp escalation in a crisis
that has convulsed this former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Armed squatters in Macheke abducted David Stevens from his farm.
Five other white farmers who came to his aid were shot at and took
refuge in the police station in Murewa, a nearby provincial center.
</P>
<P>
   But the squatters walked into the station and abducted the
farmers as the police watched, according to three of the kidnapped
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters shot and killed Stevens and beat the other farmers
throughout the night with iron bars, rocks and fan belts, before
releasing them, the injured farmers said from a hospital in
Marondera, 40 miles east of Harare.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was the first farmer killed since the farm takeovers
began in February.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer John Osborne said the attackers never mentioned the farms
during the beatings, but instead harangued the men for not
supporting Mugabe's ruling party, which faces a strong opposition
challenge in a parliamentary election. In the past, some squatters
have admitted being paid by ruling party activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not about land. It's about politics,'' Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain told Zimbabwe's
ambassador, High Commissioner Simbarashe Mumbengegwi, that Mugabe's
government must work ''to prevent further lawlessness and
violence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0215 </TRAILER>
