<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Fall Sharply  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS WAGNER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Rattled by last week's record losses on Wall
Street, Asia's top three stock markets fell sharply today, leaving
some investors worried that the bubble might have finally burst on
New York's exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, the main indexes in Tokyo, Singapore and Hong Kong
were all down more than 7 percent -- declines in range with Friday's
5.7 percent drop of the Dow Jones Industrial Average and 9.7
percent tumble on the Nasdaq Composite Index.
</P>
<P>
   In the world's second largest economy, Japan's benchmark Nikkei
225 Stock Average opened 8.8 percent lower to 18,641.06. Dropping
far below the key 20,000-point mark, the Nikkei stood at its lowest
level since Jan. 12, with technology stocks hit the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   By the afternoon, the Nikkei had recovered slightly to 18,875.02
points.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going straight down in line with the movement in New
York,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, a general manager at Chuo Securities
in Tokyo. ''I expected the market to fall, but I didn't think it
would fall quite this much.''
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said the losses ''were in line
with expectations'' and signs of Japan's economic recovery remain
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not too concerned,'' Miyazawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors clearly were. They gathered on sidewalks in central
Tokyo outside Shinko Securities to watch the stock prices flash on
the large electronic board overhead. Some worried that if U.S.
markets collapse it could be a real setback for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am scared. I am afraid this could happen all over the
world,'' said Yukio Nagano, 71, who retired last year. ''Japan's
economy is surviving only because of public spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said Wall Street's correction was long overdue and that
Japan's markets would probably quickly recover.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong and Singapore, the situation also was grim.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index was off 8.5 percent to
14,771.28 by midday.
</P>
<P>
   The big losers included Pacific Century CyberWorks Ltd., the
Internet startup run by Richard Li, the son of Hong Kong's top
billionaire, Li Ka-shing. After a few minutes of trading, PCCW was
down by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no idea this thing could be so bad,'' said Mark Mobius,
an emerging markets fund manager based in Hong Kong with Templeton
Franklin Investment Services (Asia) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, where many people are avid gamblers who love to
play the stock market, dozens gathered around computer screens in
bank offices, cursing at the sharply lower prices and grumbling
they should have gotten out earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, the Straits Times Index had fallen 8 percent to
2,014.60 by midday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're pretty much in line with what New York is doing.
It's all a question of whether or not New York is going to
recover,'' said Raymond Lee, a dealer at Keppel Securities in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Other markets in the region also dropped sharply, with
Australia's All Ordinaries Index down 5.63 percent by the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Korea Composite Stock Price Index dropped a record 11.96
percent right away before recovering slightly later on.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tumble was in sync with the crash of Wall Street, and the
trend is likely to persist for the time being,'' said Kim Sung-won,
an analyst at Dongwon Securities Co. in Seoul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0229 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma Bombing Victims Wince  </HEADLINE>
By TIM TALLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Marsha Kight wants the pain to stop. But
the prospect of a state trial for convicted Oklahoma City bombing
conspirator Terry Nichols only reminds her that it will never go
away.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like it never ends,'' said Kight, whose daughter,
Frankie Merrell, was killed in the April 19, 1995, attack. ''The
trial will open up a lot of wounds and cost a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols was already convicted and sentenced to life in prison on
federal bombing charges in a trial in Denver. In January, he was
brought to Oklahoma to face 160 state counts of first-degree
murder. Oklahoma County District Attorney Bob Macy is seeking the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims' advocates say putting Nichols on trial for his
life could just dredge up old emotions and overshadow the opening
of a memorial to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will still be dealing with the legal process for Terry
Nichols, appeals and all of that, at the 10th anniversary,'' said
Bud Welch, whose daughter, Julie, was among the 168 people killed
in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Nichols will be in a jail cell a few blocks from
where President Clinton will help dedicate a $24.1 million memorial
to victims and survivors of the blast -- the worst act of terrorism
on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a state bombing trial that could cost millions of
dollars and force survivors to relive the event has drawn
opposition from some of those most affected by the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a society, I really find it hard to believe that we're not
satisfied with life in prison,'' said Jim Denny, whose young son
and daughter were severely injured in the bombing. He said Nichols
is being forced to face trial in Oklahoma ''just to stick a needle
in his arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, 45, was convicted in federal court of eight counts of
involuntary manslaughter for the deaths of eight federal law
enforcement officers. He also was found guilty of one count of
conspiracy to use a weapon of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma, Nichols is accused of the deaths of bombing victims
who were not part of his federal trial. A preliminary hearing was
scheduled for Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols also faces one count of first-degree manslaughter for
the death of an unborn child whose mother was killed, one count of
conspiracy to commit murder and one count of aiding and counseling
in the placing of a substance or bomb near a public building.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols' co-defendant, Timothy McVeigh, was convicted on federal
murder charges and sentenced to death. State charges have not been
filed against McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   Each of their federal convictions are on appeal, and both
bombing conspirators are seeking new federal trials. It is the
possibility that Nichols' federal conviction could be overturned
that most worries those who want him tried on state bombing
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''He could conceivably walk out of a federal prison, get on a
plane and fly away,'' said Paul Heath, who was injured in the
bombing and serves as vice president of the Oklahoma City Murrah
Building Survivors Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand why any one of those family members whose loved
ones were taken away in those violent acts would want to see those
individuals prosecuted,'' Heath said.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents said any conviction on state charges will be
futile and cannot withstand the appellate process because of issues
already raised by Nichols' state defense attorneys, including his
constitutionally guaranteed right to a presumption of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not attorneys, but we know that one of the most
important parts of our justice system is the presumption of
innocence. And Terry Nichols has no presumption of innocence,''
Denny said.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols has alleged that he cannot receive a fair trial in
Oklahoma because of extensive publicity about the case and his
federal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   He has also alleged that it is unconstitutional to try him again
in Oklahoma because it would violate his constitutional guarantee
against being tried twice for the same crime.	   Welch said any state conviction
will likely be tossed out on
federal appeal because a fair and impartial jury can't be found to
try Nichols in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   But Heath said the search for justice requires that Nichols be
tried by a jury of Oklahomans.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I'm the only citizen in Oklahoma County at either a hearing
or a trial, it's because I feel it's my civic responsibility to
keep my promise to those that we would never forget,'' Heath said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City National Memorial Foundation site:
http://connections.oklahoman.net/memorial
</P>
<P>
   Families and Survivors United: http://heartserv.com/fsu
</P>
