<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, April 17, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Asian Markets Fall Sharply
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Rattled by last week's record losses on Wall Street, Asia's
top three stock markets fell sharply Monday, leaving some investors worried that
the bubble might have finally burst on New York's exchanges. By midday, the main
indexes in Tokyo, Singapore and Hong Kong were all down more than 7 percent --
declines in range with Friday's 5.7 percent drop of the Dow Jones Industrial
Average and 9.7 percent tumble on the Nasdaq Composite Index. Japan's benchmark
Nikkei Stock Average fell a staggering 1,426.04 points, to 19,008.64.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Plans Phones for Indians
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton, who played golf and hobnobbed
with the dot-com wealthy during a weekend in Silicon Valley, is getting a look
Monday at places and people who have been left out of the digital revolution.
Clinton was beginning his day in East Palo Alto, a hard-luck neighborhood in the
shadow of the high-tech giants and startups that have made this part of
California rich. Later, Clinton was headed to the Navajo Reservation in New
Mexico to announce a plan to speed computer access and improve
telecommunications for American Indians. The federal plan would provide basic
telephone service for $1 a month on reservations, the White House said Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Swarm at Finance Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Demonstrators set out to snarl workaday Washington Sunday
with protests aimed at world finance conferences that went on despite them over
the weekend. After two raucous days of marches, street theater and
confrontations with police, the federal government closed its agencies in the
potential protest zone, an 11 by 8 block swath east and west of the White House.
Both the federal and local governments encouraged all but essential workers to
stay home on leave. Police warned the protests on a busy weekday could create
fierce traffic jams.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwan Has Eye on Aegis Destroyers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When U.S. and Taiwanese officials gather behind closed
doors Monday to discuss which weapons the United States is willing to sell, the
$4.4 billion question will be whether Taiwan gets the go-ahead to buy the Aegis
destroyers it says it needs to counter a buildup of Chinese missiles. The talks
Monday and Tuesday in Washington are especially sensitive because of their
profound political implications. China has said it would be compelled to react
harshly if Taiwan acquires Aegis warships. Taiwan views its request as a test of
U.S. support in the face of China's continuing buildup of offensive missiles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Issues Environmental Warning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A United Nations-sponsored report said Sunday despite
greater environmental awareness, growing demand for resources is threatening the
world's environmental health more than ever. In the long term, it said, humans
will pay the price. The broad decline of the world's ecosystems -- the
interaction of organisms with their physical environment -- must be reversed or
there "could be devastating implications" for human development, the study said.
The study was sponsored by the U.N. Development Programme, the U.N.
Environmental Programme and the World Bank. It assessed the current health of
agriculture, coastal areas, forests, fresh water environments and grasslands.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Dad Lashes Out at Miami Kin
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's father lashed out at his Miami relatives on
Sunday, accusing them of "child abuse" for turning his son against him and
insisting that the 6-year-old boy wants to return to Cuba. With the boy's fate
still before federal judges, Juan Miguel Gonzalez said on CBS' "60 Minutes" that
he didn't believe a video taped at the relatives' home in which his son said he
didn't want to go. Family members did not make themselves available after the
show. Protesters, however, dismissed Juan Miguel's comments as either selfish or
the manipulations of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cardinals, Rockies Split Doubleheader
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) -- Jeff Manto hit a go-ahead double during an eight-run sixth
inning that propelled the Colorado Rockies to a 14-13 victory over the St. Louis
Cardinals in the second game of a split doubleheader Sunday night. The Rockies,
who lost the afternoon opener 9-3, came back from deficits of 3-0, 7-3 and 9-5
by sending 14 men to the plate against four St. Louis pitchers in the sixth.
J.D. Drew had a three-run double and Pat Hentgen kept his record with St. Louis
perfect as the Cardinals won Game 1.
</P>
