<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's largest dump to close -- but what then?  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A pair of sparrow hawks hovers overhead,
searching the wild rose bushes and crab apple trees for small prey.
Nearby a songbird remains hidden in a fledgling hackberry tree,
softly chirping a spring song.
</P>
<P>
   But now come ruder noises -- grrrrrrr, brummmmm, whirrrr,
vrooommmm and an insistent beep, beep, beep. The serene Wild
Kingdom moment vanishes as a garbage truck backs up and dumps yet
another load of rotting garbage onto an already behemoth mound.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world's largest garbage dump: the 3,000-acre
Fresh Kills Landfill in Staten Island. It's three times the size of
Central Park and at its highest point, about as tall as a 20-story
building.
</P>
<P>
   But now -- though many remain skeptical -- the quadruple towering
mounds of trash may stop growing. A closing date of Dec. 31, 2001,
was set long ago for the dump, and some politicians say it could be
shut before summer of that year since plans for exporting the last
5,100 tons of daily city trash are ahead of schedule. Three of the
four once-active dumping sites have already been closed.
</P>
<P>
   City planners have formed a commission to determine Fresh Kills'
future and after 52 long and smelly years, local politicians are
conjuring up closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Once the last mound is covered, the question remains: Will the
memory of the dump, and its pervasive stench, ever fade?
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a thicket of wild rose bushes where Rutgers
University professor Steven Handel has worked since 1993, it isn't
hard to believe that something so ugly could be transformed from
trash to treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ''The potential for ecological restoration is enormous,'' says
Handel, who was hired by the city Sanitation Department and is
working with a grant from the National Science Foundation
introducing native plants to the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   On a small patch of land where Handel has planted 70 different
species, delicate white flowers are about to bloom on a small but
sturdy crab apple tree. Red-tail hawks, egrets and herons already
call the landfill home after migrating a short distance from a
nearby wildlife refuge, which is part of the island's protected
Greenbelt forest and wetlands area.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around, Handel doesn't see garbage. He sees hope.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got to look ahead and have vision,'' he said, pointing
to seed traps that prove birds are bringing native plants back to
the area, and to a fistful of sticks duct-taped to a fledgling tree
used to attract wild bees.
</P>
<P>
   If city planners get their way, one day in the distant future --
anywhere from 10 to 50 years -- the area will be filled with natural
forests, wildflower meadows, baseball and soccer fields, hiking and
jogging trails, and even a marina.
</P>
<P>
   There are disagreements over how real -- and inviting -- this
future will be.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care what they put there. You won't find me there,''
said Staten Islander Madelyn Anastasakos, who is relieved the dump
is closing but can't imagine picnicking atop millions of tons of
trash.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanitation experts note that the future beauty of Fresh
Kills -- whose name comes from the Dutch word for water -- can
already be imagined from some 1,000 acres of the area that were
left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are sections near the upper reaches of the Kill Van Kull
that have never even seen a garbage truck,'' said Brendan Sexton, a
former deputy mayor and sanitation commissioner who is on the
city's landfill closure commission.
</P>
<P>
   Handel agreed, referring to some areas as ''virtually
pristine,'' and noting the estuaries that run through the dump are
in good shape and birds are already there.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of the ecological fabric is already present,'' he said.
''Our challenge is to maximize it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a history in taking something so ugly and turning
it into something lovely and green, said Sexton, who knows the dump
intimately, both as a former sanitation commissioner and a Staten
Islander.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that F. Scott Fitzgerald once wrote about a ''stinking
mass of burning, rotting trash and the fires of hell he had to pass
on his way back to Long Island from the city.'' That spot is now
Flushing Meadows Park, the site of two World Fairs and the giant
metal Unisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ''I grew up in Flushing Meadows, and no one in my neighborhood
ever thought of it as a dump,'' Sexton said, predicting that
memories of Fresh Kills as a dump also will fade.
</P>
<P>
   Other city parks, including Pelham Bay and Orchard Beach in the
Bronx, were landfills before their current incarnation. Centennial
Park in Liverpool, England, is another landfill conversion success.
</P>
<P>
   But for sheer size, Sexton said, ''There's never been a
reclamation project this large to my knowledge.'' He added, though,
that size could be an advantage: ''The opportunity to make
something grand is almost limitless.''
</P>
<P>
   An international design contest will be held, much like the one
used to find Central Park designers Frederick Law Olmsted and
Calvert Vaux in 1857. The competition, funded by the city and
state, is aimed at finding the best design for what many say is the
city's last great available green space.
</P>
<P>
   ''All suggestions should be considered,'' Sexton said. But he
added that the main thing city planners should realize is ''people
are desperate for open space in this town. ... People want to be
able to walk out their front door and have lunch on the grass.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation will not occur overnight. Federal
environmental laws dictate that the landfill's most contaminated
parts cannot be used for 30 years. The design competition alone
should take nearly three years, with public hearings in all five
boroughs before several designs are submitted to the City Planning
Department for final approval.
</P>
<P>
   While that is happening, the city will begin the closure
process, which includes capping the last two mounds of trash and
installing pipes to reclaim and recycle methane gas produced by the
rotting trash.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the land can almost immediately be planted with native
oak trees, shrubs and fields of flowers, and Handel believes that
''within 10 years it will be seen as a really lovely part of New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials say there will be immediate improvement for residents
living closest to the dump on the day it closes. There will be no
more trucks and barges coming so the noise level will drop and the
rotten egg smell should decrease dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ''The smell is worse of all,'' said Anastasakos, who has lived
on Staten Island for three years. ''It smacks you in the face the
minute you walk out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton said that should improve once more methane gas is drawn
out and fresh air is pumped in.
</P>
<P>
   It can't come soon enough for the nearly 400,000 Staten
Islanders who have complained since the dump opened in 1948.
Borough President Guy Molinari said his father, a state
assemblyman, fought against turning Fresh Kills into a dump because
he feared garbage eventually would cover all the vast, once vibrant
salt marshes.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has never been an issue more important to Staten
Islanders,'' said Molinari. ''The joke here is that of the 10
biggest issues on Staten Island, numbers 1 through 9 are the
garbage dump.''
</P>
<P>
   As an assemblyman himself and later as a congressman, Molinari
watched in dismay as the city closed landfills in the other
boroughs: first Edgemere in Queens, then Pennsylvania Avenue and
Fountain Avenue in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   By 1987, Fresh Kills was the city's only dump, taking in an
astronomical 27,000 tons of trash a day at its peak. Recycling has
since reduced that figure to about 14,000 tons a day.
</P>
<P>
   Those opposed to the landfill began warning city officials in
1989 that a more comprehensive plan was needed to get rid of the
city's waste. They predicted that if dumping continued at the peak
rate, Fresh Kills' mounds would reach 412 feet by 2005, making it
the highest man-made point on the Eastern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the tallest mound is 190 feet, and one councilman
suggested (somewhat tongue-in-cheek) that the city could turn Fresh
Kills into a ski slope when it closed.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari finally sued the city under the Federal Clean Air in
1996 and city, and later that year the closing date at the end of
2001 was announced for Fresh Kills.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the city has exported the bulk of its trash to other
states including New Jersey, Virginia and Pennsylvania. A recent
City Council analysis said that closing Fresh Kills and exporting
its trash will cost the city $622 million over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari looks forward to hosting ''a heck of a party,'' the day
the dump closes. And he's convinced Fresh Kills will once again be
home to fish and birds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be exquisite,'' he said confidently. ''Imagine, taking
something we are all ashamed of and making it something special.''
</P>
