<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 06:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At 96, Earthquake Survivor Recalled  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE LOCKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Bessie Shum doesn't remember the day San
Francisco came crashing down in a roar of dusty death. She was only
2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   For years, San Francisco didn't remember her pain either --
official lists of the earthquake dead list fewer than a dozen
Chinese names, even though hundreds are believed to have perished
in the crowded apartment houses of Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, organizers of the 94th annual memorial of the San
Francisco earthquake of 1906 hope to take a step toward recognizing
the victims time forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time that we find and make people aware that the Chinese
were here,'' says Gladys Hansen, city archivist emeritus and
curator of the Museum of the City of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was too little to remember the Great Quake
firsthand, Shum vividly recalls the stories her parents told, how
they dashed out of their one-room flat in Chinatown, her mother in
the arms of her husband, baby Bessie carried by a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother had bound feet; she couldn't walk too good,'' Shum
says. She throws up her slender hands to describe the flight from
Chinatown's rickety hazards: ''No time to pack! Just grabbed
diapers!''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many Chinese died in the 1906
earthquake. Hansen believes that the overall death toll was vastly
undercounted itself: At the time officials gave totals of between
478 and 498, and for decades after that the figure 700 was used.
But her research puts the toll at no less than 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, who arrived at her figure by going through letters,
newspapers and other sources from the time, blames the low figures
on the confusion, the fact that many died elsewhere after being
evacuated, fierce fires that turned bodies to cinder and a general
apathy toward the poor and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't just the Chinese. There were signs all over, 'No
Irish, no blacks, no Chinese need apply.' They got away with
this,'' Hansen says.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the story of post-earthquake Chinatown is one
of triumph over tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   After it was flattened by the earthquake, civic leaders eager to
move in on the valuable downtown property decided to push the
Chinese to the city's outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   But the community had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese-American merchant Look Tin Eli hired two architects to
design his destroyed bazaar. They gave traditional Western motifs
an Eastern flair, creating pagoda-style details that laid the
groundwork for modern-day Chinatown, a popular tourist spot nine
decades later.
</P>
<P>
   At 96, Shum still lives in Chinatown, on a street so steep you
have to bend your knees to walk up it.
</P>
<P>
   She is looking forward to getting up before dawn Tuesday to
gather for the 5:13 a.m. ceremony at Lotta's Fountain, a
post-earthquake gathering spot in 1906 and every anniversary since.
There, as always, participants will remember the dead with silence,
a wreath and then the wail of police and fire sirens.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been looking for a Chinese survivor for a really long
time,'' says event organizer Taren Sapienza. Shum was found after
Sapienza went to Mayor Willie Brown and he called in his liaison to
the Chinese-American community.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bessie sort of is my representative of the Chinese
community,'' says Sapienza, ''to make the wrong right.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.sfmuseum.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
