<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Architect Wins Pritzker  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rem Koolhaas, a Dutch architect known for
futuristic and unconventional building designs, has been named this
year's recipient of the Pritzker Architecture Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Koolhaas' work features stark designs, open space and generous
of glass. He is the first architect from the Netherlands to receive
his field's most prestigious award.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rem Koolhaas is widely respected as one of the most gifted and
original talents in world architecture today,'' said J. Carter
Brown, the prize jury chairman. Brown praised ''his restless mind,
conceptual brilliance and ability to make a building sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Koolhaas, 56, didn't become an architect until his late 20s and
was at first best known for his writing on urban design. He founded
his firm, the Office of Metropolitan Architecture, in 1975. Since
1995, he also has taught at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Koolhaas has several commissions in the United States, including
a student center for Chicago's Illinois Institute of Technology and
a new $156 million central library for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Koolhaas' European projects includes a home for a man who uses a
wheelchair -- a house in three sections, including a central large
platform that functions as an elevator. He also designed the
Educatorium, a multifunctional building for Utrecht University in
the Netherlands and Kunsthal in Rotterdam, Netherlands, which
contains exhibition space, a restaurant and auditoriums.
</P>
<P>
   The Pritzker prize, which includes a bronze medallion and
$100,000 grant was established by the Hyatt Foundation in 1979.
Koolhaas will receive the award May 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 0820 </TRAILER>
