<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Weighs Term Limits Statements  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states can require congressional candidates to support term
limits for members of Congress or be labeled an opponent on the
election ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will consider reviving Missouri's
voter-approved measure, thrown out by lower courts on grounds it
unlawfully forced candidates to speak on the subject or be
punished.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' decision is not expected until sometime in 2001,
too late for the congressional elections in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court dealt the term-limits movement a devastating
blow in 1995 by ruling that only a constitutional amendment can
limit the number of terms people can serve in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After that decision, Missouri and some other states enacted
''scarlet letter'' measures instructing their members of Congress
to push for a term-limits constitutional amendment or be branded an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's 1996 state constitutional amendment calls on members
of the state's congressional delegation to try to enact an
amendment limiting service to 12 years in the U.S. Senate and six
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do not comply, the next election ballot is to
carry the label ''disregarded voters' instruction on term limits''
next to their names.
</P>
<P>
   Non-incumbent congressional candidates are instructed to pledge
their support for term limits or have the following notation next
to their name on the ballot: ''declined to pledge to support term
limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional candidate Donald Gralike challenged the measure in
federal court, and a judge ruled the measure unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed, saying the
amendment violated candidates' free-speech rights by requiring them
to speak in favor of term limits or have a ''derogatory'' label
attached to their name on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also said the amendment unlawfully added to
the federal Constitution's list of qualifications for members of
Congress and violated a requirement that all amendment-making
efforts originate in Congress or the state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, Missouri's lawyers said the ballot
label was not punishment but lawful ''public commentary on the
behavior of congressional candidates.'' The measure does not compel
anyone to speak, the appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   Gralike's lawyers noted that every other state measure to be
reviewed by a federal court has been thrown out on constitutional
grounds. In 1997, the Supreme Court refused to revive a similar
measure in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Cook vs. Gralike, 99-929.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 8th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
