<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syracuse records eight shootings in three days, one fatal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- An 18-year-old city man was arraigned
today in the shooting death of another man.
</P>
<P>
   Jerrawn Thomas, who voluntarily surrendered to police Sunday
evening, was ordered held without bail at the Onondaga County
Justice Center following his arraignment for second-degree murder
and criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Thomas had not confessed to shooting 22-year-old
Jeffrey S. Connor and had answered no questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case is not closed,'' Syracuse police Sgt. Joe Sweeny
said, adding that more arrests could be made. ''We have much more
investigating to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeny said the weapon used to shoot Connor, the sixth homicide
victim in the city this year, had not been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Connor died Friday night after being shot twice as he walked
down South Salina Street. He was pronounced dead at 10:50 p.m.
after being shot earlier in the day in the upper leg and just below
his heart, according to University Hospital officials.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe Connor exchanged words with as many as 10
teen-agers on the front porch of a home. While they spoke, someone
fired a gun, Sweeny said. The teens then ran in different
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this time, we're not sure whether he went there looking for
someone or was just in the neighborhood,'' Sweeny said. ''We're
still questioning a whole bunch of witnesses in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers found numerous shell casings on the ground, as well as
bullet holes in nearby parked cars, Sweeny said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who live near the latest shooting understandably were
both concerned and scared.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really getting bad,'' Artina Pagan said. ''I mean, I had
just walked away from the window when I heard the shots. But I
could have been shot. My grandkids could have been shot, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of eight shootings in three days in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were wounded in the shootings. In the most serious
non-fatal incident, police said Tayon Wallace, 23, was shot
point-blank in the face while sitting in a car on the street around
3 a.m. Sunday. Police said someone had fired shots at Wallace's
house early Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Wallace and his brother were waiting for a
friend to come out of a restaurant when the second shooting
occurred. Wallace was hospitalized in serious condition today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
