<HEADLINE> Dow Up 139; Nasdaq Up 119  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today, but major indexes
rose sharply after a jittery start as investors began nibbling at
potential bargains from last week's carnage.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 139.30 at 10,445.07 after slipping 26 points near the open.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which lost one quarter of its value
last week, was up 119.90 at 3,441.19 after erasing an early
94-point drop by the technology-dominated measure.
</P>
<P>
   The modest recovery came despite sharp declines on overseas
markets in reaction to Friday's brutal slide on Wall Street, which
sliced a record 617 points off the Dow and a record 355 points off
the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, worried that rising inflation and interest rates will
cut into company profits, investors began dumping stocks in just
about every sector of the market along with the speculative
high-flyers from the Internet boom. The Dow was left 12 percent
below its record high, while the Nasdaq fell to 34 percent below
the record it reached March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly helping sentiment this morning were some more strong
profit reports on the first three months of the year, this time
from Citigroup, Merrill Lynch, Eastman Kodak and Ford Motor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while most popular stock barameters rose this morning,
the overall bias remained negative on the broad market, with
declining issues outnumbering advancers by nearly a 3-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Among other leading measures, the Standard and Poor's 500 index
was up 20.85 at 1,377.41 and the Russell 20000 index of smaller
companies was up 0.78 at 454.50.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 364.68 million million shares, exceeded
Friday's near-record pace.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 6.98 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.61 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 3.98 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 2.61 percent.
</P>
