<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Clarify Inmates' Review  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to clarify the
deadline for state inmates to seek federal court review of their
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will hear New York prosecutors' argument that
an inmate waited too long to file a federal court appeal arguing
that his conviction violated his rights. The inmate's previous
appeal in state court was not properly filed and therefore it did
not put the federal deadline on hold, prosecutors contend.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bruce Bennett was convicted of attempted murder and other
charges after a February 1983 incident in which prosecutors said he
fired two shots at a police car chasing the car in which he was
riding.
</P>
<P>
   His conviction was upheld by a New York state appeals court, and
the state's highest court refused to hear his appeal in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he asked a state court to set aside his
conviction but was turned down. In 1995, he filed a new petition in
state court raising additional grounds. The court turned him down
orally but did not issue a written order.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Bennett went to federal court, alleging that
his conviction violated his constitutional rights. A judge
dismissed his appeal, saying he missed the one-year deadline for
such appeals required by a 1996 federal law, the Antiterrorism and
Effective Death Penalty Act.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated his appeal,
saying the one-year deadline was on hold because his 1995 appeal in
state court was still pending.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 state appeal was properly filed because it met the
state's basic procedural requirements, the court said, declining to
consider whether the state appeal was improper because the issues
he raised may have been barred under state law.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, prosecutors said the 2nd Circuit
court's ruling would allow the federal deadline to be delayed by
''almost any piece of paper'' filed as a state appeal, regardless
of whether it complied with state law.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's lawyer said state courts can head off such appeals by
requiring judicial authorization to file them.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Artuz vs. Bennett, 99-1238.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Bennett v. Artuz:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on 2nd Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
