<HEADLINE> Dow, Nasdaq Up but Most Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mostly lower today, but major
indexes rose after a jittery start as investors began nibbling at
potential blue-chip bargains following last week's carnage.
</P>
<P>
   By midday on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was
up 88.42 at 10,394.19, having quickly recovered from an early
26-point dip.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which lost one quarter of its value
last week, was up 80.68 at 3,401.97 after erasing an early 94-point
drop by the technology-dominated measure.
</P>
<P>
   But while investors showed some renewed interest in many of the
biggest and most popular names that tumbled last week, the overall
bias remained negative today, with declining issues outnumbering
advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the broad market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was encouraging to see signs of stability, especially
since overseas markets had tumbled before today's open in reaction
to Friday's brutal slide on Wall Street, which sliced a record 617
points off the Dow and a record 355 points off the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, worried that rising inflation and interest rates will
cut into company profits, investors began dumping stocks in just
about every sector of the market along with the speculative
high-flyers from the Internet boom. The Dow was left 12 percent
below its record high, while the Nasdaq fell to 34 percent below
the record it reached March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly helping sentiment this morning were some more strong
profit reports on the first three months of the year, this time
from Citigroup, Merrill Lynch, Eastman Kodak and Ford Motor.
</P>
<P>
   Among other leading measures, the Standard and Poor's 500 index
was up 10.66 at 1,367.22, but the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies was down 1.20 at 452.52.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 517.43 million shares, almost even with
Friday's near-record pace.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 6.98 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.61 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 3.98 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 2.61 percent.
</P>
