<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Marshal Pleads Guilty To Theft  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former deputy U.S. marshal assigned to
protect witnesses pleaded guilty Monday to stealing about $6,500
meant for the witnesses, the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton D. Coleman, 48, a supervisor in the Witness Protection
Program in the District of Columbia Superior Court, embezzled funds
from witnesses' subsistence accounts, the department's Office of
the Inspector General said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation found Coleman forged witnesses' signatures on
voucher receipts and then pocketed the difference between the
amount on the receipts and what he gave the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, a 14-year veteran with the Marshals Service, resigned
in October while the investigation was under way. He could face a
maximum of 10 years imprisonment when he is sentenced July 12.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office and the Marshals Service
conducted the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
