<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film sales, digital photography lift Kodak profits 15 percent  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co., buoyed by higher film
sales and narrowing losses in its digital photography business,
posted a 15 percent rise in first-quarter profits Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time charges, the world's biggest photography
company earned $297 million, or 95 cents a share, compared with
$259 million, or 80 cents a share, in the same quarter a year ago.
Revenues overall were unchanged at $3.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat Wall Street analysts' expectations of 93 cents
a share, as reported by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   When one-time charges are included, Kodak's net profit totaled
$289 million, or 93 cents a share, up 51 percent from $191 million,
or 59 cents a share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak benefited from continued cost savings during the quarter
but incurred $8 million in after-tax costs associated with closing
its Elmgrove manufacturing hub in Rochester. A year ago, earnings
were reduced $68 million by a variety of restructuring charges.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its revenues from film sales rose 2 percent in
the United States and 3 percent worldwide during the quarter, with
higher volumes offsetting a 3 percent fall in prices and the
negative impact of a strong U.S. dollar in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Losses in digital photography, the recording of images on
computer chips, continued to narrow to $4 million in the quarter
from $12 million a year ago -- helped by Kodak's inclusion in the
category of digital products sold to the graphics industry.
</P>
<P>
   Digital products revenues increased 15 percent to $706 million
from $612 million a year ago, boosted by a 62 percent jump in sales
of consumer digital cameras and robust sales of health-imaging
scanners.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging-market sales accelerated 16 percent in the quarter,
helped by robust performances in China, India, Russia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak has benefited from stronger volumes in the key U.S.
consumer film market, where falling prices have pinched margins.
The market has been softening over the last year since being roiled
by a price war sparked by Japanese nemesis Fuji in 1997. That
battle led to around 20,000 jobs cuts at Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive Dan Carp cautioned that sales, expected to grow
between 6 percent and 7 percent this year, could be reduced by 1
percentage point if the dollar remained strong against other
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Carp took over Jan. 1 from George Fisher, who stepped down as
CEO after a turbulent, six-year reign. Fisher is staying on as
chairman until Dec. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 1339 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old flags rotting away; governor wants funds to restore them  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Seventy-three battle flags beneath which
Connecticut troops once fought and died are crumbling due to a lack
of funding.
</P>
<P>
   The flags from the Civil War, Spanish-American War and World
Wars I and II are the last victims of a budget deficit from 10
years ago, when a program to preserve them came to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   That project put 95 other battle banners on display in the
Capitol's dimly lit Hall of the Flags, visited by more than 30,000
schoolchildren each year. Several other flags are framed and hung
in a climate-controlled case in the Capitol's basement.
</P>
<P>
   The 73 remaining flags, including a heavily embroidered Civil
War banner created by Tiffany and Co. for Connecticut's 18th
Regiment, rest in boxes tucked away from public view, in a
fifth-floor office of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the flags' plight, Gov. John G. Rowland said he will try
to secure preservation funding during budget talks before the May 3
legislative deadline of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time to do the right thing,'' Rowland said. ''Now that
economic prosperity has returned, we have the surplus funds to do
the job. We've spent millions of dollars to restore the Capitol. We
need to make the flag preservation a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of beautiful stories about the courage of the
men from Connecticut,'' said Monsignor Joseph A. Devine, pastor of
Waterbury's Our Lady of Loreto Church.
</P>
<P>
   Devine, who is chaplain of the state Senate, also led the
Capitol preservation effort 20 years ago through the Committee on
Legislative Management.
</P>
<P>
   In laws dating back to 1949, state battle flags in public hands
were ordered deposited in the Capitol ''in suitable cases.'' By the
mid-1980s, lawmakers approved $100,000 to preserve and display
flags, with the contract going to the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   But as the state budget deficit climbed, leading to the
still-controversial income tax vote in 1991, the flag project was
quietly abandoned, leaving Devine with dozens of crumbling flags.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Gerry Caughman, a volunteer Capitol tour guide who helped
stabilize the forgotten flags, researching their history, wrapping
them in muslin, acid-free tissue and bubble wrap, shutting them
away from light in boxes in a locked office five flights up from
the Hall of the Flags.
</P>
<P>
   Now she patrols the cases, writing summaries of the military
units, monitoring fabric deterioration and evidence of insects.
Caughman feels strongly that these remnants of the state's history
should be cherished.
</P>
<P>
   ''Connecticut men died for these flags,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 1342 </TRAILER>
