<HEADLINE> Feelings Range With Start II Treaty  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three former American negotiators said Monday
that an agreement with Russia to cut nuclear arsenals is imperiled
by conservative Senate Republicans who want to jettison a ban on
missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators also questioned whether the Clinton
administration has a strategy to implement the START II treaty and
its cutbacks of about 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's a game plan,'' ex-negotiator Thomas
Graham said at a news conference held by the private Arms Control
Association. ''They are thinking mostly about domestic politics and
electing the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham also said it would be ''a recipe for rekindling the
nuclear arms race'' for the Clinton administration to go ahead with
a limited defense against missiles without a green light from
Russia, the European allies and China.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Keeny, president of the association, said it would be
the United States' advantage to carry out START II, which the Duma,
the lower house of the Russian Parliament, approved last week. The
upper house began considering the treaty Monday.
</P>
<P>
   START II refers to the second Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty,
signed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   While reducing U.S. and Russian stockpiles of long-range nuclear
weapons to fewer than 3,500 from current levels of about 6,000
each, the treaty would ban Russia's SS-18 missiles,
multiple-warhead, land-based weapons that are the most powerful in
the Russian arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Keeny, who held senior posts in the U.S. Arms Control
and Disarmament Agency, and Jack Mendelsohn, a former U.S.
negotiator on START II, said the administration was required to
seek Senate approval of various amendments to the 1993 treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But attempting that, they said, would give conservative
Republicans a chance to scuttle the 1972 treaty banning
anti-missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin said last Friday that he would
consider canceling all major arms control agreements with the
United States if it withdrew from the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   This week, U.S. and Russian negotiators are due to meet in
Geneva, to consider a treaty designed to make even deeper cuts in
nuclear arsenals and what the Clinton administration hopes will be
Russian approval of a limited missile-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is a reduction to 2,000 to 2,500 each, but Russia is
expected to push for even deeper cuts, to about 1,500 long-range
nuclear warheads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
