<HEADLINE> Clinton Going to Russia in June  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- President Clinton will travel to
Moscow in early June for a two-day summit with Russia's new
president, Vladimir Putin, the White House announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be in Moscow June 4-5 and then travel on to Kiev,
Ukraine, June 6.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made as Clinton visited East Palo Alto to
encourage investment in poorer communities in America.
</P>
<P>
   The stops in Russia and Ukraine will come at the end of a trip
that will include Portugal and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The president will be in Portugal May 30 through June 1 for a
regularly scheduled summit with European Union leaders and an
official visit to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he will go Berlin for a summit on ''third way''
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Others invited for the June 2-3 summit led by German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder are leaders from Argentina, Brazil, Britain,
Chile, France, Israel, Italy, South Africa, the Netherlands, New
Zealand, Portugal and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also will pick up the prestigious Charlemagne prize in
Aachen.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Clinton will meet with Putin and other Russian
leaders. ''The president also hopes to use his visit to speak to a
broad spectrum of Russian leaders who are building new democratic
institutions, civil society and a market economy,'' a White House
statement said.
</P>
