<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CNBC Film Examines Wall St. History  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- That sinking feeling in the pit of your
stomach, the one that feels exactly like a tumbling stock market,
is an old American malady.
</P>
<P>
   Take a market overheated by new technology mania, mix with a
dash of harsh reality and you've got a recipe for gastric
discomfort, as CNBC's documentary ''The Great Game: The Story of
Wall Street'' makes clear.
</P>
<P>
   Overvalued Internet stocks are merely the wayward stock darlings
of the day, according to historian John Steele Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've see it over and over and over again, starting with the
bank shares in the 1790s, canal shares in the 1820s, railroads in
the 1830s and airline stocks in the 1920s after Lindbergh flew the
Atlantic,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone thought the future of air travel was limitless and
started bidding up the prices of airline stocks,'' he said. ''Most
of the companies had never flown an airplane and no one had the
faintest idea of how to make money conveying passengers by
airplane. But still the stock went up.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology may change, but human nature and the emotions that
drive Wall Street -- fear and greed, as the old saying goes -- remain
the same, Gordon said. Not that there's anything wrong with that,
according to the documentary, which points a rosy view of the
evolution of the stock market and the U.S. economic system.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour film, debuting 8 p.m. EDT Monday (April 24), is a
colorful and revealing look at finance that even the uninitiated
will appreciate. Although a bit of unexplained jargon slips by
(such as buying stocks ''on margin,'' with money borrowed from a
brokerage), host Sue Herera, a CNBC anchor, and experts make the
workings of capitalism easy to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Gordon's book ''The Great Game: The Emergence of Wall
Street as a World Power'' (Scribner), the program begins at the
beginning, with the establishment of New York by business-savvy
Netherlanders.
</P>
<P>
   Besides giving us the words cookie and Brooklyn, the Dutch also
contributed such capitalist advancements as stock markets and
insurance; 17th century Holland was the cradle of modern
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, named for the wall that the Dutch had built against
invasion, became the city's financial heart.
</P>
<P>
   Among the film's intriguing historical tidbits: The Spanish
pieces of eight commonly used by colonials are why the New York
Stock Exchange quotes prices in eighths, not tenths, of a dollar;
the bank that became Chase Manhattan was founded as part of Aaron
Burr's water company scheme; signal flagmen quickly transmitted
stock prices from New York to Philadelphia in pre-telegraph days.
</P>
<P>
   Boom and bust cycles were common from the start. This ditty,
written in 1857, is virtually timeless: ''Monday, I started my land
operations. Tuesday, owed millions by all calculations. Wednesday,
my brownstone palace began. Thursday, I drove out a spanking new
span (team of horses). Friday, I gave a magnificent ball. Saturday,
smashed -- with just nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The film tracks the regulations that helped bring a measure of
stability and order to the market, such as stricter accounting
practices, the filing of annual reports and the creation of the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's first chairman was future presidential dad Joseph P.
Kennedy, who gained a reputation as a sterling and efficient
administrator. Don't count on the usually reliable Kennedy clan for
adding color to this particular story; that comes from other
dashing and eccentric figures.
</P>
<P>
   We meet the ''Witch of Wall Street,'' Hetty Green, who is
counted as the only woman among the 40 richest Americans to have
made rather than inherited her fortune. She was shrewd, tough and
chintzy, an unbeatable combination.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth operators Jay Gould and Jim Fisk, who almost scammed $7
million out of Cornelius Vanderbilt in a fight over the Erie
Railway and brought chaos to the 1869 stock market with a gold
scheme, were ''no more honest than the standards of their day,'' as
Gordon puts it.
</P>
<P>
   How the little guy is affected by such shenanigans is little
explored in the film. But ''The Great Game'' does look at one
unsettling truth: The bleakest of events can bring buoyancy to the
economy. Civil War-era gold speculators profited when battles went
against the Union, causing President Lincoln to rail, ''I wish
every one of them would have his devilish head shot off.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another issue the film skirts but which Gordon says
will become more and more urgent: the lack of international
regulation in an increasingly global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can be sitting in Madascagar with your laptop and trading
on the New York Stock Exchange and there's no real way for the SEC
or the New York Stock Exchange to regulate you,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing a global equivalent of the SEC, Gordon contends,
''is going to be the great political problem of the next decade or
so because we really don't have mechanisms to achieve that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1413 </TRAILER>
