<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notable Rulings by 'Miranda' Court  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some recent significant rulings by the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of
Appeals:
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIRANDA:
</P>
<P>
   --In February 1999, the court ruled that an obscure 1968 federal
law effectively overturned the U.S. Supreme Court's 1966 Miranda
ruling, which requires police to inform suspects of their rights.
The appeals court ruled 8-5 that the law, known as Section 3501,
made failing to give Miranda warnings just one of several factors
in deciding whether statements to police were made voluntarily. The
Supreme Court will hear the case on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE AGAINST WOMEN:
</P>
<P>
   --In March 1999, the court voted 7-4 to strike down a portion of
a federal law that allows victims of rape or domestic violence to
sue their attackers for damages under civil rights law. The court
said Congress overstepped its bounds when it relied on its power to
regulate interstate commerce to enact the Violence Against Women
Act. Christy Brzonkala was seeking a trial on her claims that her
civil rights were violated by Virginia Tech and two football
players who were accused of raping her while she was a student
there. The Supreme Court heard arguments in the case in January. It
has yet to rule.
</P>
<P>
   HANDICAPPED PARKING:
</P>
<P>
   --In a 2-1 ruling in February 1999, a panel of the court ruled
that the Americans with Disabilities Act does not prohibit states
from charging disabled people for such things as handicapped
license plates and handicapped parking placards that are hung from
rearview mirrors. Five disabled people had sued North Carolina,
saying the state broke the law by charging $5 for placards. The
full appeals court refused to rehear the case, and the Supreme
Court has not decided whether to take the case.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO:
</P>
<P>
   --In August 1998, a panel ruled 2-1 that the Food and Drug
Administration did not have the power to regulate nicotine as a
drug. The ruling was a victory for the tobacco industry, which is
strong in most of the states that are part of the 4th Circuit. The
Supreme Court upheld the ruling 5-4 last month.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVER'S PRIVACY:
</P>
<P>
   --In a 2-1 ruling in September 1998, a panel ruled that a federal
law severely restricting the release of driver's license
information is an unconstitutional infringement on states' rights.
Congress enacted the Driver's Privacy Protection Act of 1994 to
prevent stalkers from using driver's license information to find
people. The appeals court said the law went too far in prohibiting
states from selling lists of registered drivers. In January,
however, the Supreme Court unanimously reversed the 4th Circuit, a
departure from the justices' recent string of decisions reining in
federal power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
