<HEADLINE> Court To Rule on Term Limit Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taking up a dispute involving term limits and
free speech, the Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
states can require congressional candidates to push for such limits
or be branded as opponents on the election ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will consider whether Missouri's
voter-approved measure violates candidates' free-speech rights. The
measure was thrown out by a federal appeals court, as have been
similar ''scarlet letter'' laws enacted by several other states.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Benson, the lawyer for a congressional candidate who
challenged the Missouri rule, said he was surprised the Supreme
Court agreed to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'm confident that when the court looks closely at
Missouri's scarlet letter amendment, it will see it for what it is,
a gross violation of the First Amendment rights of candidates for
federal office,'' Benson said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' decision is expected in 2001, too late for the
congressional elections in November.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court dealt the term-limits movement a devastating
blow in 1995 by ruling that only a constitutional amendment can
limit the number of terms people can serve in Congress. Missouri
and other states enacted their ''scarlet letter'' laws after that
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's 1996 state constitutional amendment calls on members
of the congressional delegation to try to enact an amendment
limiting service to 12 years in the U.S. Senate and six in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do not comply, the next election ballot is to
carry the label ''disregarded voters' instruction on term limits''
next to their names.
</P>
<P>
   Non-incumbent congressional candidates must pledge their support
for term limits or have the following notation next to their names:
''declined to pledge to support term limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional candidate Donald Gralike challenged the measure in
federal court, and a judge ruled the measure unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed, saying the
amendment violated candidates' free-speech rights by requiring them
to speak in favor of term limits or have a ''derogatory'' label
attached to their name on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also said the amendment unlawfully added to
the federal Constitution's list of qualifications for members of
Congress and violated a requirement that all amendment-making
efforts originate in Congress or the state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   In appealing to the Supreme Court, Missouri's lawyers said the
ballot label was lawful ''public commentary'' on congressional
candidates' behavior and did not compel anyone to speak, the appeal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gralike's lawyers said the rule would transform the election
ballot ''to a billboard for political advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Gralike vs. Cook:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 8th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
