<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 129; Nasdaq Up 31  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices fluctuated on Wall Street today as a
battered stock market sought a direction after Friday's devastating
selloff. Major indexes alternated between positive and negative
territory, but the broader market was lower.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 129.37 at 10,435.14, having changed direction
several times since the session began.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which lost one quarter of its value
last week, was up 31.77 at 3,353.06. Earlier, the
technology-dominated measure had swung from an early 94-point drop
to a 133-point gain.
</P>
<P>
   But while investors initially showed renewed interest in many of
the big and popular companies that tumbled last week, the overall
bias was negative from the start, with declining issues
outnumbering advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on the broad market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was encouraging to see signs of stability, especially
since foreign markets had tumbled overnight in reaction to Friday's
brutal slide on Wall Street, which sliced a record 617 points off
the Dow and a record 355 points off the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, worried that rising inflation and interest rates will
cut into company profits, investors began dumping stocks in just
about every sector of the market along with the speculative
high-flyers from the Internet boom. The Dow was left 12 percent
below its record high, while the Nasdaq fell to 34 percent below
the record it reached March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly helping sentiment today were some more strong profit
reports on the first three months of the year, this time from
Citigroup, Merrill Lynch, Eastman Kodak and Ford Motor.
</P>
<P>
   Among other leading measures, the Standard and Poor's 500 index
was down 8.90 at 1,347.66, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies was down 11.76 at 441.96.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 770.25 million shares, down slightly from
Friday's near-record pace.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 6.98 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index fell 0.38 percent, Britain's
FT-SE 100 fell 2.97 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
