<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daughter in Nigeria tells mother ''you will never find me''  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A New Jersey girl left by her father in
Nigeria more than two years ago has written another letter saying
she wants to stay there, telling her mother ''you will never find
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an appellate panel ruled last week that Longy Anyanwu
is entitled to another court hearing on charges he has refused to
help return his daughter to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Anyanwu, a former computer sciences professor at Montclair State
University, has been jailed since August 1997 on contempt charges
for refusing to reveal the whereabouts of his two children, Uchechi
and Ogechi.
</P>
<P>
   Anyanwu's ex-wife, Edith, learned in 1998 that 11-year-old
Ogechi had died in Nigeria months earlier of malnutrition. Efforts
by the State Department to find Uchechi have been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   But Anyanwu said Monday from the Morris County jail that Uchechi
has been living with his sister and brother-in-law in Lagos,
Nigeria. He said he has not written a letter requesting that
Nigerian authorities return her because ''it will offend my God
that I should tell lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyanwu, 50, argues that he is bound by a Nigerian court order
that granted custody of his two daughters to him when he and his
wife divorced, and not a New Jersey court order that granted
custody to his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that Superior Court Judge Herbert Friend had ordered
him to tell Nigerian authorities that he was not in jail, and
accused the state courts of ''racial supremacy'' by refusing to
respect his African culture.
</P>
<P>
   He said on Monday that he does not see an end to his
incarceration. ''The only thing that will make it end will be if my
life expires in jail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyanwu, who had lived in Dover, mailed letters to The
Associated Press that he says 14-year-old Uchechi wrote to both him
and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, dated Jan. 18, Uchechi urged her mother to drop
her custody battle and accept Nigerian law.
</P>
<P>
   ''Daddy behaves like an Igbo man, not an American man,'' the
letter said. ''Nothing you can do can change that.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl said she would like to visit her mother in the future
but wants to finish school in Nigeria and eventually live with her
father.
</P>
<P>
   ''No matter how much you try to find and kidnap me, you will
never find me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyanwu produced a letter by Uchechi expressing similar
sentiments in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   An appellate panel of Superior Court on Friday ordered a new
hearing on Anyanwu's case after Edith Anyanwu failed to respond to
Anyanwu's latest appeals. The panel said it wanted to determine
whether Edith Anyanwu still wanted her ex-husband to obey the court
order to locate her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Porro, the attorney for Edith Anyanwu, did not return a
telephone message on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian authorities have never produced the remains of Ogechi
Anyanwu, who had a rare intestinal disorder. Porro has said the
girl likely died because she did not receive adequate medical care
in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Anyanwu said he thinks the girl stopped eating
because she missed him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was told that she was asking all the time to see her dad,''
Anyanwu said. ''The doctors said there was nothing they can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 1456 </TRAILER>
