<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Russia Ready for START III Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Top U.S. and Russian arms negotiators launched a
round of talks Monday for additional strategic arms cuts, made
possible by the Russian parliament's ratification of START II.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the two sides refused to go into detail about their
four hours of discussions beyond confirming that they took place in
Russian diplomatic quarters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But arms-control experts said the outcome could have
far-reaching impact if the two sides are able to break out of the
complex web of interrelated issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot depends on the deal the Americans and Russians can do on
missile defenses,'' said Patricia Lewis, director of the U.N.
Institute for Disarmament Research.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said progress in the talks could revive global disarmament
efforts on a broad front, especially involving other nuclear
countries, including China, India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day session comes after the Russian lower house of
parliament, the State Duma, ratified the START II treaty on Friday.
The upper house began considering the treaty Monday and is expected
to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   But an amendment to that accord is still pending in Washington.
And the two countries remain at odds over U.S. plans for a limited
missile defense system, which would require renegotiating the
landmark Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, three former U.S. negotiators warned Monday that
conservative Senate Republicans who want to jettison the ban on
missile defenses are undermining attempts to agree on START III.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the two sides toward rapid progress are President
Clinton's desire for a diplomatic success before he leaves office
and President Vladimir Putin's need to avoid burdening the Russian
economy with costs for armaments, said Daryl Kimball of a
Washington-based anti-nuclear group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia knows that the Clinton administration wants to reach an
agreement and is probably going to wait them out to the last days
of the Clinton administration to increase its negotiating
leverage,'' said Kimball, director of the Coalition to Reduce
Nuclear Dangers.
</P>
<P>
   START II would halve U.S. and Russian nuclear arsenals to
3,000-3,500 warheads each. Under U.S. and Russian proposals a START
III treaty could cut each arsenal to as low as 1,500 strategic
warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva meeting, while billed as the formal inauguration of
START III talks, is a continuation of contacts that began last
summer after Clinton got a commitment from then-President Boris
Yeltsin to talk about ABM revision and reviving efforts to cut
strategic arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration maintains that Moscow should consider
deploying its own limited missile defense against attacks from
''rogue'' nations, but Moscow says the system would upset the
strategic balance and launch a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting the two days of talks are Yuri Kapralov, head of the
Russian Foreign Ministry's arms control department, and John Holum,
the Clinton administration's key disarmament specialist. A second
round was planned for the U.S. Mission on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Center for Nonproliferation Studies of Monterey, Calif.:
http://cns.miis.edu/
</P>
<P>
   Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers, Washington, D.C.:
http://www.clw.org/coalition/
</P>
<P>
   PIR - Center for Policy Studies in Russia:
http://www.pircenter.org/english/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
