<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Off on Wet Outlook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Forecasts for more rainy weather in the Midwest
this week sent grain and soybean futures lower Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Soggy conditions are expected again in the central United States
starting later in the week from two more weather systems moving
toward the region, new forecasts showed.
</P>
<P>
   That further dampened enthusiasm for agricultural commodities,
which saw a runup in prices in late winter due to concerns that dry
soil conditions would have a detrimental effect on crops.
</P>
<P>
   Corn dipped lower on the bearish weather news, although the
decline was limited by continuing drier-than-usual conditions in
many growing areas. Only parts of Indiana and Ohio had normal
rainfall totals for the first half of April.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans also fell because of the forecasts, with the rebound in
U.S. stock markets helping to keep the decline minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat was pressured by the slide in corn along with increased
rain prospects for the winter wheat belt.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell 2} cents to $2.65{ a bushel; May
corn fell 2{ cents to $2.32{ a bushel; July oats fell 1 cent to
$1.19{ a bushel; July soybeans fell { cent to $5.44 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures retreated in trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .38 cent to 68.97 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .33 cent to 84.27 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .82 cent to 74.35 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell 1.70
cent to 94.95 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
