<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Rep. Visits Baghdad Hospital  </HEADLINE>
By LEON BARKHO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- U.S. Representative Tony Hall stroked the
heads of malnourished Iraqi children and expressed concern at the
lack of medicines in the pharmacy as he toured a pediatric hospital
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''How old is he?'' Hall asked a woman weeping by the side of her
sick son's bed.
</P>
<P>
   ''My boy can hardly breathe and he is so thin he cannot walk,''
said the woman, Amal Abass, 35.
</P>
<P>
   Though 2 years old, Hayder Abdulwahab, cannot stand on his feet.
Doctors said both he and his mother were deprived of vitamins and
nutrients needed for normal growth.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, D-Ohio, arrived Sunday to investigate the plight of Iraqi
people under nearly 10 years of U.N. sanctions. He is one of very
few U.S. Congressmen to visit Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War over
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions were imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
Iraq says about 1.2 million people have died, including some
750,000 children under age 5, because of malnutrition, lack of
medicines and other shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm trying to get a feeling ... is the food and medicine not
getting through? What's the end problem? What's the hang-up and
what can I do to make things better,'' Hall told reporters. He
plans to report his findings to the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq blames the shortages on the sanctions but the United States
and Britain are skeptical and say President Saddam Hussein's
government must share the blame by not fulfilling U.N. Security
Council resolutions that would lead to the lifting of the
sanctions. The U.S. government also accuses Saddam of squandering
money on luxuries for himself and his officials and ignoring the
plight of his people.
</P>
<P>
   Hall has said that his four-day visit is purely humanitarian and
not aimed at discussing the disputes between the Iraqi and U.S.
governments. He has refused to comment on the sanctions, describing
them as a ''very complex issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq put its hostility aside Monday as Hall was warmly received
by Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak and other senior Iraqi
health officials.
</P>
<P>
   The official Iraqi News Agency said Mubarak told Hall of the
difficulties Iraq faces in getting medicines and medical supplies.
It did not say how Hall responded.
</P>
<P>
   The two later toured the Saddam Medical Complex in Baghdad, the
best medical facility in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   After touring the hospital pharmacy, Hall said: ''There is no
question that there are hardly any drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one visit to a hospital was not enough to formulate an
opinion. More trips, including a tour of the south, will give him
''an understanding of why so many children are sick, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
