<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Block Key Bolivian Road  </HEADLINE>
By PETER McFARREN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- Coca leaf farmers blocked a key road and
scuffled with truckers Monday in a protest against government plans
to destroy illegal coca plantations.
</P>
<P>
   The peasants' blockade follows violent nationwide protests a
week earlier, which led the government to severely curtail
constitutional guarantees and give security forces a freer rein to
crack down. The restrictions are still in effect, although the
original protests have ended.
</P>
<P>
   The government said cocaine traffickers were behind Monday's
protest by coca leaf farmers. Coca leaf is used to make cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of soldiers and police were on hand, but did not
immediately move in to clear the roadblocks on the road linking
Bolivia's highlands with the tropical lowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Some clashes broke out between the coca farmers and truck
drivers trying to bring coffee, lemons, oranges and other produce
into La Paz.
</P>
<P>
   The roadblocks were set up at the Yungas, a lush tropical region
some 130 miles east of La Paz. Large quantities of produce from the
region had rotted as result of the roadblocks set up during last
week's protests.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of coca leaf growers, Jose Montevilla, said the
roadblocks will continue until the government suspends plans to
eradicate coca leaf plants in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Bolivia's anti-narcotic law allows for the cultivation of about
30,000 acres of coca plants to supply traditional markets that
include coca tea and chewing. Coca leaf fields beyond that area are
considered illegal and subject to destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates there are nearly 5,000 acres of illegal
fields in the Yungas and plans to destroy them this year, as part
of its fight against the cocaine industry.
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Banzer has vowed Bolivia will no longer produce
illegal coca and cocaine within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Walter Guiteras said cocaine traffickers are
behind the protests in the Yungas and are seeking ''to create
conditions of instability for the government and democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The destruction in recent years of more than two-thirds of coca
leaf production in the Chapare, an area east of Yungas that fed the
cocaine industry, has deprived thousands of peasants of their sole
source of income.
</P>
<P>
   The protests last week by peasants and workers were triggered by
an increase in water rates in Cochabamba, Bolivia's third largest
city, and by an economic crisis affecting South America's poorest
country. The Cochabamba region was particularly affected by the
eradication of coca plantations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
