<HEADLINE> German Cops Arrest Eight Neo-Nazis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- Eight neo-Nazis have been arrested as
suspects in the arson attack on a home for foreigners and the poor
near Munich, prosecutors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the group have admitted to the attack in Dorfen and face
possible attempted murder and arson charges, prosecutor Helmut
Kobor said.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, the suspects aged 17 to 19 were kicked out
of a youth center in Dorfen on Saturday for singing a Nazi anthem.
The main suspect, a 17-year-old in the group, also beat up another
visitor to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking revenge, authorities said the group first considered
setting fire to the youth center, but didn't because too many
people were gathered outside. Instead, they went to the nearby home
where 19 residents were staying.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old splashed a canister of gasoline on the entrance
of the house and through a window and set it on fire, police
spokesman Chris Maier said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only through luck that the residents quickly noticed and
extinguished the flames, Maier said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in another incident of anti-foreigner violence late
Sunday, a youth with a group of others shouted insults and attacked
a 27-year-old man from Cameroon in the town of Neustadt-Dosse in
eastern Brandenburg state, police said. The African asylum seeker
was treated by a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they were investigating but had no suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
