<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainians Vote on Kuchma's Power  </HEADLINE>
By MARINA SYSOYEVA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Voters have given Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma a strong mandate to expand his control over an unruly
parliament, but the vote alone does not ensure the president a
decisive victory in his power struggle with legislators.
</P>
<P>
   During a Sunday referendum, voters here gave overwhelming
approval to four Kuchma proposals that would alter parliament,
results showed Monday. The proposals, though, still must pass
parliament itself -- and if that approval is withheld, it could
ignite a deep political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum was intended to resolve a long-standing conflict
here between supporters of liberal economic reforms and those
nostalgic for more stable Soviet times and state controls. The
parliament, or Verkhovna Rada, was dominated by Ukraine's Communist
Party until earlier this year, while Kuchma has supported
IMF-sponsored reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum called for trimming the 540-seat Rada to a
300-seat assembly with two houses -- one composed of nationally
elected candidates and the other of appointed municipal and
regional officials. It also asked voters if they want to remove
deputies' legal immunity and give the president the right to
disband parliament in certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 100 percent of the 29.5 million ballots counted,
support for the four questions hovered at between 81.8 and 89.9
percent Monday, said Mykhailo Riabets, chairman of the Central
Election Commission. Initial voter turnout figures were an
unexpectedly high 78.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma initiated the referendum in January after years of
feuding with the parliament. Although a new pro-government majority
has been created in parliament, Kuchma insists it is not stable
enough to help Ukraine overcome its post-Soviet economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum is just a first step: Each question must pass the
Rada as a constitutional amendment. Analysts say parliament is
unlikely to pass all the amendments, and Kuchma has indicated he
might disband the legislature if it fails to approve the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people's will must not only be honored but implemented as
well,'' Kuchma told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Similar standoffs led former Russian President Boris Yeltsin to
forcefully dissolve his country's Supreme Soviet in October 1993
and Belarus' authoritarian President Alexander Lukashenko to
disband his parliament and vastly expand his powers in a November
1996 referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Political opponents say Kuchma is trying to create a pocket
parliament, and some accuse him of seeking dictatorial powers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time will show what are the real intentions of the president
and his circle,'' said Socialist Party leader Oleksandr Moroz, a
Kuchma rival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1638 </TRAILER>
