<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Stabilize in New York  </HEADLINE>
By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index and the Dow
industrials both rose more than 200 points in a late-session rally
today after fluctuating throughout a tentative session on Wall
Street. The Nasdaq achieved its biggest one-day point gain one
session after its biggest point drop, but the overall market still
fell as investors remained highly cautious following last week's
devastating selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq changed direction throughout the day before closing
up 218.37 at 3,539.66, according to preliminary calculations. The
advance, which surpassed its previous one-day record gain of 178.89
on April 7, followed the index's record 355.49-point plunge on
Friday. The 6.6 percent rise in Nasdaq was second only to the 7.3
percent of Oct. 21, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which reversed course several times today, gained
276.74 to 10,582.51, regaining some of the 617.78 points it lost on
Friday in the blue chips' biggest point drop on record.
</P>
<P>
   The advance in both indexes was a welcome sign of possible
stability after last week's losses, which slashed nearly $2
trillion from the stock market's value and one-quarter of the
Nasdaq's value. But with five stocks falling for every three that
rose today on the broader stock market, it was too early to tell if
Wall Street was squarely on the way to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street had been expected to decline today as investors are
extremely wary after last week's debacle. Still, the fact that
investors were interested in buying at all was a positive sign,
although they were focusing on big-name stocks, those believed to
be the most stable.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas markets closed lower, including a nearly 7 percent drop
in Tokyo, as traders reacted to Friday's plunge in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Europe's largest stock market, the FTSE 100 index of
Britain's largest companies fell nearly 3 percent on the London
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's DAX blue-chip index fell nearly 0.4 percent. In Paris,
the CAC 40 index of leading shares was down 0.09 percent from
Friday's close. Both indexes recovered from earlier heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Japan's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell
nearly 9 percent before closing with a loss of 1,426.04 points, or
6.98 percent, at 19,008.64. It was the fifth-largest percentage
drop in the Nikkei's history.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tokyo close today, ruling coalition policy chiefs
agreed to recommend pumping up to 1 trillion yen, or $9.7 billion,
in public funds into the stock market if it continues to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index finished with its second-worst
one-day point loss in history, falling 8.55 percent, to 14,762.37.
In Singapore, the Straits Times Index closed 8.69 percent lower at
1,999.39.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to their Asian counterparts, investors in Europe
appeared to be somewhat less fearful that Wall Street's bull market
might finally have expired.
</P>
</TEXT>
