<HEADLINE> Clinton To Meet Putin in June  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Arms control, economic reforms and
Russia's offensive in Chechnya will highlight talks between
President Clinton and Russia's new president in early June during a
two-day meeting in Moscow, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be in Moscow June 4-5 to meet with President
Vladimir Putin and then will travel on to Kiev, Ukraine, on June 6,
according to the announcement released Monday in East Palo Alto
where Clinton was traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president and President Putin spoke some time ago and
agreed that it was important to keep up regular meetings,'' White
House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said in Washington. They will
discuss such issues as economic and political reform and the
promotion of democracy, he said. ''Arms control will be an
important issue, and I expect they'll also discuss Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   The stops in Russia and Ukraine will come at the end of a trip
that will include Portugal and Germany. The president will be in
Portugal May 30 through June 1 for a regularly scheduled meeting
with European Union leaders and an official visit to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he will go to Berlin for still another meeting, June
2-3, with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and leaders from
Argentina, Brazil, Britain, Chile, France, Israel, Italy, South
Africa, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Portugal and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also will pick up the prestigious Charlemagne prize in
Aachen.
</P>
</TEXT>
