<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. School Takes Action on Threat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICKASHA, Okla. (AP) -- Students at an intermediate school had
to pass through metal detectors and leave their book bags and
backpacks at home Monday after a student found a note threatening a
shooting and a listing of 26 students.
</P>
<P>
   The note found Friday was pushed through the vents of a locker,
Officer Rusty Winsett said in his police report. He said three
students found it when they opened the locker.
</P>
<P>
   The letter reportedly stated that a shooting would take place
later in the school year, and 26 people would die. It also
contained a picture of a gun, 26 circled x's and a list of 26
sixth- and seventh-grade students at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Alex Souza told police that the list was a mixture of
male and female, black and white students, some of whom were
considered upper class, and some of whom were teachers' children.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Lynn Williams said the note also threatened harm to anyone
who found the note if they turned it over to authorities. The note
said the students would be harmed by May 17, the final day of
classes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, administrators allowed no loose clothing, no book
bags or backpacks, no oversized purses and no coats and jackets to
be worn during school hours.
</P>
<P>
   Students were allowed to enter through only one door and had to
pass through a metal detector. A dog trained in gunpowder detection
was at the school, along with police and school security staff.
</P>
<P>
   Only 140 of the 460 students in the intermediate school attended
classes Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
