<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Environmentalists Supported  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans are broadly supportive of the
environmental movement three decades after the first Earth Day,
says a new Gallup Poll, but they don't consider the environment a
top political priority.
</P>
<P>
   The poll released Monday indicated that one in six people are
active with the environmental movement, while just over half say
they're sympathetic to the movement though not active. Four of five
said they're sympathetic to the goals of the environmental
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's all good news,'' said Brenda Box, a spokeswoman
for the National Wildlife Federation. ''Thirty years ago when we
celebrated the first Earth Day, most people weren't aware of the
environmental movement and most people weren't actively doing
much.''
</P>
<P>
   A vast majority of people say they take steps in their personal
lives such as recycling newspapers, cans and bottles, cutting down
on use of water and fuel, and avoiding products that harm the
environment. People were divided on whether they considered
themselves environmentalists, supporting the concept more than
actually getting involved.
</P>
<P>
   ''When people hear about specific crises, they get very
interested in the environment,'' said Colleen Costello, a
27-year-old waitress and environmental activist from Columbus, Ohio
in Washington Monday to protest the World Bank. ''But it's so easy
to just go home and turn the television on without actually doing
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   While awareness and sympathy of the environmental movement have
grown since 1970, people generally do not view the environment with
a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ''People care about it, but it's not the most significant
issue,'' said Riley Dunlap, a coordinator of the environmental poll
for Gallup.
</P>
<P>
   Support in the polls for the environmental movement peaked about
10 years ago, after events like the Exxon Valdez oil spill,
discussion of global warming and the discovery of medical waste on
beaches caught public attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''People expect clean air and clean water and they get engaged
when they think that's threatened,'' said Steve Cochran, a
spokesman for Environmental Defense. ''We need to engage people on
this issue in their daily lives, not just when they're
threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   The environment doesn't rank as high as an issue in the
presidential contest as issues like education, health care, crime,
family values and the economy, the poll said. But it ranks in the
middle with such issues as gun control and tax reduction in the
poll of 1,004 adults taken April 3 through 9, It has an error
margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Because of other voter priorities, the environment is not likely
to be a dominant political issue in the presidential election. But
Vice President Al Gore's book on the environment ''Earth in the
Balance'' has been re-released and Gore defends elements of the
book that conservatives have used to paint him as an environmental
extremist, such as his call for the abolition of the internal
combustion engine. Likely Democratic nominee Gore says he's looking
for new types of cars, not the abolition of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the likely Republican nominee, has
pushed a few of his own environmental proposals, recently calling
for a cleanup of contaminated plant sites. But environmental
problems in Texas include Houston air pollution that recently
surpassed that of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unclear how the environment will play in the election,''
Dunlap said. ''Results suggest it's still a second-level issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of Earth Day, which falls on April 22, hope to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our intention is to catapult environmental issues generally
and global warming issues specifically into the top tier of
American political issues,'' said Denis Hayes, chairman of the
Earth Day Network, ''so that no one running for president or the
local city council can get elected without saying what they would
do to achieve clean energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1713 </TRAILER>
