<P>
   European Stocks Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Most European stocks fell today, but losses were
curtailed after signs of a rally in U.S. markets alleviated fears
that Friday's tumble was the start of a prolonged market slide. The
Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell 5.8
points, or 1.6 percent, to close at 368.24, while pan-European
technology index Easdaq was down 8.6 percent, both higher than
their day's lows. Observers warned that the U.S. rally could be
fragile. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended down 3.51 points on
today at 414.82. London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 183.5 points,
or 3 percent, to close at 5,994.6. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index
recovered from early losses to close just 0.4 percent lower than
Friday, down 7,187.14. Amsterdam's AEX Index down 1.9 percent to
637.87.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup Posts 49 Pct. Profit Jump
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup Inc. reported an impressive 49 percent
profit increase for the first-quarter, easily topping Wall Street's
expectations as the nation's largest financial service company
reaped the benefits of the economic expansion. Citigroup, which
owns Citibank, Travelers Insurance and the Salomon Smith Barney
investment bank, reported net income of $3.59 billion, or $1.04 a
share. Analysts had expected the company to earn just 78 cents a
share, according to First Call/Thomson Financial. In the year-ago
quarter, Citigroup had net income of $2.42 billion, or 68 cents a
share. Revenue totaled $17.50 billion, up 19 percent from $14.66
billion a year ago. Citigroup stock was up 1 13/16 at 57 today.
</P>
<P>
   Film Sales Lift Kodak's 1Q Profits
</P>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Eastman Kodak Co. reported a 15 percent
increase in first-quarter profits today, thanks to higher film
sales and narrowing losses in its digital photography business.
Excluding one-time charges, the world's biggest photography company
earned $297 million, or 95 cents a share, compared with $259
million, or 80 cents a share, in the same quarter a year ago.
Revenues were unchanged at $3.1 billion. The results beat Wall
Street analysts' expectations of 93 cents a share,
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch Reports Higher Earns
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the country's largest
brokerage firm, reported a sharp increase in first-quarter earnings
today on higher revenues from stock trading and investment banking.
Merrill Lynch earned $1.04 billion, or $2.38 a share, well above
the $1.83 a share forecast by analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial. The brokerage had profits of $609 million,
or $1.44 a share, in the same period a year ago. First-quarter
profits were down across Wall Street last year as securities firms
recovered from the fallout wrought by the Asian and Russian
financial crises. Fees from advice on mergers and acquisitions
jumped due to Merrill's role as financial adviser on the largest
corporate takeover in history, Vodaphone AirTouch's takeover of
Mannesmann, a German telecom and engineering company. Merrill Lynch
stock was up \ at 90\ today.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Earns $2.1B in First Quarter
</P>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. earned $2.1 billion in the
first quarter, a 5 percent increase from a year ago as North
American results improved and losses shrank in Europe and South
America. The results beat Wall Street expectations. The world's No.
2 automaker said today it earned $1.70 a share for this year's
first three months, compared to $2 billion, or $1.60 a share, for
the same period last year. The results topped analyst forecasts of
$1.58 a share, as reported by First Call/Thomson Financial. Ford
stock was up 4} at 57.
</P>
<P>
   Sears' Earns Shoot Sharply Higher
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s first-quarter earnings
jumped 61 percent over last year thanks to solid improvements in
both its retail and credit businesses. The earnings report released
today matched expectations on Wall Street, where investors latched
onto the latest signs of improvement in Sears' sometimes-sluggish
retail sales. The retailer's earnings for the first three months of
2000 were $235 million, or 65 cents a share, up from $146 million,
or 38 cents a share, in the same period a year ago. Revenues rose 4
percent to $8.97 million from $8.66 million.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly Profits Rise 18 Percent
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Eli Lilly &AMP; Co.'s first-quarter profits rose
a better-than-expected 18 percent, fueled by strong sales of the
drugmaker's schizophrenia and diabetes medicines. Excluding unusual
items, Lilly's net income in the quarter was $692.3 million, or 63
cents a share, up from $625.7 million, or 56 cents per share, a
year ago. Results beat Wall Street analysts' expectations by two
cents, according to First Call/Thompson Financial. Sales rose to
$2.54 billion from $2.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 IMF Protesters Arrested in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dwindling band of protesters, facing a
steady rain and police reinforcements, failed to shut down
international finance meetings today but played havoc with the
workaday life of downtown Washington. There were sporadic clashes
with police equipped with riot gear and scores of arrests. By
afternoon, a standoff between police and protesters along
barricades near the International Monetary Fund and World Bank
buildings had begun to ebb as rains intensified. Police began
arresting the demonstrators peaceably in groups of a dozen or so,
arm in arm, which allowed them to make their point.
</P>
<P>
   Tire Makers Forming Net Marketplace
</P>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany (AP) -- Six of the world's leading tire and
rubber makers are forming an online marketplace for doing business,
tiremaker Continental AG said today. German-based Continental is
joining U.S. tire giants Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. as well as
Cooper Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. in the venture would should be up and
running by the end of the year. France-based Michelin, Japan-based
Sumitomo and Pirelli from Italy are also taking part.
RubberNetwork.com, to be an independent company, will host the
worldwide marketplace, Continental said. The plan is similar to one
recently announced by automakers in the United States and Germany
for online commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden To Issue New Mobile Licenses
</P>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM -- Sweden will issue its first four licenses for the
next generation of mobile telephone technology later this year, the
national Post and Telecom Agency said today. Applications for
control of radio spectrum that will allow companies to operate
Universal Mobile Telecommunications Systems are due Sept. 1. They
will be judged according to the speed and feasibility of the
company's rollout plan, as well as how many people will benefit
from the services, the agency said. It plans to make a decision by
November.
</P>
