<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Renames Streets As Reward  </HEADLINE>
By KATE N. GROSSMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Muddy Waters has one. So do Clarence Darrow and
David Ben-Gurion. Even hot dog magnate Abe ''Fluky'' Drexler has a
Chicago intersection bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the first to admit that maybe people get carried away,''
says City Alderman Burton Natarus, who takes credit for much of
Chicago's honorary street-naming. ''Some say the signs are tacky
and all that, but you can make people feel good, so why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Good will is overflowing on Chicago's streets.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, the number of honorary signs approached 860. That
means one out of almost every five major street intersections in
the city has a brown honorary sign just below the official green
one.
</P>
<P>
   The number of such signs has exploded this decade, putting
Chicago far ahead of both New York City, which has 115, and Los
Angeles, with just 15.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Chicago's signs honor celebrities like former Chicago
Bears coach Mike Ditka and writer Studs Terkel. Most of the signs,
however, honor the not-so-famous, including dozens of local clergy
members and community leaders who have made a difference in their
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   City Council approval is usually a foregone conclusion. But last
week, Playboy founder Hugh Hefner shook up the status quo. After
two days of rowdy debate -- including the unfurling of a Playboy
centerfold in the council chamber -- and a set of flip-flop votes,
the aldermen voted to create Hugh M. Hefner Way.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Alderman Thomas Allen proposed limiting each alderman
to two street signs a year. He offered the same measure in 1997,
but it generated such controversy that he dropped it. This time,
the odds are still iffy. Mayor Richard M. Daley hasn't come out in
support of it, and street-naming remains a popular gimmick among
aldermen.
</P>
<P>
   Kenan Heise, a former Chicago Tribune reporter who has written
several books on Chicago, says he knows why: ''You win favor with a
group of constituents by naming a street after a local -- preferably
someone in a group that votes.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way. At one time, Chicago aldermen had
more impressive ways to curry favor. When Richard J. ''Boss''
Daley, the current mayor's father, ran the city, the Democratic
Machine hummed and patronage reigned. Aldermen rewarded
neighborhood loyalists with city jobs and public services.
</P>
<P>
   But good government advocates and Harold Washington, Chicago's
first black mayor, helped break the Machine. A federal decree
forbade patronage in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Heise says, aldermen reward their constituents with
''something that will put their star in the sky -- a lamppost is as
high as they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Chicagoans say their aldermen's hearts are in the right
place.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my neighborhood, there are streets after people who died in
Vietnam and the Gulf War, and people who did something in the
area,'' says Don Hayner, a Chicago Sun-Times editor who wrote a
book on Chicago street names. ''It leaves a little bit of
neighborhood history.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, says Natarus: ''People hate the government. This might
actually help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1720 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
