<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Tells of Lebanon Pullout Plan  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Israel officially informed the United
Nations Monday that it plans to withdraw its forces from Lebanon by
early July, handing the world body the tough task of helping to fix
borders and ensure security.
</P>
<P>
   All Israeli forces will be pulled out ''in one go'' by July 7 to
the internationally recognized border, Israeli U.N. Ambassador
Yehuda Lancry told reporters after delivering a letter from Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and has occupied part of southern
Lebanon since 1985 as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on
northern Israel. The withdrawal of Israeli forces would fulfill
1978 U.N. resolutions on ending the occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Israeli officers say there are less than a thousand
Israeli troops in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Lancry stressed that ''no pockets'' of Israeli military would
remain in Lebanon. ''We are going to redeploy in the international
recognized border under the auspices of the United Nations,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Levy told reporters after meeting his French
counterpart, Hubert Vedrine, that ''the withdrawal will be at the
line accepted by the experts of all parties involved -- the United
Nations, Lebanon and Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1978 Security Council resolutions established a U.N.
peacekeeping force whose main job is to confirm an Israeli
withdrawal. U.N. troops have been in Lebanon since that spring
monitoring attacks by the Israeli forces and by the Islamic
Hezbollah guerrillas who have fought for years to expel Israel from
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The resolutions call for the peacekeeping force to restore peace
to the region and help the Lebanese government regain its authority
in the country, where Syria remains the main power broker. Levy's
letter, which Annan later sent to members of the U.N. Security
Council, said ''Israel will do its utmost to assist the United
Nations'' in implementing the resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Israel Television, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said U.N. troops will be in south Lebanon after a withdrawal
-- ''possibly as an expanded force.'' Israel believes the U.N.
force, now numbering nearly 4,500 troops, will be enough to patrol
the Israel-Lebanon border if expanded to its full mandate of 7,000
soldiers, a senior Israeli official said recently, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has pledged for months to withdraw Israeli troops from
Lebanon by summer, preferably as part of an agreement with Lebanon
and Syria but unilaterally if necessary. Talks between Israel and
Syria have stalled since January.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Lancry, Annan held separate talks with Lebanese
U.N. Ambassador Selim Tadmoury and Syrian U.N. Ambassador Mikhail
Wehbe to inform them of Israel's intention. He also telephoned
Lebanese and Syrian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from Lebanese officials. In the
past, they have welcomed Israeli withdrawal but have insisted on
their own conditions to implement the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   On Israel's northern border, Kiryat Shemona Mayor Chaim Barbivai
called on Barak to reconsider his decision. Residents of the region
fear an Israeli withdrawal will leave them vulnerable to attacks
from the guerrillas across the border in Lebanon. Israel has
promised to swiftly respond to any such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very grave,'' Barbivai said. ''To our dismay people
are frightened and feel in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said the challenge for
the United Nations is ''to see to it that the withdrawal is
conducted safely without any resumption of conflict or escalation
of violence.'' He said contingency planning by the U.N. Secretariat
is already under way.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. forces on the ground fear a unilateral withdrawal will be a
nightmare because they will have to deal with Israel's proxy
militia, the South Lebanon Army, as well as Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the South Lebanon Army will be allowed to live in
Israel after the withdrawal, Lancry said. He said the government
expects between 3,000 and 4,000 families to settle in the Jewish
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
