<HEADLINE> Copper Prices Down on Economy Worry  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Copper prices tumbled to a seven-month low Monday on investor
jitters about the stock market and the state of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, heating oil futures leaped higher,
pulling other energy products up with them, and sugar roared to a
five-month high.
</P>
<P>
   Every jolt to the stock market or confidence in the U.S. economy
has an aftershock in copper, whose fate is tied closely to that of
the construction industry and U.S. homebuilding trends.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, even a resurgent stock market couldn't overcome
uneasiness that the wind has gone out of the sails in the economy's
and equities' booms, meaning uncertain times ahead for the
industrial metal.
</P>
<P>
   Copper for May delivery settled down 1 cent at 74.35 cents a
pound after falling to a 7{-month low of 74.10 cents on the Comex
division of the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   That extended a slide that began in January with prices at a
26-month high of more than 88 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   ''You would have thought you would have seen a little more
strength in copper because of the stock rally'' which began Monday
morning, said Dave Megar, metals analyst for Alaron Trading Corp.
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blame mostly heavy fund selling ... along with the equity
market jitters,'' he said. ''People are still extremely nervous
about the weakening economic outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, seasonal demand is waning with summer building projects
all booked by now. Bargain-hunting, the analyst said, is likely to
boost the market soon with prices having fallen so low.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the New York Merc, heating oil prices rocketed 5
percent higher as distillate fuel supplies tightened with farmers
filling their tractors for spring planting.
</P>
<P>
   Exacerbating the distillate supply crunch were continued
operating problems at an Exxon Mobil unit in Joliet, Ill. The unit,
which produces 240,000 barrels a day of diesel fuel, is a main
source for Midwestern farm suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   May heating oil rose 3.07 cents to 69.47 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices, meanwhile, also were buoyed by news that
Motiva was delaying the restart of a 90,000-barrels-a-day
gasoline-producing unit at its refinery in Port Arthur, Texas, by
two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   May crude rose 32 cents to $25.89 a barrel, May unleaded
gasoline rose 2.16 cents to 81.98 cents a gallon and May natural
gas rose 8 cents to $3.158 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea rose 33 cents to
$22.74 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar zoomed higher on a technically inspired rally on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange. Shrinking crop acreage in
some countries as a result of recently low prices underpinned the
price rise.
</P>
<P>
   July sugar settled up .25 cent at 6.60 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
