<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changes in store for Niagara Falls park  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- For the first time in decades, the
state is changing its approach to improving the parkland
surrounding Niagara Falls, focusing less on concrete and asphalt
and more on nature.
</P>
<P>
   While construction blooms across the Niagara River on the
Canadian side, officials will concentrate on turning the American
side into an ''ecotourism'' destination, with interactive centers
that celebrate nature, landscape architect Frederick Law Olmsted
and the Free Niagara movement that saved the falls from
industrialization, state Parks Commissioner Bernadette Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Niagara Reservation should be a gateway to the Frederick
Law Olmsted experience,'' Castro told The Buffalo News. ''What we
have here you can't experience anywhere else. But we have to work
harder to get people to think, 'I can't possibly go to Niagara
Falls and not experience the American side.'''
</P>
<P>
   Officials will seek public input as they revise the master plan
for the Niagara Reservation over the next two years. Plans so far
include connecting existing sections of the Niagara Gorge trail to
create a scenic seven-mile hike from the falls to Artpark in
Lewiston, and turning the outdated Schoellkopf Geological Museum,
down the river from the falls, into an interactive children's
nature exhibit and virtual reality theater.
</P>
<P>
   A vacant century-old fieldstone building on Goat Island, which
had served as the park's vehicle garage until several years ago,
would become another education-centered, interpretive site,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro emphasized that the state's primary role in the Niagara
Reservation, to safeguard the natural resource, would not change.
</P>
<P>
   She said tourists are seeking more active and outdoor things to
do with their families while on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're taking a whole new approach. We think people are
different today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state will pursue corporate partnerships to help with the
cost, Castro said, but the project still will require support from
Gov. George Pataki and the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''As this gathers momentum and enthusiasm, I think the governor
will be interested in this plan,'' Castro said. ''I have every
reason to believe he would be (supportive).''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Schillaci, chairwoman of the Olmsted Conservancy, said
the private environmental preservation group would help in any way
it can.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shame on us for letting it get so run down, so far from what
it was and what it could be again,'' she said. ''Now is the time to
think about how we will leave this natural wonder to our children
and their children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 1742 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
