<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Reports Higher Earns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the country's largest
brokerage firm, reported a sharp increase in first-quarter earnings
Monday on higher revenues from stock trading and investment
banking.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch earned $1.04 billion, or $2.38 a share, well above
the $1.83 a share forecast by analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial. The brokerage had profits of $609 million,
or $1.44 a share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter profits were down across Wall Street last year as
securities firms recovered from the fallout wrought by the Asian
and Russian financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   Fees from advice on mergers and acquisitions jumped due to
Merrill's role as financial adviser on the largest corporate
takeover in history, the acquisition by British telecommunications
company Vodaphone AirTouch of Mannesmann, a German telecom and
engineering company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it's too early to say how Merrill's second-quarter
earnings will be affected by the recent market downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Merger and acquisition activity, which has surged recently as
companies have taken advantage of their high stock prices to
purchase other companies, is certain to slow down if the market
fails to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The market for initial public stock offering will also slow if
stocks continue to falter and demand for new shares dries up.
</P>
<P>
   Total first-quarter revenues were $7.25 billion, up from $5.27
billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''These outstanding results demonstrate the power of our global
institutional franchise and the momentum generated by the
far-reaching changes we have implemented in our private client and
asset management businesses,'' said Merrill Lynch chairman David
Komansky.
</P>
<P>
   Like many old line Wall Street brokerage firms, Merrill Lynch
recently began offering clients online trading services at lower
rates than their traditional full service brokerage fees.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching a 52-week high of $115.18} last month, Merrill's
stock has slipped with the rest of the market. Company shares rose
25 cents to $90.25 in trading Monday at 4:30 p.m. on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
