<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutual Fund Investors Stay On Track  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mutual fund investors held firm Monday,
apparently shrugging off the temptation to flee the stock markets
in the wake of last week's huge selloff.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that resistance helped the markets bounce back
from Friday's historic losses, when the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 617.78 points and the Nasdaq composite index dropped
355.49.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, stocks dipped in and out of positive territory before
rallying late in the session. The Dow average rose more than 276
points, and the Nasdaq experienced its largest one-day point gain
ever, climbing nearly 218 points.
</P>
<P>
   Art Bonnel, portfolio manager of U.S. Global Investor's Bonnel
Growth Fund, said most mutual fund investors don't concern
themselves with temporary market fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in mutual funds have more of a long-term mentality,''
he said. ''They aren't the day traders. That's one of the reasons a
lot of the professional mutual fund people aren't selling out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnel speculated that most of the selling by mutual fund
managers in recent days was done by newer funds that were started
in the last few years to capitalize on the demand for technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But as those stocks began to plunge, fund managers needed to
sell to cut their losses, Bonnel said.
</P>
<P>
   Information on specific funds that have sold shares in the past
few days wasn't available Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Individual fund investors seemed to take the market's mood
swings in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Methner, a retired investor in Denver who invests only in
conservative so-called value funds, said he pays no attention to
''market hiccups.''
</P>
<P>
   Value funds try to invest in solid companies whose stocks are
undervalued.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't even turned on the television or listened to the
radio today to see what the markets are doing because I'm not
selling or buying. Daily occurrences don't affect my investment
strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the larger fund families, there were few signs of panic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tenor of our calls today was strictly business as usual,''
said John Demming, a spokesman at Vanguard Group, the second
largest U.S. mutual fund company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1757 </TRAILER>
