<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Touts Tax Plan As Boon  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Flanked by single mothers and working
families, George W. Bush argued Monday that the real winners in his
$438 billion tax-cut package are those ''living on the outskirts of
poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive GOP presidential nominee used a high school
appearance to rip into Democratic rival Al Gore on both taxes and
gun control, accusing the vice president of flip flops and a dearth
of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want four more years of Clinton-Gore, I'm not the right
guy,'' Bush declared in President Clinton's home state.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor used the focus on tax-filing deadline day to
argue that fewer issues offer a starker contrast with Gore than
taxes, and to claim that his package focuses on blue-collar
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rejected the ''risky'' label Gore and other Democrats apply
to his five-year tax cut plan in arguing that it would eat up too
much of the expected budget surplus and plunge the nation back into
deficit spending. Bush also dismissed critics who say his plan
would help the rich more.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's risky is overtaxing the people who work for a living in
America,'' said Bush, who criticized Gore for not convincing fellow
Democrats in Congress to get rid of the so-called tax marriage
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for Vice President Al Gore to stand up and show some
leadership,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane quickly fired back, repeating the
campaign's charges that Bush is offering ''an irresponsible, risky
tax scheme'' but conceding that taxes is a clear difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a real choice,'' said Lehane. ''The American people
will have to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush argued that troubling news on the stock market and economic
nervousness underscores the need for a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you cut the taxes on people who work, it serves as an
insurance policy against economic downturn,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was pitching tax cuts, Bush got his biggest cheers
when he underscored his anti-abortion views during a question
session. He added, however, that ''people should be realistic''
about what can be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said there is insufficient support for a constitutional
amendment outlawing abortions with exceptions for rape, incest and
to save the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand that people disagree,'' said Bush, who said he
backs the Republican Party platform's strict anti-abortion
language.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Thursday's anniversary of a bloody Columbine High
School shooting in Littleton, Colo., Bush also was questioned about
gun control and a Texas law allowing concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''This law has made Texas a safer place,'' Bush argued, noting
that when Tennessee adopted a similar law ''Al Gore was totally
silent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would sign a bill that mandated the sale of trigger locks
with guns,'' Bush added. ''It's one thing to have a trigger lock
sold with a gun, it's another thing to encourage people to use
them.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a distinct working class feel to Bush's campaign swing
Monday. He visited a town that's headquarters to the blue-collar
retailing giant Wal-Mart and toured a museum touting the company's
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want tax relief to go to everybody ...,'' said Bush. ''Money
will go to people in families who are living on the outskirts of
poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   In a high school gymnasium, packed with about 500 students and
adults, Bush was introduced by Kim Jenning, a single mother who
made $20,000 and said she would pay no taxes under Bush's plan,
saving $830.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee, however, noted that the
richest 5 percent of Americans would get more than 50 percent of
the Bush tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign set up a Web site, allowing people who have
incomes of $100,000 or less to figure how much they would save with
Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC posted a rival Web site, ''millionairesforbush.com,''
that calculates the tax bill for people making $1 million or more.
''What a boon the Bush tax scheme is for the wealthiest
Americans,'' the DNC said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his tax-cut plan would spend barely a quarter of the
projected budget surplus over 10 years. Experts peg the cost of
Bush's tax plan at up to $1.3 trillion over 10 years, while
estimates of the projected budget surplus range from $900 billion
to $1.9 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, back in Washington after a weekend fund-raising swing
through California, took the day off at home. His White House staff
circuitously picked their way through police checkpoints to report
to work on a day when much of the capital was shut down by
protesters outside the World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.georgebush.com/taxcalc/Demographics.asp
</P>
<P>
   http://www.millionairesforbush.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
