<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citigroup Posts 49 Pct. Profit Jump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Citigroup Inc. reported an impressive 49 percent
profit increase for the first-quarter, easily topping Wall Street's
expectations as the nation's largest financial service company
reaped the benefits of the economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, which owns Citibank, Travelers Insurance and the
Salomon Smith Barney investment bank, reported net income of $3.59
billion, or $1.04 a share. Analysts had expected the company to
earn just 78 cents a share, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   In the year-ago quarter, Citigroup had net income of $2.42
billion, or 68 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue totaled $17.50 billion, up 19 percent from $14.66
billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very well positioned going forward in all of our
businesses,'' said Sanford I. Weill, chairman and co-chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The recent turbulence in the stock markets and the threat of
higher interest rates -- often bad news for banks -- haven't dimmed
Weill's view.
</P>
<P>
   ''One never enjoys watching significant market corrections,'' he
said. ''As far as our company's position, long term, events like
this should put us in a better position, vis-a-vis what's happening
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based company is spending a lot of money to expand
its brand online. The company lost $93 million on its e-Citi effort
in the quarter, up from a loss of $35 million in the first quarter
last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of just a few areas where Citigroup isn't making money.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank's banking and mortgage income rose 27 percent to $610
million in the quarter. Meanwhile, Salomon Smith Barney's income
from underwriting stock offerings and advising on mergers and
acquisitions totaled $957 million, a 48 percent increase over the
year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   The Travelers Insurance Group was one of the weaker performers
with income rising 12 percent to $381 million.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup's shares rose $1.25 to $59.25 in trading at 4:30 p.m.
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
