<HEADLINE> Eli Lilly Profits Rise 18 Percent  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SKILES LUKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Eli Lilly &AMP; Co.'s first-quarter profits rose
a better-than-expected 18 percent, fueled by strong sales of the
drugmaker's schizophrenia and diabetes medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding unusual items, Lilly's net income in the quarter was
$692.3 million, or 63 cents a share, up from $625.7 million, or 56
cents per share, a year ago. Results beat Wall Street analysts'
expectations by two cents, according to First Call/Thompson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose to $2.54 billion from $2.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Prozac, which makes up nearly a quarter of Lilly's
revenues, rose 1 percent in the quarter to $596.2 million from
$589.9 million. Sales of the depression drug rose 2 percent in the
United States but plummeted by 35 percent overseas due to generic
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Zyprexa, a schizophrenia medicine, rose 14 percent to
$458.1 million from $401.2 million. In March, the Food and Drug
Administration approved the drug for the treatment of manic
depression.
</P>
<P>
   The Indianapolis-based company's diabetes products, including
the pill Actos and insulin Humulin, rose 53 percent to $392 million
from $256.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the cancer drug Gemzar rose 19 percent to $136 million
$from $114.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two one-time events in the quarter were the company realizing a
$214 million profit from the sale of claims processing firm Kinetra
to Healtheon/WebMD. In addition, about $91 million of sales that
normally would have been realized during the first quarter of 2000
were realized during the fourth quarter of 1999 due to Y2K-related
wholesaler buying.
</P>
<P>
   Including these events, sales increased 13 percent to $2.54
billion and operating income increased 16 percent to $874.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly stock rose $2.56\ to $70 in trading at 4:30 p.m. Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
