<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Details Looted Jewish Assets  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Calling the extent of wartime looting ''stunning,''
France on Monday acknowledged that $1.3 billion in assets was
confiscated from Jews during World War II -- including 50,000
businesses -- but that most property and money was returned to
survivors or their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000-page report, prepared by a special government
commission and headed by former French resistance fighter Jean
Matteoli, is France's answer to charges that the nation has been
unwilling to face its own role in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The report outlined the collaborationist Vichy regime's
systematic looting of Jewish property -- from bank accounts and
insurance policies to art works and pianos -- as well as postwar
restitution policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We discovered that the extent of the looting was far greater
than we thought, but the good news is that restitutions after the
war were also greater than we had thought,'' historian Claire
Andrieu told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Of the bank accounts dormant since 1945, only 5 percent have not
found their rightful owners or heirs, Andrieu said, adding that the
commission studied the banking situation ''account by account.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission Vice President Ady Steg said about $294 million in
assets was never returned to the rightful owners. The commission
has recommended that the funds go toward creating a Holocaust
foundation in France.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an important moment when our country can look lucidly
at part of its past,'' said Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, adding
that he agreed in principle with the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Three years in the making, the report distinguished between the
widespread confiscation of Jewish property by Vichy, eager to keep
French-owned assets in France, and Nazi looting.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazis emptied some 30,000 Jewish apartments, shipping the
contents to Germany. They also seized valuable art works owned by
Jewish dealers and collectors in a plan established long before the
1940 invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Matteoli said it was ''profoundly revolting'' that the Vichy
government as early as 1940 took ''measures that went beyond what
the Nazis demanded.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is something we did not want to hide,'' he told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Vichy's anti-Jewish measures banned Jews from many professions
and owning businesses. Bank accounts were frozen, insurance
policies and stock certificates were confiscated. Some 50,000
Jewish-owned companies were ''aryanized'' -- turned over to
non-Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Jews interned at French-run transit camps before being
transferred to Auschwitz were stripped of all personal possessions.
Their valuables were sold, and the proceeds were then turned over
to the French national deposit bank, which holds the funds today.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most stunning aspect of our findings is the extent of the
looting,'' historian Annette Wieviorka told The Associated Press.
''Every Jew in France was affected, from the poorest tailor to the
richest art collector.''
</P>
<P>
   About 76,000 Jews, including 12,000 children -- about a quarter
of the Jews living in France -- were deported from France to Nazi
death camps between 1941-44. Only about 2,500 survived.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that of the 2,000 unclaimed art works
looted by the Nazis and recovered in Germany after the war -- and
currently held by France's National Museums Authority, only 163
were seized from Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The report proposed that several art works with no known heirs
be donated to the Israeli Museum in Jerusalem as testimony to the
Nazi looting, and that the remainder become part of the French
national collections.
</P>
<P>
   The commission continues to handle individual claims for
restitution, and about 4,500 requests have been received so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1801 </TRAILER>
