<HEADLINE> RJ Reynolds Earnigs Top Expectations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Increased cigarette sales helped R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Holdings post a 5 percent increase in earnings in
the first quarter, beating Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second biggest tobacco company earned $80 million,
or 77 cents a diluted share, up from $76 million, or 70 cents a
share, from ongoing operations in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The latest results, helped by a 14 percent increase in sales of
Reynolds' cigarette brands and an active share repurchase program,
were ahead of analysts' consensus expectations. Analysts forecast
earnings of 74 cents per share for the first quarter, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds shares rose 62{ cents to $18.68} in trading Monday at
4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Net sales for the quarter were $1.92 billion, up 14 percent from
$1.69 billion for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing operations figures for a year ago exclude onetime
items related to last year's sale of international tobacco
operations and Reynolds' spinoff from RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of Winston, Camel and Salem cigarettes began operating
on its own in June after being spun off from RJR Nabisco Holdings
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Tobacco's volume for the first quarter was 23 billion units,
up 2.9 percent from 22.4 billion units in the first quarter of
1999. The company attributed the increased volume to shifts in
wholesale and retail buying patterns, rather than to an increase in
cigarette consumption.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Tobacco's retail share of market through February was 23.5
percent, reflecting a slight decline from its fourth-quarter 1999
share of 23.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
