<HEADLINE> US, India Seek To Boost Cooperation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and India entered into an
agreement Monday to create a forum to promote economic cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and India's Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha, who was here to attend the spring meetings of the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, signed the pact,
which calls for officials from both countries to meet periodically
to discuss, among other things, financial developments and
investment issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''Strengthening our economic and financial relationship through
dialogue is critical to developing a closer, deeper, multifaceted
relationship with India,'' Summers said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement grew out of discussions Summers, while visiting
New Dehli in January, had with Sinha. The idea also was discussed
at a March meeting between President Clinton and India's Prime
Minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
