<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convictions in Israeli Bridge Fall  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Five Israelis were convicted Monday in
the death of four Australian athletes who were killed when a
rickety footbridge collapsed at the beginning of the 1997 Maccabiah
games, known as the Jewish Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The court blamed the chairman of the Maccabiah, the engineer who
built the bridge, the director of the company that staged the event
and two contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Elterman, the father of 18-year-old Australian Sasha
Elterman, who ingested a poisonous fungus from the polluted river
she and the others were dumped into, said he was pleased with the
verdict. After more than 30 operations, Elterman remains seriously
ill, her father said.
</P>
<P>
   In an Olympics-like opening ceremony on July 14, 1997,
delegations of athletes were supposed to enter the main stadium by
crossing the footbridge over the polluted Yarkon River. With the
Austrian and Australian athletes waiting on the bridge, it suddenly
buckled, dumping them into the water. Four died and 64 were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict blamed the defendants for using a traditional
Israeli ''trust me'' method of bypassing procedures and
regulations. Each level assured the one below that the bridge
construction was being carried out properly, but no one checked.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the bridge was thrown up in less than a month with no
blueprint, no foundation and inadequate materials. It was designed
by an engineer who had never crafted a similar bridge before,
constructed by a contractor who had no experience in building
bridges and supervised by no one, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mordechai Peled said, ''Allowing a contractor to work
without supervision is like telling a student that his teacher will
not check his work.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges heaped scorn on project engineer Micha Bar-Ilan,
noting that he has a doctorate in engineering and lectures at a
university, yet he built a bridge that was doomed to collapse and
did not keep an eye on the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Bar-Ilan's lawyer, Avraham Landstein, said he would
''definitely'' appeal. Pre-sentencing arguments are to be heard May
11. The charges carry maximum 5-year prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that Yoram Eyal, the chairman of the Maccabiah
organizing committee, ''tested the bridge by jumping on it to see
if it swayed.'' According to regulations, the bridge should have
been ten times as strong as it was.
</P>
<P>
   The court convicted the Maccabiah games organizer and
contractors along with Eyal and Bar-Ilan on the same charges of
criminal negligence, drawing no distinction among them about
responsibility for the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Israeli courts have come under criticism for
blaming workers and clearing managers. In a case that set the
standard over a decade ago, a military court sent a gatekeeper to
prison after a guerrilla infiltrated an army base after landing
nearby in a hang glider, but cleared officers of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Australia, Colin Elterman said he
hoped that Maccabiah organizers would learn the lesson of the
verdict, ''that they will realize that they are morally
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyal told reporters in the courtroom that the tragedy was a
personal blow to him since he knew all the victims. ''I feel I hold
full responsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Israeli board members of the Maccabiah games said
they would suspend themselves until a meeting of the organization's
international body next month, Israel Television reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1819 </TRAILER>
