<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign finance reform bill heads to governor  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A bill that would use taxpayer dollars to
pay for political races and creates voluntary spending caps on
campaigns narrowly cleared a final legislative hurdle Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance reform bill passed the House 77-71 and
heads to Gov. John G. Rowland. Only one Republican voted for the
measure Monday. Three GOP senators voted for the bill last week.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani said the governor has not decided
whether he will sign the bill. Rowland had stipulated he would only
sign a bill that had bipartisan support
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill won't accomplish the dreams of its most ardent
admirers and it won't produce the nightmares its opponents say it
will,'' said Rep. Alex Knopp, D-Norwalk. ''It will move us a giant
step forward to campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans blasted the bill, saying it will drain millions of
dollars from the General Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe we should be using tax money to pay for
political speech,'' said House Minority Leader Robert Ward,
R-Northford. ''It is a mistake to begin to use tax dollars on
political campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would establish a Citizens Elections Fund to collect
cash to pay for campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The money would largely come from voluntary income and corporate
tax check-offs, drawing as much as $7.7 million from the General
Fund each year. With other donations, the fund is expected to raise
up to $9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gubernatorial candidates who raise $500,000 on their own would
qualify for public dollars if they agreed to spend no more than $6
million beginning in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates for other constitutional offices such as treasurer
and attorney general would get public funding if they raised
$75,000 on their own and capped their spending at $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   In 2004, voluntary spending limits would be set for House races
at $50,000; Senate races would be capped at $130,000. Critics say
the legislative caps are irrelevant because candidates historically
raise far less than those limits. Gov. Rowland had threatened to
veto any bill that did not include limits on legislative races.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, if only one candidate agrees to spending limits,
that person would receive taxpayer money matching every dollar over
the limit spent by the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The House earlier this month narrowly passed a similar bill that
capped gubernatorial races at $4 million. GOP lawmakers said that
voluntary limit was too low and was a political slap at Rowland,
who raised $6 million during his last election.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate then raised the voluntary cap to $6 million, and the
House OK'd that increase Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said the bill creates an unfair advantage to
incumbents and favored candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, gubernatorial candidates who win their party
endorsement would be eligible for $1.5 million of public financing.
Candidates who win 15 percent of the vote at the party's nominating
convention would receive $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The House defeated by one vote a Republican amendment that would
have made all candidates eligible for $1.5 million if they won
support from at least 15 percent of convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not fair,'' said Rep. Ronald San Angelo, R-Naugatuck,
''That's not equitable. It puts challengers at a three-to-one
disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of capping expenditures, opponents said the bill should
ban special interest money from organizations such as political
action committees, lobbyists and unions.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would does limit donations from private contributors
and business PACs.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform advocates applauded the bill Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not so sure the governor is going to veto this,'' said
Karen Hobert Flynn, executive director of Common Cause/Connecticut.
''We've tried to address Republican concerns with the bill, and
we've been successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 1824 </TRAILER>
