<HEADLINE> Afghan Water Shortage Is Critical  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR ZIA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- Abdul Nadir bowed his head and prayed
Monday for an end to a prolonged dry spell that has turned his
golden wheat fields into dry stubble.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over his fields on the western edge of the Afghan
capital of Kabul, the 65-year-old Nadir said there is little else
for him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be a tough year,'' he said, shaking his head. ''All
our hard labor is for nothing. We won't get a single morsel of
wheat from our fields because there is no water.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban religious army that rules 90 percent of Afghanistan
has been asking people to pray for rain, both in and around Kabul
and in southern Afghanistan, also hard hit by the dry spell.
</P>
<P>
   In Kandahar and Helmand provinces in the south, the World Food
Program has brought in tons of feed for dying cattle. Some
estimates say 60 percent of the cattle in the region have already
died as a result of water shortages.
</P>
<P>
   The drought is being blamed on light snowfall snow during winter
and no rain so far this spring. The Kabul River, which is usually
swollen this time of year, is dry. Two of the three dams that
provide water and power to Kabul are almost dry. The third one is
barely half-full.
</P>
<P>
   Some aid workers say the drought is the worst to hit Afghanistan
in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the worst in decades and these are just the initial
days of the drought,'' said Abdul Baqi Afzali, of the Danish
Committee for Aid to Afghan Refugees. ''People have yet to feel its
full effect. The crisis will become severe in the days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Without international aid, the drought could result in a famine,
he warned. More than 85 percent Afghanistan's population is
dependent on agriculture or cattle breeding.
</P>
<P>
   ''Agriculture production will fall sharply this year, increasing
Afghanistan's dependence on outside help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan is already heavily dependent on international aid.
More than half of Kabul's 750,000 people rely on food provided by
the United Nations and other international aid groups. Bakeries
have been set up throughout Kabul to provide subsidized bread to
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of war have compounded the problem for impoverished
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Almost 70 percent of our irrigation system is destroyed so
people rely on the rains,'' said Maulvi Ahmed Jan, the Taliban's
minister for water and power.
</P>
<P>
   International aid is needed to rebuild the irrigation systems,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign donors have been reluctant to invest in Afghanistan
because of the Taliban's harsh brand of Islamic law that bars women
from work and education, forces men to wear beards and outlaws all
light entertainment, including music and television.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need foreign help to rebuild our systems,'' said Jan. ''But
unfortunately it's not there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1835 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two DEA Agents on Leave During Probe  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN SKORNECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two Drug Enforcement Administration agents
have been taken off duty temporarily as investigators probe an
alleged bribery and obstruction of justice scam by two Miami men,
the agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The DEA spokesman Terry Parman denied the two agents -- Larry
Castillo and David Tinsley, both part of a DEA enforcement group in
Florida -- were suspended. He said the two agents are not accused of
any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pending further inquiry by our Office of Professional
Responsibility, the agents were placed on administrative leave.
They were basically asked to stay home (with pay),'' said Parman.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation involves an alleged scheme of two Miami men
who used their status as occasional informants for U.S. law
enforcement agencies to scam narcotics traffickers, possibly of
millions of dollars, according to an FBI affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says that the two men -- Baruch Jairo Vega and
Roman Hernando Suarez Lopez -- took money from indicted and
unindicted narcotics traffickers, and in return promised them they
could get federal agents to drop the charges or get their sentences
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ''According to sources who have spoken with several of these
drug traffickers, Vega and Suarez's fees have ranged from $6
million to $100 million,'' FBI agent John C. Jones claimed in the
March 22 affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit cites a witness who allegedly paid Vega and Suarez
$3.5 million for help in connection with his own indictment and
that of several family members.
</P>
<P>
   That witness, who was not identified in the affidavit, reported
that Vega said about 80 percent of the money typically was ''paid
to important people in Washington'' while Vega and Suarez kept the
rest, the affidavit says.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit provides no evidence of wrongdoing by Washington
or other law enforcement officials even as it recounts that
cooperating witness' tale of a meeting with four DEA agents and a
Miami police officer in a Panama hotel room in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''The meeting lasted several hours, during which the agents
discussed the procedures for the surrender and cooperation of the
(witness') indicted family members,'' Jones wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
