<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Drama Tops Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ''Rules of Engagement'' held its ground as
the No. 1 film in North American theaters, taking in $10.9 million
over its second weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The military court drama starring Samuel L. Jackson and Tommy
Lee Jones withstood the openings of four films, which took in a
combined $25.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Bullock's ''28 Days'' -- dealing with a party girl's
alcohol rehabilitation -- was second, earning $10.3 million in its
first weekend. The debut of the romantic triangle comedy ''Keeping
the Faith'' was third with $8.1 million. ''American Psycho'' opened
in seventh place with $4.96 million. The Paul Newman film ''Where
the Money Is'' was a disappointing 13th in its first three days
with $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Sixth Sense'' dropped out of the Top 20 after 37 weeks,
and $293 million in earnings. It was second among 1999 films behind
the ''Star Wars'' prequel's $431 million.
</P>
<P>
   The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through
Sunday, followed by distribution studio, gross, number of theater
locations, average receipts per location, total gross and number of
weeks in release, as compiled Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co.
Inc. and ACNielsen EDI Inc.
</P>
<P>
   1. ''Rules of Engagement,'' Paramount, $10.9 million, 3,190
