<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hespe releases preschool standards, child advocates say more isneeded  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Preschool standards released Monday are a
nice first step, but New Jersey's poorest school districts need
more help to set up court-ordered, quality preschools, some
educators and child advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't give a district any guidance on how to put together
high quality programs,'' Tom Dunn, superintendent of Elizabeth
schools, said of the 72-page document, ''Early Childhood Education
Program Expectations: Standards of Quality.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd say they're high on expectations and low on standards,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Trenton superintendent James Lytle, who was a member of the
committee that wrote the standards, said they provide districts
with the right amount of guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's meant to be a kind of curriculum and instructional
framework for teachers and early childhood program providers,''
said Lytle.
</P>
<P>
   The standards are a collection of goals and activities for
various subject areas, including art, music, science, language
arts, social development and foreign language.
</P>
<P>
   They include lists of ''expectations,'' such as ''All children
will develop self-confidence and self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   The standards also offer broad goals for creating a good
classroom environment and getting parents involved in their
preschoolers' education.
</P>
<P>
   Lytle said people who are disappointed in the standards have
another agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ''What they want is something that gives them more leverage for
squeezing the department and the state for additional funding,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner David Hespe said the document is a first
step toward guiding districts on creating high quality programs. He
promised more detailed direction.
</P>
<P>
   Hespe was meeting an April 17 deadline imposed by the state
Supreme Court in its latest ruling in the 30-year-old school
funding fight. That ruling required the commissioner to issue clear
standards for these court-ordered programs, which are being
developed in 30 of New Jersey's poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that providing poor children with quality
preschool is one of the best ways to ensure their success later in
school.
</P>
<P>
   In its last ruling in March, the court said the state is failing
to implement quality preschool programs. The justices ordered
several changes to the state's plan, including moving up the
deadline for having certified preschool teachers from 2004 to 2001.
The court also ordered the state to reduce permissible class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that ruling, districts can submit revised
preschool plans -- and request additional funding -- by May.
</P>
<P>
   But David Sciarra, director of the Education Law Center, which
represents poor children in the school funding fight, said the new
standards fail to meet the court's first requirement and they give
the districts no guidance for creating new plans.
</P>
<P>
   He said the standards lack guidance on teacher quality,
facilities, health and social services and transportation. Without
that guidance, the districts can't submit revised plans by May.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court called for substantive guidance so districts could
revise preschool plans to reach uniform, high quality programs,''
Sciarra said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All these expectations are fine, but if you don't have the
teachers you need, adequate space, supplies, support staff,
transportation and all the other ingredients that are necessary,
then children are not going to have the chance to learn them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra also noted that Gov. Christie Whitman's proposed budget
includes no new state money for preschool programs. She is tapping
into $69 million in federal welfare funds that will go primarily to
daycare centers providing preschool to many of the estimated 50,000
eligible children.
</P>
<P>
   Ceil Zalkind, associate director of the Association for Children
of New Jersey, also said the state needs to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ''They describe what to do, but not how to get there,'' said
Zalkind. ''This is the first real program content document and, in
that regard, I think it's good. It is clearly not an implementation
guide to assist districts. There's still an enormous amount of
confusion for districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Zalkind said some key unanswered questions are: Do districts
provide transportation? How do they assess the quality of a child
care program? How are daycare centers going to get teachers
certified in time to meet the court's deadline? Who's going to pay
for it?
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the basics and they're not getting those questions
answered,'' said Zalkind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
