<HEADLINE> Italian Leader Rejects Resignation  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCES D'EMILIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Italy's president on Monday rejected an offer by
Premier Massimo D'Alema to resign, a day after his center-left
forces suffered a stinging blow in regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at the presidential palace, President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi told D'Alema to put his political fate in parliament's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will now take my proposal (to resign) to parliament, because
I believe that's the politically sensitive thing to do, because I
have to take into account the success of the opposition in these
elections, and this opposition has long said that this government
should resign,'' D'Alema said after emerging from his talks with
the head of state at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   Senate officials said debate would likely start in the upper
chamber on Wednesday but that the exact schedule would be announced
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As head of state, Ciampi can dissolve parliament or ask for a
confidence vote to test the 18-month-old center-left coalition's
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be a mistake to dissolve parliament now,
because the country needs stability at this moment,'' D'Alema said.
</P>
<P>
   The victorious conservative opposition led by media mogul and
former Premier Silvio Berlusconi earlier in the day pressed for
parliamentary elections soon. The elections must be held by spring
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi's alliance won eight of the 15 regional races in
Sunday's balloting, while D'Alema's forces captured seven. Some 30
million of Italy's 56 million people voted.
</P>
<P>
   Every day D'Alema is in office ''is an affront to the popular
sovereignty,'' said Gianfranco Fini, whose formerly neo-fascist
National Alliance is a key member of Berlusconi's alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives scored big, sweeping the affluent north, in
part thanks to a campaign marriage with Umberto Bossi's Northern
League.
</P>
<P>
   Bossi, an undependable coalition partner, helped bring down
Berlusconi's conservative government in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right's victory weakened D'Alema's prospects for
heading the center-left ticket in the next general election.
</P>
<P>
   ''How long can you govern knowing you have more than half the
country against you?'' asked the Rome daily, Il Messaggero.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly smarting defeat was the loss of Lazio, the region
which includes Rome. The regional presidency was won by the
spokesman for Fini's party, Francesco Storace.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema's Democratic Left kept its hold on central regions.
</P>
<P>
   His coalition ranges from hardline Communists to Greens to
former Communists to the former Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Pietro Folena, second-in-command of the Democratic Left, said
Berlusconi had successfully ''demonized the left'' during the
campaign and turned issues like crime and immigration to the
right's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives have called for tougher crackdowns on crime
and stricter controls on immigration.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear why the conservatives did well at
the center-left's expense. The campaigning had dealt little with
issues and instead was dominated by mudslinging by national
politicians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 1937 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
