<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, April 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protests End Amicably, IMF Meets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though demonstrators disrupted the government's workday
and private business in a big swath of the capital, they failed to shut down the
two days of meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. About
600 people were arrested today, bringing the total to more than 1,300 since the
protests began. The protesters accused the bank and IMF of imposing crushing
debts on poor nations, destroying the environment and perpetrating a host of
other ills. World Bank spokeswoman Caroline Ansety said officials in the
meetings felt ''bewilderment and surprise at the degree of anger'' outside. She
said the officials were talking about ways to relieve poverty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sale of Destroyers to Taiwan Nixed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior U.S. official said President Clinton today
decided against the sale of four Aegis destroyers to Taiwan, but approved the
sale of a long-range radar designed to detect missile launches, and a weapons
package that includes help in integrating $18 billion worth of weapons Taiwan
has already bought. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Clinton acted on the recommendation of top advisers who met earlier in the day
at the White House. The decision could touch off a fight with Congress, where
support for Taiwan and its growing democratic trends is strong, especially in
light of menacing gestures by Beijing toward the island.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 276; Nasdaq Gains 217
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Big-name stocks pushed higher again this afternoon, but most
shares remained lower in nervous trading following last week's freefall. At the
close of the regular session, the Dow industrials were up 276.74 to 10,582.51.
On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,725-1,310. The Nasdaq had its biggest
one-day point gain ever, rising 217.87 to 3,539.16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Ruling Awaited in Elian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- On the 39th anniversary of the Bay of Pigs fiasco, Cuban exiles
today stood watch at the home where Elian Gonzalez's relatives waited for a key
ruling in the custody fight. Protesters recalled the disastrous and deadly
attempt on April 17, 1961, in which CIA-trained exiles failed to invade Cuba.
Their criticism was extended to the Clinton administration, which wants the
6-year-old Cuban boy returned to his Cuban father. The boy's Miami relatives say
he will have a better life here. Both sides were awaiting a ruling from the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. The government wants the court to lift
an order that bars Elian's removal from the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush: Tax Plan To Benefit Poor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Flanked by single mothers and working families,
George W. Bush argued today that the real winners in his $438 billion tax-cut
package are those ''living on the outskirts of poverty.'' The Texas governor
used the focus on tax-filing deadline day to argue that fewer issues offer a
starker contrast with Gore than taxes, and to claim that his package focuses on
blue-collar workers. ''What's risky is overtaxing the people who work for a
living in America,'' said Bush, who criticized Gore for not convincing fellow
Democrats in Congress to get rid of the so-called tax marriage penalty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rwanda Elects Tutsi as President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- A former rebel leader whose forces stopped the 1994
genocide was chosen on Monday as president of Rwanda, the nation's first Tutsi
leader since independence in 1962. Paul Kagame, 43, who previously had rejected
the top post out of fear of antagonizing the Hutu majority, was chosen president
by the Parliament and the Cabinet in an 81-5 secret ballot. Kagame was slated to
be sworn in Saturday by the Supreme Court as Rwanda's fifth president since
independence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Environmentalism Supported
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans don't consider the environment a top political
priority, says a new Gallup Poll, but they are broadly supportive of the
environmental movement three decades after the first Earth Day. The poll
indicated that one in six people are active with the environmental movement.
Four of five said they're sympathetic to the goals of the environmental
movement. Support in the polls for the environmental movement peaked about 10
years ago, after events like the Exxon Valdez oil spill, discussion of global
warming and the discovery of medical waste on beaches caught public attention.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kenyans Win Boston Marathon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Kenya's domination of the Boston Marathon extended to a record
10 consecutive victories today, as Elijah Lagat outkicked Ethiopia's Gezahenge
Abera and Kenya's Moses Tanui in the closest finish in the race's 104-year
history. Catherine Ndereba made it a Kenyan sweep, winning the women's race in
another close finish. Lagat won in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 47 seconds to break the
tape a stride ahead of Abera, who was second in the same time.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
