<DOCNO> APW20000417.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Seeks 'Smarter' Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Confronted with a mixed record in the
success of U.N. sanctions, the Security Council took the first
steps Monday toward making embargoes more effective and less
harmful to civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Council members announced they would set up a special working
group to recommend ways of making sanctions ''smarter'' by
targeting them better against regimes and enforcing them more.
</P>
<P>
   The move was aimed at answering mounting criticism that U.N.
sanctions, which are increasingly being used as an alternative to
military force, have often gone ignored in the past 10 years --
particularly in the case of arms embargoes on Rwanda, Liberia and
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   When enforced, they have often hurt innocents more than the
regimes they were intended for, such as the case of sanctions on
Iraq and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Those conclusions were highlighted by an independent analysis of
U.N. embargoes, ''The Sanctions Decade: Assessing U.N. Strategies
in the 1990s,'' which was launched Monday at a symposium and
discussed at length in an open meeting of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan told the symposium that the mixed
success had raised ''serious doubts'' about U.N. sanctions'
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in some cases not only transfer hardships onto their
people, ''but perversely often benefit from such sanctions by their
ability to profit from black market activity, by controlling the
distribution of the limited resources, and by exploiting them as
pretext for eliminating domestic sources of political opposition,''
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   The move to review of sanctions comes at a critical time for the
council, which is now negotiating a resolution to tackle violations
of sanctions against Angola's UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassadors are also dealing with the continued dilemma of
sanctions against Iraq, which has been under an embargo for nearly
10 years -- the most comprehensive of the 12 regimes imposed this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   French Ambassador Jean-David Levitte told the council that Iraq
sanctions had largely achieved Baghdad's disarmament. But Levitte
said they had been so extended that the human cost ''manifestly
outweighs the benefits the council can expect.''
</P>
<P>
   France, which has advocated a suspension of sanctions against
Iraq, suggested embargoes have a specific duration, which could
only be extended by council action. That mechanism would enable any
of the veto-wielding members to block attempts to continue the
measures, a clear critique of efforts by the United States to
maintain sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Ambassador James Cunningham said it may be possible
in some cases to link suspension or a relaxation of sanctions to
changed behavior of the targeted state.
</P>
<P>
   But he stressed that ''once sanctions have been imposed, it is
essential to place the burden of proof regarding their suspension
or termination where it properly belongs: on the demonstrated
behavior of the sanctioned entity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2017 </TRAILER>
