<DOCNO> APW20000417.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colonel Pleads Guilty in Drug Case  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An Army colonel who once commanded the
military's anti-drug operation in Colombia pleaded guilty to a
federal charge Monday, admitting that he knew his wife was
laundering drug money but failed to turn her in.
</P>
<P>
   James Hiett, 48, entered the plea as his wife, Laurie Hiett,
sank her face into her hands and sobbed from a bench in the first
row of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   He faces up to three years in prison and $250,000 in fines when
he is sentenced June 23. Federal sentencing guidelines call for him
to spend between one year and one and a half years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Hiett said that in April and May 1999, his wife traveled from
Bogota, Colombia to New York City twice and returned home with more
than $25,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   In early June 1999, he said he was told by Army investigators
that his wife had been sending narcotics from Colombia to New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prior to that time I did not know my wife was involved in
narcotics trafficking,'' he said. ''I then knew that the cash my
wife had previously given me came from drug trafficking.''
</P>
<P>
   In June and July, after he knew of his wife's drug activities,
he tried to get rid of the money and failed to tell law enforcement
authorities about the cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''I then took the steps to dissipate this cash by paying as many
bills as possible in cash and depositing the rest of the cash in
our bank accounts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Laurie Hiett pleaded guilty to drug conspiracy
charges, admitting she shipped packages containing $700,000 worth
of drugs to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   After his plea, Hiett hugged his wife and left the courthouse
holding her hand.
</P>
<P>
   The couple paused to allow their picture to be taken and were
asked how their marriage was holding up. ''Great,'' Laurie Hiett
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Hiett, a 24-year Army veteran, remains on active duty at Fort
Monroe, in Hampton, Va., where he was transferred after his wife
was accused of a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Lee G. Dunst said Hiett has filed for
retirement from the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Army Criminal Investigation Division in Panama had
cleared Hiett, saying he had ''no prior knowledge'' of his wife's
crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2032 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000417.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI arrests former Grand Union executive in $2 millionembezzlement  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Hours before he and his wife were to board a
plane for Brazil, a longtime executive at Grand Union was arrested
Monday, accused of embezzling $2 million from the supermarket chain
over eight years.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents searching the Park Ridge home of Donald C.
Vaillancourt found round-trip tickets indicating that the Bergen
County man and his wife were leaving Monday night for Rio de
Janeiro, Assistant U.S. Attorney Vaughn McKoy said in seeking $2
million bail.
</P>
<P>
   McKoy said agents also found $55,000 in cash at the home.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate G. Donald Haneke ordered Vaillancourt, 56, held
on $600,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Vaillancourt's lawyer, Robert Reed, declined to comment after
the bail hearing. The former executive attended in a black leather
jacket and slacks, shackled at the wrists and ankles. He spoke only
to acknowledge the charges.
</P>
<P>
   His 29-year Grand Union career ended in February as part of a
downsizing, the Wayne-based company said. At the time of his
dismissal, Vaillancourt, a lawyer, held the posts of vice
president, public affairs counsel, and corporate secretary, Grand
Union said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaillancourt was among 30 people let go at headquarters just
three days after the chain fired its chairman, and its vice
chairman resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The upheaval followed last year's third-quarter loss of $35.6
million, 25 percent more than a year earlier. The company emerged
from bankruptcy court protection in August, its second Chapter 11
filing in five years.
</P>
<P>
   After Vaillancourt's termination, the company uncovered
wrongdoing and notified the U.S. attorney's office for New Jersey,
said a lawyer for Grand Union, Michael Chertoff, himself a former
U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   While at the company, Vaillancourt had the authority to approve
payments to vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the scheme outlined by McKoy and the FBI, from 1991-99,
Vaillancourt opened post boxes and bank accounts in the names of
Grand Union vendors, submitted false invoices on vendor stationery,
and then approved the payments, which were sent to the postal
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The mail fraud charge filed by the FBI carries up to five years
in prison and a $1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Union said that any embezzled funds will not hurt its
financial statements, because the funds already were accounted as
expenses in prior statements.
</P>
<P>
   The company will seek to recover embezzled funds, said Grand
Union, which operates 217 stores in Connecticut, New Hampshire, New
Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania and Vermont.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-17-00 2033 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
