<HEADLINE> Barak Readies Israel for Concessions  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak told the Israeli
people Monday they should prepare for a Palestinian entity that
would comprise a solid bloc of land abutting Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Israel Television timed for the Passover
holiday, Barak made his case to the public for what he told his
Cabinet over the weekend -- that Israel would hand over West Bank
land to give the Palestinians territorial contiguity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It needs to be clear to us that what will emerge from an
agreement is not a limited autonomy or a protectorate,'' Barak
said. ''There will not be good neighborliness between the two
countries if one of them is collection of islands on a map.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak also suggested that the Palestinians would receive West
Bank suburbs bordering contested Jerusalem, though he insisted
Jerusalem would remain united and under Israel's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Jewish settlements would also be kept under the
country's control.
</P>
<P>
   In his report to the Cabinet on Sunday, Barak came closer than
ever to conceding the inevitability of Palestinian statehood. But
the Palestinians say he is not going far enough, and have continued
to demand all of the Gaza Strip, West Bank and east Jerusalem,
captured in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, President Clinton will meet with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, a Palestinian human rights group accused Jewish
settlers of attacking and trying to kill a 71-year old Palestinian
woman.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Thahab al-Najjar, from the village of Borin outside
of the northern West Bank city of Nablus, told the Palestinian
Society for the Protection of Human Rights and the Environment that
settlers had tried to stab her with a knife and bury her alive
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rafi Yafe, a spokesman for the Israeli police, said an
investigation has been launched but at the time no suspects had
been identified. Yafe said al-Najjar was lightly injured in the
incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
