<HEADLINE> Chicago Janitors Hold 24-hour Strike  </HEADLINE>
By MARIO FOX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Thousands of janitors who work at downtown office
buildings went on a 24-hour walkout Monday to protest a lack of
progress in their contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Munz, spokesman for Local 1 of the Service Employees
International Union, said janitors have seen their pay decrease
over the last eight years compared to the cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   Their salary of $10.10 an hour in 1992 has only increased to
$11.40, $1.10 short of keeping up with the cost of living during
that period, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wage they are offering this time is again below the cost
of living,'' Munz said. ''Also, the janitors are working harder and
harder each year as retirees are not being replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Building Owners and Managers Association, which is
negotiating with the union, released a statement saying ''it is
most unfortunate that our janitors, their families and building
tenants have been hurt by these actions and we hope for a speedy
resolution to minimize their suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The janitors' contract expired at midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout affects some 200 buildings and 5,500 workers,
hundreds of whom attended an afternoon rally outside the downtown
building where the contract talks were being held. Then they
marched to other union-serviced buildings in the Loop business
district to bring attention to their cause as office workers headed
for home.
</P>
<P>
   Janitors in the suburbs are threatening to walk off their jobs
if negotiations with a mediator fail to make any headway Tuesday.
Their contract expired April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is the latest city to see labor unrest among janitors.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of commercial building janitors are on strike in Los
Angeles, seeking wage increases and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say similar labor unrest could occur in other
cities, including New York, Cleveland, Detroit and Philadelphia,
where union janitor contracts are due to expire this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
