<HEADLINE> Women's Soccer Team Back On Field  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHULA VISTA, Calif. (AP) -- Although their uniforms had no
numbers on them, Mia Hamm, Brandi Chastain and some of their
teammates were identified easily.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm and Chastain, who starred on the 1999 Women's World Cup
championship team, were among 15 returning players who took part in
Monday's opening practice of the Olympic residency camp for the
U.S. women's national team.
</P>
<P>
   Joining them at the ARCO Olympic Training Center for the start
of extended preparation for the Sydney Olympics were 15 others
looking for spots on the final 18-member roster.
</P>
<P>
   ''Definitely this turns up the heat,'' said Chastain, who scored
the Cup-winning goal in a shootout against China, then stripped off
her jersey in celebration. ''The kitchen's getting a little hotter.
When you get out to the training center, it's hard not to feel the
anticipation and excitement of the Olympics with all these great
athletes surrounding you.''
</P>
<P>
   The team will remain at the center before heading to the U.S.
Women's Cup tournament starting May 5 in Portland, Ore., then
return for more training before defending the gold medal it won at
the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The United States won the World Cup at a sold-out Rose Bowl. On
Monday, there were about 50 onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was no doubting the carryover effect that remains
from the World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is more visibility and more responsibility. Everyone's
going to be watching and that's great,'' said Hamm, the U.S.
women's career leader with 117 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the things that we pride ourselves on as a team is the
way that we represent ourselves. When we are out there training, we
don't cut corners and we work extremely hard.''
</P>
<P>
   New coach April Heinrichs, a former team captain, repeatedly
encouraged players during the opening two-hour practice by
shouting, ''That's the kind of aggression that I love.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The attitude is established by the players,'' said Heinrichs,
who succeeded Tony DiCicco after the World Cup. ''They are highly
motivated and bring that work ethic to the field every day. We are
putting an extra emphasis on competitiveness and how to show it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team, which has all 11 starters back from the World Cup
final, is 7-2-2 this year without the benefit of extended team
training.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before a tournament, you only have four or five days together,
and there's only so much that you can work on and also look at the
opponent,'' Hamm said. ''But this is an opportunity to focus on us
as a team. Both as a group and individuals, we can sharpen our
skills and get our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs said she's in no hurry to make roster cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to bring (new) players along as long as we can,''
she said. ''We want them to get experience with world-class
players. We're looking at that in terms of our long-term future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
