<SUBHEAD>
Gephardt Expected To Nix China Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt is expected to
announce on Wednesday he will vote against hotly contested legislation granting
permanent normalized trade relations with China, Democratic officials said
today. These officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Gephardt,
D-Mo., had informed senior White House officials of his decision. Clinton favors
the measure, as do members of the Republican leadership in the House. In
opposing the legislation, Gephardt would side with the majority of his own
Democratic caucus. A close vote is expected on the legislation when the House
votes sometime next month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IMF Meets Despite Disruptive Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though demonstrators disrupted the government's workday in
a big swath of the capital, they failed to shut down the two days of meetings of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. About 600 people were arrested
today, bringing the total to more than 1,300 since the protests began. The
protesters accused the bank and IMF of imposing crushing debts on poor nations,
destroying the environment and perpetrating a host of other ills. World Bank
spokeswoman Caroline Ansety said officials in the meetings felt ''bewilderment
and surprise at the degree of anger'' outside. She said the officials were
talking about ways to relieve poverty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court: Baggage Squeeze OK Needed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police officers must get travelers' consent or a court
warrant before squeezing their luggage to see if drugs might be inside, the
Supreme Court ruled today in an expansion of public transit passengers' privacy
rights. The 7-2 decision in a Texas case said a U.S. Border Patrol agent who
felt a bus passenger's bag violated the Constitution's Fourth Amendment ban on
unreasonable searches. The bag later was found to contain drugs. The National
Association of Police Organizations said it was disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Won't Sell Destroyers to Taiwan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior U.S. official said President Clinton today
decided against the sale of four Aegis destroyers to Taiwan, but approved the
sale of a long-range radar designed to detect missile launches, and a weapons
package that includes help in integrating $18 billion worth of weapons Taiwan
has already bought. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Clinton acted on the recommendation of top advisers who met earlier in the day
at the White House. The decision could touch off a fight with Congress, where
support for Taiwan and its growing democratic trends is strong, especially in
light of menacing gestures by Beijing toward the island.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Readies Israel for Concessions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak told the Israeli people Monday
they should prepare for a Palestinian entity that would comprise a solid bloc of
land abutting Jerusalem. In an interview with Israel Television timed for the
Passover holiday, Barak made his case to the public for what he told his Cabinet
over the weekend -- that Israel would hand over West Bank land to give the
Palestinians territorial contiguity. Barak also suggested that the Palestinians
would receive West Bank suburbs bordering contested Jerusalem, though he
insisted Jerusalem would remain united and under Israel's sovereignty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 276; Nasdaq Gains 217
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Big-name technology stocks sprang back to life Monday,
driving the Nasdaq composite index to a record point gain, as investors mustered
some confidence to hunt for bargains in the wreckage of last week's selling
frenzy. At the close of the regular session, the Dow industrials were up 276.74
to 10,582.51. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,725-1,310. The Nasdaq had
its biggest one-day point gain ever, rising 217.87 to 3,539.16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tribal Whale Hunt Begins in Wash.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEAH BAY, Wash. (AP) -- A Makah whaling family set out today in the tribe's
first gray whale hunt of the spring, but the crew returned late in the day
without killing a whale. The Coast Guard arrested two protesters. While tribal
leaders insist the seasonal hunt -- a centuries-old tradition that resumed after
a 70 years absence with the first kill in May -- is vital to preserving the
Makah identity, anti-whaling activists fear it could open the door to a
worldwide renewal of commercial whaling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kenyans Sweep Boston Marathon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Kenya's domination of the Boston Marathon extended to a record
10 consecutive victories today, as Elijah Lagat outkicked Ethiopia's Gezahenge
Abera and Kenya's Moses Tanui in the closest finish in the race's 104-year
history. Catherine Ndereba made it a Kenyan sweep, winning the women's race in
another close finish. Lagat won in 2 hours, 9 minutes, 47 seconds to break the
tape a stride ahead of Abera, who was second in the same time.
</P>
