<HEADLINE> Peru Candidate Demands Fair Play  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo on
Monday urged President Alberto Fujimori and his supporters to
ensure a clean vote count in the upcoming runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori fell less than 2 percentage points short of the
majority he needed to claim a third term victory last week, after a
first round election tainted by irregularities and accusations of
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates will face off in a second round showdown in
late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said the balloting must have ''credibility in the eyes of
the world and in the eyes of Peruvians to dispel any question about
the results, whatever they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo called for an end to what he called stepped-up personal
attacks against him and his family on mostly pro-government
television networks, and he demanded equal access to TV stations to
present his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Tudela, Fujimori's vice presidential candidate and a
former foreign minister, said Monday that the government would try
to increase vote monitoring as well as encourage more equitable
media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls during the April 9 election and unofficial tallies by
independent monitors had indicated Fujimori would not reach the 50
percent plus one vote needed to win. But after an unexplained
12-hour delay, the first official returns showed Fujimori on track
to claim a first-round victory, prompting suspicions of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's supporters protested and much of the international
community added its voice, all but insisting on a second round.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials took three days to determine Fujimori had
fallen short of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has denied that election rigging occurred and has
downplayed mounting irregularities, saying they had no significant
impact on the vote outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
