<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Grand Union Executive Arrested  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Hours before he and his wife were to board a
plane for Brazil, a longtime executive at Grand Union was arrested
Monday, accused of embezzling $2 million from the supermarket chain
over eight years, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents searching the Park Ridge home of Donald C.
Vaillancourt found round-trip tickets indicating the Bergen County
man and his wife were leaving Monday night for Rio de Janeiro,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Vaughn McKoy said in seeking $2 million
bail.
</P>
<P>
   McKoy said agents also found $55,000 in cash at the home.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate G. Donald Haneke ordered Vaillancourt, 56, held
on $600,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Vaillancourt's lawyer, Robert Reed, declined to comment after
the bail hearing, where Vaillancourt spoke only to acknowledge the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   His 29-year Grand Union career ended in February as part of a
downsizing and management shakeup, the Wayne-based company said. At
the time of his dismissal, Vaillancourt, a lawyer, held the posts
of vice president, public affairs counsel, and corporate secretary,
Grand Union said.
</P>
<P>
   After Vaillancourt's termination, the company uncovered
wrongdoing and notified the U.S. attorney's office for New Jersey,
said Michael Chertoff, a lawyer for Grand Union, Michael Chertoff.
</P>
<P>
   While at the company, Vaillancourt had the authority to approve
payments to vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the scheme outlined by McKoy and the FBI, from 1991-99,
Vaillancourt opened post boxes and bank accounts in the names of
Grand Union vendors, submitted false invoices on vendor stationery,
and then approved the payments, which were sent to the postal
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The mail fraud charge filed by the FBI carries up to five years
in prison and a $1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Union said any embezzled funds will not hurt its financial
statements, because the funds already were accounted as expenses in
prior statements. The company said it will seek to recover the
embezzled money.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Union operates 217 stores in Connecticut, New Hampshire,
New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania and Vermont.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2115 </TRAILER>
