<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A rebound on Wall Street pushed Tokyo stocks
moderately higher early Tuesday after Monday's steep selloff. The
dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 226.96 points,
or 1.19 percent, to 19,235.60 in the first 30 minutes of trading.
On Monday, the average closed down a huge 1,426.04 points, or 6.98
percent after a record drop Friday on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.52 yen, up 1.16 yen from late Monday in
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 104.26 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index rose as Tokyo investors
were reassured by a strong showing on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose
276.74 points to 10,582.51 after a 617.78-point plunge on Friday.
The technology-rich Nasdaq composite soared 217.87 points to
3,589.16 at Monday's close after its 355.49-point slide on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 44.89 points, or 2.90 percent, to 1,597.35
percent. The TOPIX closed down 107.98 points, or 6.53 percent, the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa sought to calm
investors, saying early Tuesday that Japan's economic recovery
appears healthy enough that Monday's sharp plunge on the stock
market should have no impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the strength of Japan's recovery is quite strong, I'm
not that worried,'' Miyazawa told reporters, adding, however, that
he would be closely watching the U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's fall in the Nikkei was its fifth worst in both points
and percentage.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 98.98 yen, down from
99.51 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7300 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7050 percent. Its price
fell 0.23 point to 101.46.
</P>
</TEXT>
