<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Promotes Two in USDA Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A judge for the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission has ordered the Agriculture Department to promote two
black managers who were denied advancement because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Herron and Harold Connor, managers at the department's
Farm Service Agency, will receive promotions, four to five years of
back pay and $10,000 each for damages, the commission said in a
decision made public Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission in December dismissed a class-action claim by
more than 300 black Agriculture Department managers who said they
were denied promotions because of their race. Connor and Herron
were the only exceptions to the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ruling, dated April 14, denied the two managers most
of their requested damages, saying that they failed to prove they
suffered medical and emotional problems caused by the
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ''The judge did not consider the grave harm to their
professional reputations,'' said the Joseph D. Gebhardt, the
managers' attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The original class-action complaint was filed in 1997 against
the Farm Service Agency, which administers subsidy and loan
programs for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Other discrimination complaints by black, Hispanic and female
employees in the department are still pending before the
commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
