<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Father Talks About Athlete Daughter  </HEADLINE>
By MARTA W. ALDRICH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- In December, Kaia Jergenson was running
on the basketball court and hitting jump shots for Lipscomb
University.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she's using a wheelchair until she can be fitted for
prosthetic limbs.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2 freshman from nearby Gallatin, who averaged 12.5
points and 5.5 rebounds during her short career at Lipscomb, was
hospitalized Jan. 3 with a bacterial infection in her bloodstream.
Surgeons later amputated to remove dead tissue and muscle they said
threatened her life.
</P>
<P>
   With both legs gone below the knee, Jergenson is learning how to
shift from bed to a chair. And writing is another challenge for the
18-year-old pre-med student, with only her thumb and half of her
ring finger remaining on her writing hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a survivor,'' father Bert Jergenson said Monday in an
interview with The Associated Press. ''She keeps herself upbeat.
She has her days and her times when she's down, but it doesn't last
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaia (pronounced KYE'yuh) recovered from the meningococcal
disease and was transferred March 23 to the Rehabilitation
Institute of Chicago, where she is learning new skills with a
wheelchair and voice-activated computer and relearning some old
ones with her remaining fingers and limbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's out of shape and they've got to bring her back,'' her
father said in the first family interviews since Kaia went in the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever you stay in a hospital bed that long, no matter how
good a shape you're in, you lose a lot of muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   Jergenson recounted the long fearful days during his daughter's
illness, including the anguish of signing forms permitting doctors
to amputate if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were hoping it would only be the toes,'' he said. ''But the
worst-case scenario was above the knee. When the doctor came out
smiling and said it was below the knee, that was good news, even
though you normally wouldn't think of it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kaia regained consciousness about three weeks later, her
doctor and mother explained that part of her legs and fingers were
gone. But Jergenson believes his daughter already knew the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ''When she came out of her induced coma, she was reaching
around,'' he said. ''I think they more or less just confirmed what
she already knew.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Thomas Hospital in Nashville, Kaia received daily visits
from friends, teammates, coaches, teachers and pastors that
Jergenson believes helped his daughter come to grips with her new
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   He was concerned her spirits would dissipate when she arrived in
Chicago with only her mother, who is a physical therapist, for
support. But that worry was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ''That first Sunday, they got her into a wheelchair with a
joystick and went outside. That's when I realized she was going to
be OK -- that she could get around and meet people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaia's biggest physical challenge now is the numerous skin
grafts St. Thomas surgeons performed around the stumps on her legs
and on her thighs and arms.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have to heal, and only time will do that,'' Jergenson
said. ''And they can't fit her with prostheses until the skin
heals.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she is fitted, though, she will learn to walk again. She
hopes to return to Nashville in late May, and to school at Lipscomb
in August.
</P>
<P>
   Jergenson said it's the tenacity his daughter learned on the
basketball court, where she was MVP of the Tennessee prep
tournament in 1999, that likely will get her through the
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ''When she first started playing, she went into weight training
and couldn't even lift the bar,'' Jergenson said. ''She had to work
at it. She'll have to work at this, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And she has no plans to abandon the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think basketball will always be a part of her life,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
