<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, April 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Expands Passengers' Privacy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an expansion of public transit passengers' privacy
rights, the Supreme Court ruled today that police officers must get travelers'
consent or a court warrant before squeezing their luggage to see if drugs might
be inside. The 7-2 decision in a Texas case said a U.S. Border Patrol agent who
felt a bus passenger's bag violated the Constitution's Fourth Amendment ban on
unreasonable searches. The bag later was found to contain drugs. The National
Association of Police Organizations said it was disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IMF Meets Despite Disruptive Protests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though demonstrators disrupted the government's workday in
a big swath of the capital, they failed to shut down the two days of meetings of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. About 600 people were arrested
today, bringing the total to more than 1,300 since the protests began. The
protesters accused the bank and IMF of imposing crushing debts on poor nations,
destroying the environment and perpetrating a host of other ills. World Bank
spokeswoman Caroline Ansety said officials in the meetings felt ''bewilderment
and surprise at the degree of anger'' outside. She said the officials were
talking about ways to relieve poverty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Won't Sell Destroyers to Taiwan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior U.S. official said President Clinton today
decided against the sale of four Aegis destroyers to Taiwan, but approved the
sale of a long-range radar designed to detect missile launches, and a weapons
package that includes help in integrating $18 billion worth of weapons Taiwan
has already bought. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Clinton acted on the recommendation of top advisers who met earlier in the day
at the White House. The decision could touch off a fight with Congress, where
support for Taiwan and its growing democratic trends is strong, especially in
light of menacing gestures by Beijing toward the island.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Readies Israel for Concessions
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak told the Israeli people Monday
they should prepare for a Palestinian entity that would comprise a solid bloc of
land abutting Jerusalem. In an interview with Israel Television timed for the
Passover holiday, Barak made his case to the public for what he told his Cabinet
over the weekend -- that Israel would hand over West Bank land to give the
Palestinians territorial contiguity. Barak also suggested that the Palestinians
would receive West Bank suburbs bordering contested Jerusalem, though he
insisted Jerusalem would remain united and under Israel's sovereignty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A rebound on Wall Street pushed Tokyo stocks moderately higher
Tuesday in early trading. The Nikkei Stock Average rose 226.96 points to
19,235.60. At the close of the regular session, the Dow industrials were up
276.74 to 10,582.51. The Nasdaq had its biggest one-day point gain ever, rising
217.87 to 3,539.16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Laptop With Classified Info Missing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI is investigating the disappearance from the State
Department two months ago of a laptop computer that contained highly sensitive
information. A State official said the laptop was shared by several officials.
The Washington Post, quoting a person familiar with the incident, said the
missing computer contained ''code word'' information, a classification higher
than top secret. It also contained intelligence information and plans, the
person was quoted as saying.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Area 51 Images Said Posted on Web
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Photos of Area 51, the super-secret Air Force test site
in Nevada that has long tantalized UFO and conspiracy buffs, are being posted
online. Beginning with the U-2 spy plane in the 1950s, the base has been the
testing ground for a host of top-secret aircraft, including the B-2 stealth
bomber. Aerial Images Inc. of Raleigh planned to post five images of the site.
Aerial Images, at www.terraserver.com, planned to offer a link to the Area 51
pages. Viewing the images is free; downloading them costs $8.95 and up. Kodak
will print photographs for $20 to $30.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sale of Royals To Glass Approved
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Baseball owners voted unanimously today to approve the $96
million sale of the Kansas City Royals to team chairman David Glass. Glass took
over as Royals chairman in September 1993, shortly after the death of founding
owner Ewing Kauffman. Under Kauffman's succession plan, the team was offered for
sale to Kansas City-area individuals and companies, with the money earmarked for
charity. Glass is the former chief executive officer of Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
