<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Procter &AMP; Gamble Gets Drug Approval  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. has received federal
approval to market Actonel, its drug for prevention and treatment
of osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Actonel, which received Food and Drug Administration approval
Monday, faces some well-established competition in the lucrative
market, which is quickly expanding as the baby boom generation
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Merck &AMP; Co.'s Fosamax, also sold as a prevention and treatment
medication for osteoporosis, has been on the market five years. It
had sales of $1.06 billion last year and has been used by more than
3.5 million patients. And in September, the FDA approved Eli Lilly
&AMP; Co.'s Evista as an osteoporosis drug.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoporosis gradually weakens bones and often leads to painful
and debilitating fractures. Vertebral fractures can lead to stooped
posture, chronic pain or disability and can cause compression of
the lungs and stomach. Hip fractures can be life-threatening
because of possible complications. Twenty percent of those who
suffer hip fractures die within a year.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10 million U.S. women age 50 and older have the
disease, but fewer than one-quarter of those have been diagnosed
with it, Procter &AMP; Gamble spokesman Don Tassone said. Over the next
decade, 200 million women worldwide could be at risk to contract
the disease, according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Fosamax, the market leader, costs $1.69 per tablet at wholesale
rates, Merck spokeswoman Donna Cary said from the company's
headquarters in Whitehouse Station, N.J. P&AMP;G's goal is to set a
wholesale price that is 10 percent less than Fosamax, Tassone said.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G expects to start shipping Actonel, generically known as
risedronate, in the United States within three weeks. Since
February, the company has obtained market approval for the drug in
Sweden, the United Kingdom and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Tassone declined to say how much money P&AMP;G has spent in a decade
of developing Actonel. But, he said the spending is in line with
industry averages of $300 million-plus costs of getting a drug to
market approval from its first discovery.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G and partner Aventis Pharmaceuticals will co-market Actonel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2206 </TRAILER>
