<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Has 'Digital Divide' Plan  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIPROCK, N.M. (AP) -- Pushing to bring high-tech benefits to
places excluded from the nation's prosperity, President Clinton on
Monday promised $1-a-month telephone service to 300,000 American
Indian households to spread the power of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this day and age, when we want every American to have
access to the Internet, we must first make sure that every American
has access to a phone so there will be a line to hook into,''
Clinton told the Navajo Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back over a history of broken promises, Clinton also
said the federal government ''did not live up to its end of the
deal'' when Indians gave up fighting and surrendered their land in
return for peace, security, health care and education. ''That was
wrong,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke in this impoverished Navajo town after earlier
announcing more than $100 million in pledges from the computer
industry for hard-luck communities nationwide -- an effort to erase
the digital divide that separates poor and prosperous Americans in
technology's benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''In much of America it takes just a modest amount of money and
time to get someone on the Internet,'' Clinton told the Navajos.
''But here an astonishing 37 per cent of the households are without
electricity, about 70 percent without phone service, more than half
without work.''
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Clinton answered questions in an Internet
video conference with seventh- and eighth-grade students at Lake
Valley School, 150 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came to Shiprock -- named for a 1,700 foot geological
monument rising from the surrounding plains -- after a morning stop
in East Palo Alto, Calif., a pocket of poverty in technology-rich
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   More than 24 percent of youngsters in East Palo Alto live in
poverty and over 80 percent are eligible for the free-lunch
program. Schools have just one computer for every 28 students.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visits, along with a stop Tuesday at a computer show
in Chicago, were intended to dramatize the ''digital divide'' of
inequality between computer haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that new technologies like the Internet and wireless
communications can have an enormous positive impact on the Navajo
nation,'' the president said. ''They can help you to leapfrog over
some of the biggest hurdles to develop your economic and human
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   The president was sporting cowboy boots as he spoke in the
parking lot of the Boys and Girls Club in Shiprock. He was
introduced by 13-year-old Myra Jodie, who won a computer from a San
Jose-based website, but was unable to connect to the Internet
because she lives in a home with no telephone.
</P>
<P>
   American Indians rank far below the national average in their
access to telephones, computers and the Internet. The Navajo high
school dropout rate averages 20 percent for 9th graders, and only
one-quarter of adult Navajos have graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced a plan to provide basic telephone service to
American Indians for $1 a month. That would be financed by raising
universal service assessments on interstate and international
carriers by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, head of the president's National Economic
Council, said long-distance users would pay about a penny a month
more if carriers pass the charge on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In East Palo Alto, speaking at a community technology center
called Plugged In, Clinton said, ''We can truly move more people
out of poverty more rapidly than ever before. Or we can allow
access to new technology to heighten economic inequality and
sharpen social division. ... The choice is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a young boy about his own computer use, Clinton said,
''I confess I don't use it much for e-mail but that's for very
personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If you work for the government you don't use e-mail very much
unless you want it all in the newspapers,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has opened an investigation into the
White House failure to review thousands of e-mails that may have
been under subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined in East Palo Alto by computer and civil
rights leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gateway would provide technology training to 75,000
teachers, including every teacher in East Palo Alto, while Novell
would donate $20 million in software for nonprofit organizations
helping Hispanic organizations. Hewlett-Packard will invest $15
million in a new ''digital village'' initiative in three
underserved communities, including East Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm will commit $25 million to bridge the digital divide in
San Diego, where it is based.
</P>
<P>
   PowerUp, a partnership of America Online, Gateway and other
companies to bring technology to young people in schools and
community centers, pledged to expand from 19 to 250 sites
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said it would provide 100,000 accounts for use at PowerUp,
and the Waitt Family Foundation said it would donate 50,000 Gateway
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Department digital divide: http://www.digitaldivide.gov
</P>
<P>
   Plugged In computer center: http://www.pluggedin.org
</P>
<P>
   Palo Alto: http://www.city.palo-alto.ca.us
</P>
<P>
   East Palo Alto: http://www.ci.east-palo-alto.ca.us
</P>
<P>
   Navajo Nation: http://www.navajo.org/nnhomepg.html
</P>
</TEXT>
