<HEADLINE> Football Player Leaves Florida  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida sophomore John Capel, a member
of the Gators' football and track teams, withdrew from the
university.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Oswald, spokesman for Florida's track team, confirmed
Monday that Capel left the Gainesville school last week before the
Sea Ray Relays meet at Tennessee. But Oswald refused to give any
details concerning the departure.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Doug Brown told a Knoxville newspaper during the meet that
Capel, a 2000 Olympics, had left the team.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Capel nor Brown could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Capel, of Brooksville, Fla., likely will concentrate on
qualifying for a spot on the U.S. Olympic track team.
</P>
<P>
   Capel currently leads the nation's 200-meter qualifiers with his
19.87 second effort to win the NCAA outdoor title in June,
according to USA Track &AMP; Field. The U.S. Olympic Trials begin on
June 14 in Sacramento, Calif. The top three finishers qualify for a
spot on the Olympic squad.
</P>
<P>
   Capel was used mostly as a kick returner on the football team.
He also caught nine passes for 84 yards, but did not participate in
spring drills so he could concentrate on the track season.
</P>
<P>
   He had been expected to play a larger role on the football team
after the departures of wide receivers Travis Taylor and Darrell
Jackson, who left school early for the NFL.
</P>
</TEXT>
