<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gephardt Expected to Nix China Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt is
expected to announce this week he will vote against a bill granting
permanent normalized trade relations to China, Democratic officials
said Monday, dealing a blow to administration lobbying efforts on
the hotly contested measure.
</P>
<P>
   These officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Gephardt, D-Mo., had informed senior White House officials of his
decision, and would likely announce it on Wednesday in a speech in
his hometown of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton favors the measure, as do members of the Republican
leadership in the House and the two men in line to become the major
party presidential nominees, Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In opposing the legislation, Gephardt would side with the
majority of his own Democratic caucus, as well as virtually the
entire House Democratic leadership and the party's traditional
allies in organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   A close vote is expected on the legislation when the House votes
sometime next month.
</P>
<P>
   The White House played down Gephardt's decision, saying it had
been expected for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's important is that he's going to let Democrats in the
caucus vote on this up or down on the merits,'' said presidential
spokesman Jake Siewert, accompanying Clinton on a visit to New
Mexico. ''We think that given a chance to explain the merits of
this deal to Democratic caucus, that we'll secure enough support to
approve the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, Congress has reserved the right to make an
annual decision on whether to extend trading rights to the Chinese
that are currently extended to almost every other country. The
pending legislation would put an end to that practice in favor of a
permanent grant.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt is expected to argue the measure is not strong enough
to justify surrendering the potential for the United States to
influence China's polices on human rights, the environment and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that while Gephardt intends to announce his
opposition to the measure, he is not expected to join in a
full-fledged effort to defeat it, a campaign being led in the House
by the Democratic whip, Rep. David Bonior of Michigan. Rather, the
Missouri lawmaker likely will explain his position to fellow
Democrats, and continue to urge the members of the rank-and-file to
come to their own decision, this official added.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a politically perilous one for Gephardt and the
Democrats, who are waging a strenuous effort to win back the House
in the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is fighting the trade bill, fearing the
potential loss of jobs. Business groups, eager to open up an
enormous new market, are strongly for it. That sets up a
potentially dangerous vote for Democratic lawmakers from swing
districts, who might customarily rely on backing from the AFL-CIO
to win difficult re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gephardt's leadership, Democrats also have made a strong
effort to raise campaign donations from business leaders,
particularly the high tech industry, without diminishing their
traditional ties to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech, Gephardt emphasized support for several
items on the high tech industry's agenda, but sidestepped the issue
of trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand your concerns,'' he said late last month to a
business group. But he added that any legislation must provide
''the right incentives for China to move towards the rule of law,
to protect both personal and property rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on trade relations with China is expected to be one of
the most hardfought of the entire 106th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert recently announced a vote would be
held on the bill the week of May 22. That was widely seen as a
concession to Clinton and an enticement to wavering Democrats, who
had feared that the GOP leadership would maneuver to postpone the
roll call until closer to the fall elections, when the political
danger to Democrats could be greater.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Calif., a supporter of the
bill, recently predicted that as many as 70 or 80 Democrats would
wind up supporting the measure. Many of those votes will come from
within the New Democrat Coalition, a group of mostly younger
lawmakers who are attempting to push the party toward a new
position on economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Even support from 70 or so Democrats would fall short of what
Republicans once said they would need. Recently, however, some GOP
aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, have begun to suggest
that 70 or 80 Democratic votes will be enough to get the measure
passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2214 </TRAILER>
