<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanic Lawmakers Seek Explanation  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Hispanic state lawmakers, dissatisfied with
a recent apology by the state's health commissioner, sent letters
Monday demanding a better explanation of his remarks on Hispanic
communities' attitudes toward teen pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Health Commissioner William ''Reyn'' Archer apologized last week
after being quoted in newspapers as saying Texas has a high teen
pregnancy rate because the state's Hispanic population lacked the
belief ''that getting pregnant is a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Were these comments personal feelings, impressions of Hispanic
culture or a slip of the tongue?'' said one of the letters, signed
by Democratic Rep. Rene Oliveira, chairman of the 37-member Mexican
American Legislative Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Mario Gallegos Jr., chairman of the Senate
Hispanic Caucus, wrote in another letter on behalf of the caucus:
''Your remarks showed complete lack of understanding of our culture
and our values.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Charlie Gonzalez, D-San Antonio, and the National
Council of La Raza have called for Archer's resignation, but Gov.
George W. Bush, who approved Archer's 1997 appointment, has
rebuffed those demands.
</P>
<P>
   In his written apology, Archer said he deeply regretted creating
an ''erroneous impression about Hispanics and teen pregnancy. I
apologize for any harm that it may have caused.''
</P>
<P>
   Department of Health spokesman Doug McBride said Archer ''will
respond to the caucus concerning the questions raised by the
caucus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
