<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Procrastinators Mob Post Office  </HEADLINE>
By MELANIE CARROLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- As the midnight tax deadline loomed Monday
night, thousands of last-minute filers mobbed post offices around
the country to get their forms postmarked on time.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, umbrella-toting procrastinators crowded into
the city's main post office to face the inevitable. These
stressed-out latecomers didn't let the extra two days given to
taxpayers this year stop them from cutting it close.
</P>
<P>
   Qudsiya Assan, 26, of Brooklyn, couldn't finish her forms on
time, and said she ''just came for the extension.'' Finishing up a
letter to the Internal Revenue Service explaining why her form was
going to be late, her head started to hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ''I caught a headache coming in here today,'' Assan said at the
James A. Farley Post Office in midtown Manhattan. ''I pay enough
taxes already.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone at the block-long columned building on Eighth
Avenue was feeling the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Parker, 36, said he likes ''the party atmosphere'' of the
post office on tax day. ''I'm in a good mood,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a man dressed as Uncle Sam in silver pants and a top
hat was hoisted up on stilts, giving out chocolate coins to promote
his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just mailed my taxes,'' Parker said. ''I'm getting a
significant return. Then I got some pens and chocolate outside.''
He says the many promotional freebies that companies distribute at
the main post office on tax day keep taxpayers' spirits up.
</P>
<P>
   Because April 15 fell on a Saturday this year, most Americans
got two extra days to file their taxes. But people in
Massachusetts, Connecticut, Maine, New Hampshire, Rhode Island,
Vermont and most of New York outside of the New York City area have
another day -- until midnight Tuesday -- because of the Patriot's Day
holiday in Maine and Massachusetts. Many of the returns from the
region are handled by the IRS service center in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At the Terminal Annex post office in downtown Los Angeles, lines
of cars a block long snaked steadily past open-air booths set up to
collect tax returns in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the booths, postal workers wearing yellow slickers to
protect them against the day's steady rain, collected the envelopes
and sent the taxpayers on their way.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to see the lovely postal workers,'' was Maureen
Tabor's excuse for waiting until the last minute Monday night.
''And I guess I like procrastinating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles woman will procrastinate a bit longer, having
filed an extension form, not her return.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, so many people chose electronic filing that the
usual last-minute rush seemed calmer, one tax preparer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're less swamped than usual,'' said Dan Griffiths, district
manager for H&AMP;R Block's 11 offices in south central Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   But in Chicago, pen and paper ruled.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second year in a row that Isaiah Heard, 28, found
himself trying to beat the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't mind waiting to the last day. It's almost like
tradition now,'' he said at the downtown post office, which was
open until midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Heard said he had planned to file electronically before he was
informed of the additional charges. So, he spent Monday morning
completing the forms.
</P>
<P>
   Eric O'Quinn, another last-minute Chicago filer, said he waited
on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew I owed money,'' he explained. ''I figured it didn't
make sense to send it in earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2235 </TRAILER>
