<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, April 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Nixes Taiwan Destroyer Sale
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, backed by his senior advisers, decided
today against the sale of four Aegis destroyers to Taiwan, but approved a
smaller package including long-range radar designed to detect missile launches,
two senior U.S. officials said. Clinton acted on the recommendation of top
advisers who met earlier in the day at the White House. The Pentagon had
recommended that the administration put off Taiwan's request to buy new weapons,
including the destroyers, submarines and anti-submarine aircraft, in order to
avoid angering China, which views Taiwan as a rebellious province.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Expands Passengers' Privacy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court ruled today that police officers must
get travelers' consent or a court warrant before squeezing their luggage to see
if drugs might be inside. The 7-2 decision in a Texas case said a U.S. Border
Patrol agent who felt a bus passenger's bag violated the Constitution's Fourth
Amendment ban on unreasonable searches. The bag later was found to contain
drugs. The ruling expands public transit passengers' privacy rights, but the
National Association of Police Organizations said it was disappointed by the
ruling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IMF Protesters Disrupt Capital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Demonstrators disrupted the workday in much of the
nation's capital today, but they failed to shut down the two days of meetings of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. About 600 people were arrested
today, bringing the total to more than 1,300 since the protests began. The
protesters accused the bank and IMF of imposing crushing debts on poor nations,
destroying the environment and perpetrating a host of other ills. World Bank
spokeswoman Caroline Ansety said officials in the meetings felt ''bewilderment
and surprise at the degree of anger'' outside. She said the officials were
talking about ways to relieve poverty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Fate in the Hands of Court
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- On the 39th anniversary of the Bay of Pigs fiasco, Cuban
Americans in Miami stood watch at the home where Elian Gonzalez's relatives
waited for a key ruling in the custody fight. Protesters recalled the deadly
attempt on April 17, 1961, in which CIA-trained exiles failed to invade Cuba.
Their criticism was extended to the Clinton administration, which wants the
6-year-old Cuban boy returned to his Cuban father. The boy's Miami relatives say
he will have a better life here. Both sides were awaiting a ruling from the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. The government wants the court to lift
an order that bars Elian's removal from the United States and to order Elian's
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez to release the boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
P&AMP;G Osteoporosis Drug Approved
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. has received Food and Drug
Administration approval to market Actonel, its drug for prevention and treatment
of osteoporosis. Actonel faces some well-established competition in the
lucrative market. Merck &AMP; Co.'s Fosamax has been on the market five years and
had sales of $1.06 billion last year. And in September, the FDA approved Eli
Lilly &AMP; Co.'s Evista as an osteoporosis drug.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A rebound on Wall Street pushed Tokyo stocks moderately higher
Tuesday in early trading. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose
226.96 points to 19,235.60. At the close of the regular session, the Dow
industrials were up 276.74 to 10,582.51. The Nasdaq had its biggest one-day
point gain ever, rising 217.87 to 3,539.16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
State Dept. Laptop Missing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI is investigating the disappearance from the State
Department two months ago of a laptop computer that contained highly sensitive
information. A State official said the laptop was shared by several officials.
The Washington Post, quoting a person familiar with the incident, said the
missing computer contained ''code word'' information, a classification higher
than top secret. It also contained intelligence information and plans, the
person was quoted as saying.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Penguins Beat Capitals 4-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jiri Slegr's slap shot beat goaltender Olaf Kolzig with
4:32 remaining and the Pittsburgh Penguins, luring Washington into an unwanted
shootout, won 4-3 today night to seize a 3-0 Eastern Conference playoff lead.
Jan Hrdina scored twice as the seventh-seeded Penguins moved within a victory of
their second major playoff upset in two seasons. The Penguins eliminated
top-seeded New Jersey in the first round a year ago and now need one more
victory to oust the second-seeded Capitals, who failed to hold a 1-0 lead for
the second successive game. Game 4 will be Wednesday night in Washington.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
