<DOCNO> APW20000417.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Can't Persuade U.S. on Ships  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's failure to persuade the United
States to sell it four high-tech Aegis warships has set back the
island's hopes of bolstering its defenses in the face of mounting
threats by China.
</P>
<P>
   For years, analysts have said Taiwan's military -- with its
highly motivated troops and advanced U.S.-made weapons -- could
repel or at least give China a bloody nose if it ever makes good on
threats to attack this island. Taiwan and China split amid civil
war in 1949, and Beijing has warned it might use force to reunify
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, some analysts have begun doubting Taiwan's war
readiness and have raised questions about whether morale, loyalty
and training have slipped in recent years as this island changed
from a poor, authoritarian society to a prosperous, vibrant
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson Fu, director of the Strategic Studies Institute at the
Armed Forces University, which trains Taiwan's military leaders,
doesn't believe the military is facing a talent crisis and he
doubts there is an ideological conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Those who disagree on the independence issue still share a
common goal, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They both want to defend Taiwan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious signs the military is aware of the growing
urgency to attract new talent. A new slick ad being shown on TV and
at movie theaters encourages young, educated Taiwanese to put their
computer skills at work on board warships and jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
   But Damon Bristow, a researcher with Britain's Royal United
Services Institute for Defense Studies, doubts Taiwan's military
would have been able to find enough trained sailors to crew the
Aegis ships, equipped with Tomahawk cruise missiles of the kind the
U.S. Navy used in the Kosovo conflict last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Taiwanese have reached the saturation level when it comes
to the big things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, President Clinton decided Monday against the sale
of the destroyers. The Pentagon had recommended that the
administration put off Taiwan's request to buy new weapons in order
to avoid angering China.
</P>
<P>
   At a Taipei news conference Tuesday, Taiwanese military
spokesman Kung Fan-ding declined to discuss the requests for
weapons. But Kung said Taiwan urgently needs a better anti-missile
system.
</P>
<P>
   ''The military has always done its best to acquire any weapons
that would help build up its anti-missile defenses,'' Kung said.
</P>
<P>
   Bristow, who has spent the past six months in Taiwan researching
the military, said the Taiwanese should suspend purchases of
expensive weapons and focus on trimming their ranks and building a
professional armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taiwan's armed forces are flabby and unfit,'' Bristow said,
noting that the island's force of 400,000 troops is made up mostly
of unmotivated conscripts serving their two years of mandatory
service in the army.
</P>
<P>
   A war between China and Taiwan would be unlike ones they have
fought before. Like Taiwan's military, China's 2.5 million-member
People's Liberation Army has never fought a war over a body of
water as big as the 80-mile-wide Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   The last big battles the two have fought involved each other 51
years ago. China's guerrilla PLA troops won that conflict, forcing
the Nationalist government and military to retreat to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   While the military's top leadership still favors eventual
reunification with China and opposes independence, it's not clear
whether junior officers and the enlisted ranks agree.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of young people call themselves Taiwanese, not
Chinese, are interested in developing their own culture and oppose
reunification with China.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the soldiers aren't singing off the same song books
as their bosses,'' Bristow said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-17-00 2315 </TRAILER>
