<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index fell Tuesday
morning adding to Monday's big losses, despite a rebound on Wall
Street. The dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which was up some
300 points early in the session, fell 103.99 points, or 0.55
percent, to 18,904.65 at the end of the morning session. On Monday,
the average closed down a huge 1,426.04 points, or 6.98 percent
after a record drop Friday on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.41 yen in late morning trading, up 1.05
yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also above its late New York
level of 104.26 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index started higher as Tokyo
investors were reassured by a strong showing on Wall Street but
moved into negative territory as players locked in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the Nikkei average was technically weighed down by
active portfolio adjustments before next Monday's reshuffle of 30
index components.
</P>
<P>
   The Nihon Keizai newspaper, Japan's major financial daily and
the administrator of the index, has said it will replace some
old-line industrial stocks April 24 to better reflect market
trends.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose
276.74 points to 10,582.51 after a 617.78-point plunge on Friday.
The technology-rich Nasdaq composite soared 217.87 points to
3,589.16 at Monday's close after its 355.49-point slide on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Nikkei's decline, the broader Tokyo Stock Price
Index of all issues listed on the first section was up 33.11
points, or 2.14 percent, to 1,585.57. The TOPIX closed down 107.98
points, or 6.53 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa sought to calm
investors, saying early Tuesday that Japan's economic recovery
appears healthy enough that Monday's sharp plunge on the stock
market should have no impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the strength of Japan's recovery is quite strong, I'm
not that worried,'' Miyazawa told reporters, adding, however, that
he would be closely watching the U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's fall in the Nikkei was its fifth worst in both points
and percentage.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 99.08 yen, down from
99.51 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7200 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7050 percent. Its price
fell 0.14 point to 101.55.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
