<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Show Early Gains  </HEADLINE>
By DIRK BEVERIDGE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Shares rose across Asia early Tuesday in line
with Wall Street's gains, but the big Tokyo market soon turned
lower, raising concerns about the fragility of any recovery from
the global sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not out of the woods entirely,'' said Russell Jones,
chief Asia economist for the investment bank Lehman Brothers in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average was up by as much as 1.7
percent early Tuesday, after prices rose Monday on Wall Street and
signaled to some that the selling had run its course.
</P>
<P>
   But by late morning, the Nikkei was off by 103.99 points, or
almost 0.6 percent, at 18,904.65, adding to its losses of 7 percent
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The panicky mood that swept Asia a day earlier had eased after
prices increased later Monday in New York -- but traders were more
cautious than optimistic after seeing shares take such huge hits in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa sought to calm
investors, saying early Tuesday his nation's economic recovery
appears healthy enough that the sharp plunge on the stock market
should have no impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the strength of Japan's recovery is quite strong, I'm
not that worried,'' Miyazawa told reporters. But Miyazawa added he
would be closely watching U.S. shares.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, where the blue chips had fallen 8.6 percent on
Monday, they came back Tuesday with a quick gain of 3.6 percent.
The Hang Seng Index was up 537.11 points at 15,299.48 after about
15 minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong investors gathered around stock-quotation terminals in
local bank offices, anxiously watching the numbers flash.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, where the blue chips had fallen 8.6 percent on
Monday, they came back Tuesday with a quick gain of 3.6 percent.
The Hang Seng Index was up 537.11 points at 15,299.48 after about
15 minutes of trading.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, the Korea Composite Stock Price Index, or Kospi,
started Tuesday with a gain of more than 8 percent but dipped by
later in the morning to show an increase of just 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean shares were hit particularly hard Monday with a
loss of 11.6 percent as red ink splashed through Asia's exchanges,
to be followed later by substantial but slightly lesser losses in
major European markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the share price outlook -- at least for the short-term --
appeared brighter after Wall Street opened again on Monday and
finished with some sizable gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 276.74 points to 10,582.51
on Monday, following its slide of 617.78 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Nasdaq composite index, a major barometer of the
so-called ''new economy'' high-tech companies, gained 217.87 points
to 3,589.16 in Monday's dealings, after a plunge of 355.49 points
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In other Asian markets Tuesday, Australian shares were up 2.6
percent, Singaporean shares rose 2.7 percent and Taiwanese shares
were up 3.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
