<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-17 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Stabilize  </HEADLINE>
By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Heartened by better results on Wall Street Monday,
European stock markets clawed back much of the ground they had lost
earlier in the day following last week's dramatic plunge in U.S.
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Many European exchanges recovered from heavy losses suffered in
the first few hours of trading, as the Nasdaq Stock Market and New
York Stock Exchange staved off a repeat performance of Friday's
collapse and ended the day higher.
</P>
<P>
   Also emboldened by Wall Street's bounce, Asian markets opened
higher Tuesday, after taking sharp declines the day before in
response to U.S. losses last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the big Tokyo market soon turned lower in early trading
Tuesday, raising concerns about the fragility of any recovery from
the global sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, trading intensified later in the day, with the number
of purchase orders rising as investors noted the relative stability
on U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   The FTSE 100 index of leading British shares climbed back from a
4.3 percent drop to finish the day 3.0 percent lower at 5,994.60.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were seeing a bit of recovery at the close, on the back of
a steady opening on Wall Street,'' said Andrew Miller of the
London-based brokerage Greig Middleton.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was quite a rally in some of the technology stocks over
the day,'' he added, suggesting that the flight from high-tech
shares might be nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
   On Europe's second-biggest stock market in Frankfurt, Germany,
the Xetra DAX index of blue-chip shares bounced back from a 4.3
percent slump to end 0.4 percent down from Friday's close at
7,187.14 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris CAC 40 index did even better, closing just 0.1 percent
lower at 6,060.54 points.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Dow fell 617.78 points, or by 5.7 percent,
Friday, its biggest one-day point drop ever. The Nasdaq, home to
technology stocks whose popularity has evaporated, tumbled 355.49
Friday, or by 9.7 percent. The point drop was its worst ever.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, the markets bounced back, with the Nasdaq gaining
6.5 percent, its highest one-day rise. The Dow also rose 276.74 to
10,582.51.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said it was too soon to tell if Wall Street was
truly recovering from last week's plunge, which slashed nearly $2
trillion from the market's value.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly in Asia early Tuesday, analysts were unsure if the
stronger opening was a sign that prices were recovering from their
plunge on Monday or just pausing at the start of a new downturn.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, the region's largest market, the 225-issue Nikkei
Stock Average rose 248.34 points, or 1.3 percent, to reach
19,257.98 in early dealings. The Nikkei had fallen almost 7
percent, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, the Korea Composite Stock Price Index, or Kospi,
opened with a surge of more than 8 percent, wiping out much of
Monday's 11.6 percent decline, but prices soon eased to show a gain
of 6.7 percent on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa sought to calm
investors, saying early Tuesday his nation's economic recovery
appears healthy enough that Monday's sharp plunge should have no
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since the strength of Japan's recovery is quite strong, I'm
not that worried,'' Miyazawa told reporters. But Miyazawa added he
would be closely watching the U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Wall Street's showing Monday, stock markets in Eastern
Europe tumbled on average by as much as 6 percent, with shares in
telecommunications companies among those hit hardest.
</P>
<P>
   While most main European markets struggled upward but still
closed lower, Sweden offered a rare example of recovery into
positive territory. Shares in Stockholm closed up 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that investors' dumping of technology stocks
last week caused a much-needed correction in share prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''What this will do is sort the wheat from the chaff, but at a
faster rate than anyone would have thought. Investors have been
spooked by the speed of these falls,'' said Nigel Little of the
investment bank Nomura.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
